WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.440
[Amit Varma]: At the start of April 2000, I wrote an article in the Times of India that argued that we

00:00:09.440 --> 00:00:14.440
[Amit Varma]: were fighting two disasters. One, of course, was the immediate problem of COVID-19. The

00:00:14.440 --> 00:00:20.120
[Amit Varma]: other was the hidden problem of the dysfunctional Indian state. COVID-19 would eventually recede,

00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:24.560
[Amit Varma]: and indeed one hopes the worst is behind us now. But the Indian state remains, and the

00:00:24.560 --> 00:00:29.520
[Amit Varma]: damage it causes is normalized every day. Before COVID struck us, it was estimated that

00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:34.920
[Amit Varma]: around 3,000 children die every day in India of starvation. One in four Indian children

00:00:34.920 --> 00:00:39.280
[Amit Varma]: are malnourished. We would have to be blind not to see the poor all around us, often lacking

00:00:39.280 --> 00:00:44.480
[Amit Varma]: livelihood and homes, these 75 years after independence. If any of this had been caused

00:00:44.480 --> 00:00:49.120
[Amit Varma]: by a natural disaster, the world would rush to help. The UN would declare an emergency.

00:00:49.120 --> 00:00:53.460
[Amit Varma]: There would be headlines about it every day. But we've normalized, and it took the disaster

00:00:53.460 --> 00:00:59.280
[Amit Varma]: of COVID to reveal to many of us again the greater disaster of the flailing Indian state.

00:00:59.280 --> 00:01:04.600
[Amit Varma]: Now another potential disaster awaits us down the road. Climate change. We must do something

00:01:04.600 --> 00:01:09.480
[Amit Varma]: about it before it is too late and the cost is unbearable. But our dysfunctional state

00:01:09.480 --> 00:01:14.200
[Amit Varma]: stands in the way. A problem like climate change cannot be tackled by central planning

00:01:14.200 --> 00:01:19.520
[Amit Varma]: and rent-seeking bureaucracies. We need to fix these problems of the state first. Can

00:01:19.520 --> 00:01:23.760
[Unknown]: we do that?

00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:29.440
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:35.800
[Unknown]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:40.040
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen. My guests today are Akshay Jaitley and Ajay Shah. Akshay

00:01:40.040 --> 00:01:44.520
[Amit Varma]: is one of the founders of the law firm Trilegal, and he now lives in Paris, where he is more

00:01:44.520 --> 00:01:49.080
[Amit Varma]: or less retired from the law, but still working hard on problems he has deep experience in,

00:01:49.080 --> 00:01:53.560
[Amit Varma]: such as our energy sector. Ajay has been a guest on the show many times, and I know he's

00:01:53.560 --> 00:01:58.840
[Amit Varma]: the listener favorite for his incredibly lucid insights. A few months ago, Akshay and Ajay,

00:01:58.840 --> 00:02:03.520
[Amit Varma]: thinking together about climate change, released a superb paper named The Lowest Hanging Fruit

00:02:03.520 --> 00:02:06.760
[Amit Varma]: in the Coconut Tree â€“ India's Climate Transition through the Price System in the

00:02:06.760 --> 00:02:10.840
[Amit Varma]: Power Sector. I've linked it from the show notes. The paper describes how fighting climate

00:02:10.840 --> 00:02:16.800
[Amit Varma]: change and reducing carbon emissions is achievable, but only if we reform the power sector, get

00:02:16.800 --> 00:02:21.120
[Amit Varma]: the incentives right, and society and markets will act in ways that move us towards a cleaner

00:02:21.120 --> 00:02:25.720
[Amit Varma]: and safer world. How is this to be achieved? What are the problems we face today, and how

00:02:25.720 --> 00:02:30.080
[Amit Varma]: can we solve them? Akshay and Ajay joined me to chat about their paper and much more.

00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:34.240
[Amit Varma]: Now, Ajay has been a frequent guest, so we spent the first half of this episode exploring

00:02:34.240 --> 00:02:38.360
[Amit Varma]: Akshay's formative years, and from after the first break, around the 1 hour 55 minute

00:02:38.360 --> 00:02:43.040
[Amit Varma]: mark, we got down to talking about this great paper of theirs. I loved every minute of this

00:02:43.040 --> 00:02:48.200
[Amit Varma]: entire conversation, and Akshay and Ajay gave me a lot to think about. Before we get to

00:02:48.200 --> 00:02:52.480
[Amit Varma]: that though, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:02:52.480 --> 00:02:57.080
[Amit Varma]: All around us we hear about unicorns, and many of these unicorns create notional value

00:02:57.080 --> 00:03:01.960
[Amit Varma]: in the world of bits and bytes. But the sponsor of today's episode is a giant company that

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:07.600
[Amit Varma]: creates real value in the world of atoms. KNEST is an aluminium formwork company that

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:12.600
[Amit Varma]: was founded in 2014 and is today India's largest and the world's largest growing formwork

00:03:12.600 --> 00:03:16.680
[Amit Varma]: company. Now, what is formwork? It's a building technology that makes construction

00:03:16.680 --> 00:03:22.440
[Amit Varma]: more efficient, sustainable and scalable. Until recently, Indian real estate had to

00:03:22.440 --> 00:03:27.560
[Amit Varma]: outsource this tech to foreign companies at crazy prices. KNEST changed the game with

00:03:27.560 --> 00:03:31.860
[Amit Varma]: their state of the art automated unit and the largest design team in the industry that

00:03:31.860 --> 00:03:36.840
[Amit Varma]: uses virtual reality to make their customised aluminium products. They've had a massive

00:03:36.840 --> 00:03:41.320
[Amit Varma]: impact that is unseen in two ways. One, of course, they make the building they are used

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:46.880
[Amit Varma]: for sturdier and more reliable. Two, they've brought value to the entire industry and not

00:03:46.880 --> 00:03:51.880
[Amit Varma]: just the industry but also the environment as projects that use KNEST use less wood and

00:03:51.880 --> 00:03:56.800
[Amit Varma]: are friendlier to the natural world around them. KNEST shows that not only is sustainable

00:03:56.800 --> 00:04:01.880
[Amit Varma]: development possible in these urbanising times, but also that India can show the way in how

00:04:01.880 --> 00:04:07.120
[Amit Varma]: it's done. Their slogan goes, desh mein bana, desh ka apna. And companies like this are

00:04:07.120 --> 00:04:11.680
[Amit Varma]: the Atmanirbhar India I like. They're already multinational, by the way, building not just

00:04:11.680 --> 00:04:17.000
[Amit Varma]: for this country, but for the world. To know more about KNEST, check out knestalueform.com.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:21.720
[Amit Varma]: The link will be at the bottom of the show notes. Technology, design, innovation, they

00:04:21.720 --> 00:04:27.480
[Amit Varma]: all come together in KNEST. Ajay and Akshay, welcome to the scene and the

00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:33.920
[Amit Varma]: unseen. Thanks, Amit. Pleasure to be here. Always happy to be here. You know, as I announced

00:04:33.920 --> 00:04:37.960
[Amit Varma]: in my introduction, Ajay, you've been a frequent guest on the show, and we've kind of chatted

00:04:37.960 --> 00:04:42.320
[Amit Varma]: a lot. So I'd like to get to know Akshay a little better. And we can kind of chat about

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:47.040
[Amit Varma]: his life a little bit right now. But before that, a little bit of trivia for you, Ajay,

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:52.880
[Amit Varma]: that one of my listeners sort of trawled all the data in my show notes and figured out

00:04:52.880 --> 00:04:56.840
[Amit Varma]: that the book that I have linked to most often, you know, through the scene and the unseen

00:04:56.840 --> 00:05:01.600
[Amit Varma]: is in service of the Republic. So congratulations on that minor victory.

00:05:01.600 --> 00:05:09.320
[Guest 1]: Yeah, and I am 100% a victim of the insecure author syndrome. So it means the world to

00:05:09.320 --> 00:05:15.240
[Amit Varma]: me that people care about the book. And I also want to start with a story that

00:05:15.240 --> 00:05:19.600
[Amit Varma]: a friend of mine tweeted about. This is a gentleman named Narendra Shenoy, who was on

00:05:19.600 --> 00:05:25.080
[Amit Varma]: the show in episode 250, fantastic storyteller. So he told a story about how once when he

00:05:25.080 --> 00:05:30.720
[Amit Varma]: was a kid, he had to go to a fancy dress party. And this is like early 80s, 70s, whatever.

00:05:30.720 --> 00:05:35.320
[Amit Varma]: So everybody at that time, like half the people will dress up as Arab sheiks, because that's

00:05:35.320 --> 00:05:38.680
[Amit Varma]: the easiest to dress up as you take a bedsheet or whatever, and you make a hole and you put

00:05:38.680 --> 00:05:43.600
[Amit Varma]: it around you. And my friend decided he wants to do something different. And he was a bit

00:05:43.600 --> 00:05:48.500
[Amit Varma]: of a science geek at the time. So he took a disc condenser, and he decided to dress

00:05:48.500 --> 00:05:52.880
[Amit Varma]: up as a disc condenser. And he gave an image of it basically. And he said, Look, I already

00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:59.040
[Amit Varma]: had the spindly legs of a disc condenser. So he made the rest of the sort of costume

00:05:59.040 --> 00:06:04.200
[Amit Varma]: of what a disc condenser would look like. And then he went on a stage, and he sang,

00:06:04.200 --> 00:06:12.880
[Amit Varma]: I am a disc condenser. This condenser, which is and the reason I thought of you guys, the

00:06:12.880 --> 00:06:18.720
[Amit Varma]: reason I thought of this rather while reading your paper is full of discom, discom, discom.

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:24.880
[Amit Varma]: This story immediately came to mind, but kind of moving away from these trivialities. So

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:29.160
[Amit Varma]: Akshay, again, welcome again on the show. And tell me a bit about, you know, your life.

00:06:29.160 --> 00:06:31.200
[Amit Varma]: Where did you grow up? What was childhood like?

00:06:31.200 --> 00:06:35.600
[Guest 2]: Well, just just before that, I've been I really impressed with the amount of effort to come

00:06:35.600 --> 00:06:42.600
[Guest 2]: up with both in visual and an audio pun, really appeals to the cheap humor that I've sort

00:06:42.600 --> 00:06:48.600
[Guest 2]: of grown up with. Well, you know, I, I was actually born here in Bombay, but accident

00:06:48.600 --> 00:06:53.440
[Guest 2]: of fate, because my father at the time was the deputy commissioner of a small district

00:06:53.440 --> 00:06:57.960
[Guest 2]: frontier district called Punch. And this was in 1967, when there was something called the

00:06:57.960 --> 00:07:03.680
[Guest 2]: infiltration. And my grandparents lived, coincidentally, both sets of my grandparents lived here, my

00:07:03.680 --> 00:07:08.480
[Guest 2]: grandparents on one side, my grandmother on the other. And it was not the nearest hospital

00:07:08.480 --> 00:07:11.920
[Guest 2]: in which I could be born, but the one where there was the most support. So I was born

00:07:11.920 --> 00:07:17.240
[Guest 2]: here in Bombay. But because my father was in the in government and in the IAS in Kashmir

00:07:17.240 --> 00:07:23.720
[Guest 2]: Kader, which was unusual for non state officers at the time, I spent the first 10 years of

00:07:23.720 --> 00:07:28.160
[Guest 2]: my life in Kashmir. And in fact, when people say where do you grow up? I say Kashmir, although

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:34.280
[Guest 2]: it was only till the age of 10. But it's more home to me in intellectual, emotional in a

00:07:34.280 --> 00:07:39.320
[Guest 2]: variety of different ways than anywhere, anywhere else. So Punch was where I sort of had my

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:44.980
[Guest 2]: first year or two. Then we moved to Jammu as my father was deputy commissioner there.

00:07:44.980 --> 00:07:52.200
[Guest 2]: Then we moved to Ladakh. And I was in fact in Leh as a four-year-old during the 71 war.

00:07:52.200 --> 00:07:57.560
[Guest 2]: So in fact, my first distinct memories are from then when, which is being in a blacked

00:07:57.560 --> 00:08:03.760
[Guest 2]: out room with a Bukhari, generating heat, my mother heating water on the Bukhari, because

00:08:03.760 --> 00:08:08.280
[Guest 2]: there was no light, being put into a steel tub and having a bath in the living room.

00:08:08.280 --> 00:08:13.160
[Guest 2]: While my father was in Kargil, which was at that time, it was the same district as Ladakh,

00:08:13.160 --> 00:08:17.280
[Guest 2]: where he was there with, you know, as the, as the head of the civil administration of

00:08:17.280 --> 00:08:22.120
[Guest 2]: the district, he was there with the army on the frontier. So, so it was, you know, I think

00:08:22.120 --> 00:08:27.600
[Guest 2]: there'll be many other aspects of my upbringing that will be common to a lot of people. But

00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:32.640
[Guest 2]: I think, for me, at least the fact that I grew up in a place like Kashmir, I would like

00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:37.560
[Guest 2]: to think and I'm quite sure that it's, there are various aspects of who I am have been

00:08:37.560 --> 00:08:43.240
[Guest 2]: dictated by that for multiple reasons, and not just the physical landscape, but also

00:08:43.240 --> 00:08:49.160
[Guest 2]: the, you know, the unique history of the place, the unique religious breakdown of the state,

00:08:49.160 --> 00:08:53.880
[Guest 2]: etc. So all of those were really important. So I was there till the age of four. Then

00:08:53.880 --> 00:09:00.120
[Guest 2]: my father was, was sort of went on study leave to the UK, to Cambridge for a year. So lived

00:09:00.120 --> 00:09:06.400
[Guest 2]: abroad between the ages of five and six, at which point I picked up very, very small boys,

00:09:06.400 --> 00:09:11.720
[Guest 2]: irrational love for Liverpool Football Club, which remains with me till today, in a very

00:09:11.720 --> 00:09:14.120
[Guest 2]: strong sense. It's not just a passing fancy.

00:09:14.120 --> 00:09:15.120
[Guest 2]: Around which year was this?

00:09:15.120 --> 00:09:20.720
[Guest 2]: This was in 1973. So you're talking about Kevin Keegan, and John Toshack, and Ray Clemens.

00:09:20.720 --> 00:09:25.040
[Guest 2]: And basically, they won everything. So obviously, you want to support a team that wins, but

00:09:25.040 --> 00:09:30.920
[Guest 2]: also, they wore red, which was nice. And they came from Liverpool. And my father was a bit

00:09:30.920 --> 00:09:35.520
[Guest 2]: of a lefty at the time, socialist working class town. So they were all the ingredients

00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:40.160
[Guest 2]: for a father to tell a son, this is your team. And that was my team and still is. And I've,

00:09:40.160 --> 00:09:44.400
[Guest 2]: and it's the team of my nephew and my daughters, if they support anyone, they support Liverpool.

00:09:44.400 --> 00:09:48.800
[Guest 2]: So there's this funny, quirky thing. Then we came back to India, where we went to Kashmir.

00:09:48.800 --> 00:09:54.200
[Guest 2]: Funny thing here is that when we went to England, I didn't speak any English. I understood apparently,

00:09:54.200 --> 00:09:58.160
[Guest 2]: my parents would speak partly English, largely English to each other, because my mother's

00:09:58.160 --> 00:10:02.760
[Guest 2]: from Kerala, my father's from the north. So that was the common language between them.

00:10:02.760 --> 00:10:07.320
[Guest 2]: But I never spoke any English. And so I was put into school, my parents were worried wondering,

00:10:07.320 --> 00:10:12.000
[Guest 2]: you know, how's this chap going to manage things. And they asked the teachers after

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:15.600
[Guest 2]: a few days and said, no, he speaks perfectly fluent English. So apparently, I'd picked

00:10:15.600 --> 00:10:20.160
[Guest 2]: it all up, but never found the need to speak any English. But by the time I came back to

00:10:20.160 --> 00:10:25.400
[Guest 2]: India a year later, I didn't speak any Hindi. I'd forgotten most of my English and, and

00:10:25.400 --> 00:10:29.960
[Guest 2]: then my Hindi, sorry, and I had to pick it up again. And this was back in up in Kashmir

00:10:29.960 --> 00:10:35.240
[Guest 2]: again, where I went to a school called the Presentation Convent, which was a girl's school

00:10:35.240 --> 00:10:40.880
[Guest 2]: that accepted boys until class three, after which they were deemed to be too dangerous

00:10:40.880 --> 00:10:45.360
[Guest 2]: to be around girls at the time. So yeah, so that's, that's the first, you know, five,

00:10:45.360 --> 00:10:49.680
[Guest 2]: six years. Interesting thing there is I used to live on one side of the Jhelum and the

00:10:49.680 --> 00:10:54.600
[Guest 2]: school was on the other side. So I'm probably one of the few people you guys know who used

00:10:54.600 --> 00:10:59.840
[Guest 2]: to go to school by boat every day. I used to go to school by Shikara and the Shikarawala

00:10:59.840 --> 00:11:04.440
[Guest 2]: had a small paddle called the Chappu. So, you know, you need to, if you want to cross

00:11:04.440 --> 00:11:08.280
[Guest 2]: a river, you actually have to row upstream, and then you catch the current back down because

00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:12.880
[Guest 2]: otherwise you get carried down beyond the past, the point that you go to. So that little

00:11:12.880 --> 00:11:18.440
[Guest 2]: bit of river navigation, crossing the river every day, at the age of seven, walking to

00:11:18.440 --> 00:11:22.240
[Guest 2]: school on your own and crossing the river, that's what Kashmir was like. This was in

00:11:22.240 --> 00:11:25.240
[Guest 2]: Srinagar. That's what it was like in the in the mid 70s.

00:11:25.240 --> 00:11:28.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's, that's fascinating. And just speaking of Liverpool, I mean, one theory

00:11:28.920 --> 00:11:33.320
[Amit Varma]: I read about why people support the clubs they do, is that at a particular age, which

00:11:33.320 --> 00:11:36.960
[Amit Varma]: seems to correspond with whatever age you were, a team that's doing well, they end up

00:11:36.960 --> 00:11:40.360
[Amit Varma]: supporting that team. And then later in life, that team may not do well or whatever, but

00:11:40.360 --> 00:11:44.080
[Amit Varma]: they're lifelong supporters. But like good fortune for you that the Liverpool team has

00:11:44.080 --> 00:11:45.960
[Amit Varma]: been so exciting over the last few years.

00:11:45.960 --> 00:11:50.120
[Guest 2]: Yeah, I know it is. And I, you know, I used to hold it very strongly against the people

00:11:50.120 --> 00:11:54.720
[Guest 2]: who started supporting ManU in the early 90s when, you know, when it when things started

00:11:54.720 --> 00:11:58.720
[Guest 2]: coming on TV, but effectively, they were they're the same. They're the version of me from the

00:11:58.720 --> 00:12:03.480
[Guest 2]: 90s, with the technology that was available that I was at the same time. So I've sort

00:12:03.480 --> 00:12:08.880
[Guest 2]: of revisited that view. I still don't like Manchester United fans, but but not for that

00:12:08.880 --> 00:12:09.880
[Amit Varma]: reason.

00:12:09.880 --> 00:12:13.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. So you know, what he was saying about Kashmir and how you think of it as home reminded

00:12:13.080 --> 00:12:18.080
[Amit Varma]: me of a question that I, a chat I had with Amitabh Kumar on the show at the time we are

00:12:18.080 --> 00:12:23.120
[Amit Varma]: recording is not yet out, but it'll be out soon. And I'll read this bit out. And then

00:12:23.120 --> 00:12:29.240
[Amit Varma]: I'll come to my question from one of his books, where he wrote, in Raza's Adhagaon, the protest

00:12:29.240 --> 00:12:33.160
[Amit Varma]: against the nation is being made in the name of the village, while the fiercely well educated

00:12:33.160 --> 00:12:37.520
[Amit Varma]: Muslim students come to Gangauli to preach about partition and the necessity for the

00:12:37.520 --> 00:12:43.020
[Amit Varma]: creation of a new nation of Pakistan. The Muslim villagers are genuinely bewildered.

00:12:43.020 --> 00:12:47.080
[Amit Varma]: One of the villagers is a young man called Tandu, who has returned from battle fighting

00:12:47.080 --> 00:12:51.040
[Amit Varma]: for the British in the Second World War. He argues against the urban visitors in the name

00:12:51.040 --> 00:12:55.560
[Amit Varma]: of his village. And now these are his words. I'm a Muslim, but I love this village because

00:12:55.560 --> 00:13:00.320
[Amit Varma]: I myself am this village. I love this indigo warehouse, this tank and these mud lanes because

00:13:00.320 --> 00:13:05.040
[Amit Varma]: they are different forms of myself. On the battlefield, when death came very near, I

00:13:05.040 --> 00:13:10.360
[Amit Varma]: certainly remembered Allah. But instead of Mecca or Karbala, I remembered Gangauli, stop

00:13:10.360 --> 00:13:16.560
[Amit Varma]: quote, right. And, and what I asked Amitabh was what is your Gangauli? Because I wanted

00:13:16.560 --> 00:13:21.040
[Amit Varma]: to kind of get a sense of what his notion of home is, because in my own sense, I just

00:13:21.040 --> 00:13:26.920
[Amit Varma]: feel that it is very splintered. I no longer think of a place. I think there are disconnected

00:13:26.920 --> 00:13:31.360
[Amit Varma]: memories that are people who are no more, there are things which have scattered or are

00:13:31.360 --> 00:13:35.480
[Amit Varma]: not there anymore. And I found that interesting. And your answer, I guess, would therefore

00:13:35.480 --> 00:13:37.160
[Guest 2]: be Kashmir, right? That's for you.

00:13:37.160 --> 00:13:43.480
[Guest 2]: More specifically, I mean, it's, it's Kashmir broadly, and many different, you know, specific

00:13:43.480 --> 00:13:47.840
[Guest 2]: aspects, specific memories. I learned how to swim in the Dal Lake. I learned, I did

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:51.480
[Guest 2]: a bit of skiing very early on. And these are sort of things that my contemporaries later

00:13:51.480 --> 00:13:57.880
[Guest 2]: in life had not done. So maybe the fact that they'd not done them, reinforced the memories

00:13:57.880 --> 00:14:02.320
[Guest 2]: that I had of these things and made them more special, at least to myself. But, but the

00:14:02.320 --> 00:14:07.800
[Guest 2]: one image for me that really makes me, it's going to sound a bit cheesy, but I'm going

00:14:07.800 --> 00:14:12.600
[Guest 2]: to say it anyway, makes me feel that I'm home is when I see the curve of the Shankaracharya

00:14:12.600 --> 00:14:18.320
[Guest 2]: Hill, effectively going into the Dal Lake in the evening, there's a sense of, oh, gosh,

00:14:18.320 --> 00:14:23.640
[Guest 2]: this is so familiar. And I, you know, I've lived in many other places, Delhi, notably

00:14:23.640 --> 00:14:29.280
[Guest 2]: much more than I've lived in Srinagar. But there's no other visual that comes into mind

00:14:29.280 --> 00:14:33.780
[Guest 2]: associated with a place more than that. So, and then other things like, you know, going

00:14:33.780 --> 00:14:38.920
[Guest 2]: fishing for trout, going, going to Gulmarg on a weekend, people, you know, going to Pahalgam

00:14:38.920 --> 00:14:44.800
[Guest 2]: on a weekend, these are the sort of things, you know, we would do. So I completely associate

00:14:44.800 --> 00:14:49.400
[Guest 2]: with, you know, the feeling coming out of what you just read out. And yes, it is, it

00:14:49.400 --> 00:14:53.200
[Guest 2]: is, it is Srinagar, more than any other place in the world.

00:14:53.200 --> 00:14:57.040
[Amit Varma]: And Ajay, you know, you kind of zoned out because you were told we are going to talk

00:14:57.040 --> 00:15:00.000
[Amit Varma]: about Akshay for the first one hour. But this is a question we haven't actually discussed.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:03.800
[Amit Varma]: I'd like to ask you this also. What is home for you?

00:15:03.800 --> 00:15:10.880
[Guest 1]: I was just struck by the coincidence. I also attended three years at Mount Mary convent,

00:15:10.880 --> 00:15:15.300
[Guest 1]: because from class one to three boys were not so dangerous. Yeah, so I think for me

00:15:15.300 --> 00:15:16.920
[Amit Varma]: home is Bandra.

00:15:16.920 --> 00:15:23.360
[Amit Varma]: Home is Bandra for you. Lovely. So getting back to Akshay now after that brief Ajay break.

00:15:23.360 --> 00:15:25.240
[Amit Varma]: So what after Kashmir, what happens?

00:15:25.240 --> 00:15:29.840
[Guest 2]: Well, I switched schools, went to a boy school for a couple of years. And at the age of 10,

00:15:29.840 --> 00:15:34.640
[Guest 2]: we moved to Delhi. I think your father was in government as well. So yeah, Kashmir Kada,

00:15:34.640 --> 00:15:40.080
[Guest 2]: you get moved to the centre for a few years. And it was a big, big change in my life. I

00:15:40.080 --> 00:15:46.520
[Guest 2]: mean, I went from being very much the small town boy. It shouldn't, in some ways, maybe

00:15:46.520 --> 00:15:51.160
[Guest 2]: it shouldn't have been such a change. But I certainly felt it because, you know, my

00:15:51.160 --> 00:15:56.520
[Guest 2]: parents had a social life in a community in Delhi, which was very natural to them, both

00:15:56.520 --> 00:16:01.560
[Guest 2]: in government, they both went to Delhi University. So the sort of range of friends that they

00:16:01.560 --> 00:16:08.120
[Guest 2]: had, and their kids, were people who I'd sort of met occasionally on holidays, and they

00:16:08.120 --> 00:16:12.760
[Guest 2]: were uncles and aunties who were very close, who I loved and continue to, you know, be

00:16:12.760 --> 00:16:17.840
[Guest 2]: in touch with. But I wasn't part of their world at all. And their world was, you know,

00:16:17.840 --> 00:16:22.200
[Guest 2]: the kinds of holidays they'd been on the fact that they were either members of the Delhi

00:16:22.200 --> 00:16:26.960
[Guest 2]: Gymkhana or the Delhi Golf Club. And we were not, my father refused to go to an interview

00:16:26.960 --> 00:16:30.880
[Guest 2]: at the Delhi Gymkhana Club, because he had to wear a suit. And he said, if they're not

00:16:30.880 --> 00:16:36.520
[Guest 2]: going to take me in the way that I am, then I don't want to be a member. Many years later,

00:16:36.520 --> 00:16:40.720
[Guest 2]: maybe 30 years later, he wore a suit and went to an interview and became a member. But,

00:16:40.720 --> 00:16:45.840
[Guest 2]: you know, that's another story. But so I moved to Delhi, it was a big change. And also school

00:16:45.840 --> 00:16:53.120
[Guest 2]: was tougher, the level of education was slightly higher in Delhi, in primarily in maths and

00:16:53.120 --> 00:16:57.800
[Guest 2]: in Hindi. So, you know, suddenly there was concepts in maths had not done before. I was

00:16:57.800 --> 00:17:02.080
[Guest 2]: a good student in Kashmir had come, you know, second, third, fourth in class, incidentally

00:17:02.080 --> 00:17:08.640
[Guest 2]: has to come second for nine exams in a row, three years, I came second to a girl called

00:17:08.640 --> 00:17:14.120
[Guest 2]: Valley Call. And I wonder where she is and what she's doing. But I, there's no way that

00:17:14.120 --> 00:17:19.120
[Guest 2]: I could sort of beat her. And in realization of that, I took the foot off the pedal and

00:17:19.120 --> 00:17:24.000
[Guest 2]: I said, now third, fourth, which I like a person and I kind of think so. And that's,

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:30.000
[Guest 2]: it's something academically something I've sort of always kept as a working principle,

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:33.840
[Guest 2]: which is do well enough, do well enough not to get into trouble, do well enough to get

00:17:33.840 --> 00:17:39.160
[Guest 2]: into the right college, do well enough to not be not disgrace yourself. But otherwise,

00:17:39.160 --> 00:17:43.880
[Guest 2]: there's no real point in coming, you know, first or second, just do well enough. So anyway,

00:17:43.880 --> 00:17:48.200
[Guest 2]: we came to Delhi, that's what I did. Then it was, you know, very much the life of living

00:17:48.200 --> 00:17:53.440
[Guest 2]: in a government colony, playing cricket with boys, being told, you go out of the house,

00:17:53.440 --> 00:17:58.040
[Guest 2]: come back when it's dark. That was a level of parental oversight that used to exist for

00:17:58.040 --> 00:18:03.760
[Guest 2]: most of us, I think then. My house in Bharti Nagar in Delhi shared a wall with the community

00:18:03.760 --> 00:18:08.160
[Guest 2]: center, which was called the club. There's where there was a badminton, badminton court,

00:18:08.160 --> 00:18:12.680
[Guest 2]: the table tennis table. So it was literally you jump the wall and play sports as playing

00:18:12.680 --> 00:18:17.780
[Guest 2]: sport all the time. Never was exceptionally good at anything, but again, did well enough

00:18:17.780 --> 00:18:23.720
[Guest 2]: to be included in better players' sports. There was also a tennis court behind, learned

00:18:23.720 --> 00:18:27.960
[Guest 2]: how to, you know, taught, we all taught ourselves how to play tennis. And it was, you know,

00:18:27.960 --> 00:18:34.640
[Guest 2]: going around to Khan market and other India gate on our bikes. Interestingly, if you know

00:18:34.640 --> 00:18:38.680
[Guest 2]: where the India Habitat Center is in Delhi, which it used to be barracks, it used to be

00:18:38.680 --> 00:18:42.880
[Guest 2]: some BSF barracks, which were abandoned. And we used to play in those barracks. We then

00:18:42.880 --> 00:18:48.920
[Guest 2]: played in the building site that became the Nehru Stadium before the 1982 Asian Games,

00:18:48.920 --> 00:18:53.320
[Guest 2]: where they had these massive mounds of mud that had been dug out. And we would run up

00:18:53.320 --> 00:18:56.440
[Guest 2]: and down them and roll down them and do that sort of thing. So it was just that sort of

00:18:56.440 --> 00:19:01.680
[Guest 2]: carefree while not doing particularly well in school, but again, well enough. I think

00:19:01.680 --> 00:19:07.480
[Guest 2]: the other, the next thing that's worth that, that was a big marker in my life was 1984.

00:19:07.480 --> 00:19:13.320
[Guest 2]: And 1984 was, you know, again, looking back, it was much more of a defining moment than

00:19:13.320 --> 00:19:17.920
[Guest 2]: it felt. I think there'll be a lot of people for whom this COVID period will be like that,

00:19:17.920 --> 00:19:22.560
[Guest 2]: although it's much longer and arguably more traumatic, even though that was short and

00:19:22.560 --> 00:19:29.700
[Guest 2]: sharp and horrible. But my parents were very, very liberal and in a variety of meanings

00:19:29.700 --> 00:19:35.160
[Guest 2]: of that word. And they also were perhaps, you know, arguably slightly foolhardy. So

00:19:35.160 --> 00:19:43.640
[Guest 2]: I was 17 when this happened, but they included me, took me along to on peace marches on,

00:19:43.640 --> 00:19:48.680
[Guest 2]: I was very, very involved with a bunch of other contemporaries in relief efforts, went

00:19:48.680 --> 00:19:54.520
[Guest 2]: to Gurdwaras, where people were taking shelter to write hundreds of affidavits, where, you

00:19:54.520 --> 00:19:57.920
[Guest 2]: know, the various names that we all heard at the time, who were then members of the

00:19:57.920 --> 00:20:04.640
[Guest 2]: ruling party, who their names as being leaders of mobs wrote affidavits, organized clothing,

00:20:04.640 --> 00:20:08.120
[Guest 2]: did all of that sort of thing. But so it's this is not to say that I did some great thing,

00:20:08.120 --> 00:20:13.760
[Guest 2]: but that that was a massively big waking up moment. And my parents allowed us to just

00:20:13.760 --> 00:20:17.960
[Guest 2]: go and do this and not always supervised by them. You'd go off with other people who are

00:20:17.960 --> 00:20:21.800
[Guest 2]: from university and made lots of friends. I was in class 12, the beginning of class

00:20:21.800 --> 00:20:26.400
[Guest 2]: 12, made lots of friends who were in college, who came from similar backgrounds, but we

00:20:26.400 --> 00:20:31.480
[Guest 2]: became friends over this much more than we had growing up because there's something,

00:20:31.480 --> 00:20:35.960
[Guest 2]: something important had happened. And we felt that whatever little we were doing was somewhat

00:20:35.960 --> 00:20:43.520
[Guest 2]: important at the time. So it was 84 for me was a very, very big deal. There was a very

00:20:43.520 --> 00:20:49.560
[Guest 2]: ugly echo of that a few years later in 1988. And this is something that was sort of largely

00:20:49.560 --> 00:20:56.840
[Guest 2]: forgotten in the annals of the time. But taking a cue from what had happened in 84, in 88,

00:20:56.840 --> 00:21:02.120
[Guest 2]: there was a university and a gurdwara in Bidar in Karnataka that was attacked. And one of

00:21:02.120 --> 00:21:06.000
[Guest 2]: my closest friends from school got killed in that in that riot. There were, you know,

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:11.160
[Guest 2]: three or four, five, six boys were killed. And that whole thing that that whole period

00:21:11.160 --> 00:21:15.160
[Guest 2]: and the series of events that happened, and how they happened, the fact that there was

00:21:15.160 --> 00:21:21.520
[Guest 2]: complicit, there was the government was sort of complicit in it. All of that has an effect

00:21:21.520 --> 00:21:26.880
[Guest 2]: on what you think about politics, what you think about the narrative that a certain party

00:21:26.880 --> 00:21:32.820
[Guest 2]: gives about what its role is. So I've never been able to sort of move on from a certain

00:21:32.820 --> 00:21:39.960
[Guest 2]: aspect of what 1984 was. So that was the, there's another big, big thing in my life.

00:21:39.960 --> 00:21:45.160
[Amit Varma]: It's kind of interesting that there are these moments, which form this kind of landscape,

00:21:45.160 --> 00:21:50.720
[Amit Varma]: like when I talk to my guests of similar age or older than me, about these periods of time

00:21:50.720 --> 00:21:54.000
[Amit Varma]: where we might have lived through together, they'll mention a time. And I'll straight

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:58.120
[Amit Varma]: away remember where was I when this happened. Like I remember being told about the 84 riots,

00:21:58.120 --> 00:22:02.240
[Amit Varma]: for example, I was in a car with my parents from Delhi to Chandigarh, or vice versa, I

00:22:02.240 --> 00:22:05.440
[Amit Varma]: don't remember in which direction they were going. And then my dad said, this horrible

00:22:05.440 --> 00:22:09.240
[Amit Varma]: thing is happening. And people have been taken out of buses. And, you know, husbands are

00:22:09.240 --> 00:22:13.360
[Amit Varma]: being killed in front of wives and all of this and all these stories were kind of coming.

00:22:13.360 --> 00:22:17.760
[Amit Varma]: So it's just an odd feeling where someone tells you about something and you know, you

00:22:17.760 --> 00:22:24.120
[Amit Varma]: realize I was like, I had another guest on the show where we realized that in 1989, at

00:22:24.120 --> 00:22:27.640
[Amit Varma]: exactly the same time, we were at mood and ego together, though, obviously completely

00:22:27.640 --> 00:22:32.220
[Amit Varma]: different and whatever 89 or 91 or whatever it was. So that's interesting. So many things

00:22:32.220 --> 00:22:38.640
[Amit Varma]: to double click on. And one of them, of course, is that if there was a chapter on in a book

00:22:38.640 --> 00:22:44.200
[Amit Varma]: about you, one chapter heading could be the importance of valley call, because what you

00:22:44.200 --> 00:22:48.440
[Amit Varma]: said there is very interesting that because she was coming first all the time, you just

00:22:48.440 --> 00:22:52.200
[Amit Varma]: said, screw it, I'm just going to chill and I'm going to do my thing. What if you had

00:22:52.200 --> 00:22:57.760
[Amit Varma]: been coming first all the time? Like would it have then driven you to go to a different

00:22:57.760 --> 00:23:03.440
[Amit Varma]: lens and made you a different person to just retain your position? I mean, which is I mean,

00:23:03.440 --> 00:23:07.520
[Amit Varma]: you were kind of quipping when you said that, you know, there's not necessarily a causal

00:23:07.520 --> 00:23:13.640
[Amit Varma]: relation. But it's interesting how we are shaped by all these sort of little things

00:23:13.640 --> 00:23:15.440
[Amit Varma]: that happened to us.

00:23:15.440 --> 00:23:20.840
[Guest 2]: You don't know how much I believe in that. It's there are some of the most sort of seminal

00:23:20.840 --> 00:23:27.120
[Guest 2]: moments of decisions that I've taken, or parts that my life has taken have been on

00:23:27.120 --> 00:23:32.000
[Guest 2]: utter randomness. I mean, utter randomness. I'll tell you one thing that happened much,

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:38.000
[Guest 2]: much later, which was, you know, I studied law in England, and I was going to come back

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:41.960
[Guest 2]: and join a senior council like everybody did at the time. There were no such things as

00:23:41.960 --> 00:23:47.480
[Guest 2]: law firms really in India of any significance. And my mother happened to be visiting and

00:23:47.480 --> 00:23:52.200
[Guest 2]: she came and said, you know, why don't you think of doing a little bit of work here in

00:23:52.200 --> 00:23:56.160
[Guest 2]: England for a few months before you come back, not knowing at all what the job market was

00:23:56.160 --> 00:24:00.600
[Guest 2]: like or anything. But I remember in university in Oxford, there was a something called the

00:24:00.600 --> 00:24:03.720
[Guest 2]: eighths week brochure. The eighths week is when Oxford and Cambridge, there are lots

00:24:03.720 --> 00:24:08.360
[Guest 2]: of rowing races basically. And in the brochure, there was this ad from this firm called Asha

00:24:08.360 --> 00:24:14.240
[Guest 2]: St. Maurice Crisp, which had on one side, this picture of a guy in a boat and said,

00:24:14.240 --> 00:24:19.760
[Guest 2]: Olympic rower, it was Johnny Searle of the Redgrave and Searle combination. And on the

00:24:19.760 --> 00:24:25.280
[Guest 2]: other side, trainee solicitor, and it had him in a, wearing a suit on a desk in an office.

00:24:25.280 --> 00:24:33.640
[Guest 2]: And it said offices in XYZ and Delhi. This was, so we're talking about 1995. And in that,

00:24:33.640 --> 00:24:37.560
[Guest 2]: that moment, I remembered that that brochure and I said, okay, let me give these guys a

00:24:37.560 --> 00:24:40.960
[Guest 2]: call. They had something in India. So let me call them. So I called directory inquiry,

00:24:40.960 --> 00:24:45.120
[Guest 2]: literally, I called directory inquiry. And I said, you know, you have the number for

00:24:45.120 --> 00:24:48.560
[Guest 2]: Asha St. Maurice Crisp, they're called Asha St. now and great people, I'm still in touch

00:24:48.560 --> 00:24:53.280
[Guest 2]: with them. And they said, here it is, which should we connect you and they connected me.

00:24:53.280 --> 00:24:58.160
[Guest 2]: So I ran through to the switchboard. And I said, can I speak to someone who has something

00:24:58.160 --> 00:25:02.360
[Guest 2]: to do with India? And they looked at it, waited for a second, and they rang it through to

00:25:02.360 --> 00:25:08.680
[Guest 2]: an extension, which rang to a secretary because the person who's extension it was wasn't there.

00:25:08.680 --> 00:25:13.560
[Guest 2]: So I repeated my question. And she said, Oh, this is so and so he's in Delhi, here's a

00:25:13.560 --> 00:25:18.760
[Guest 2]: fax number for him. And I was sitting in my boxer shorts and a pair of and a t shirt in

00:25:18.760 --> 00:25:23.280
[Guest 2]: a friend's house in London, I had no access to a fax machine or anything of the sort.

00:25:23.280 --> 00:25:29.640
[Guest 2]: So I took the number down and I said, okay, you know, dead end. Forgot about it. An hour

00:25:29.640 --> 00:25:33.880
[Guest 2]: later, the phone rings, a phone rings, I pick it up. And this in the guy said, this is so

00:25:33.880 --> 00:25:38.440
[Guest 2]: and so I believe you called my number. And I had this complete sort of, you know, twilight

00:25:38.440 --> 00:25:43.640
[Guest 2]: zone moment. How is this guy called me because caller ID was almost unheard of, they happened

00:25:43.640 --> 00:25:47.880
[Guest 2]: to have got it shortly before this happened. I didn't know how he called me, but I gathered

00:25:47.880 --> 00:25:52.140
[Guest 2]: my wits. And I told him who I was. And it turned out that we had some similarities in

00:25:52.140 --> 00:25:56.200
[Guest 2]: terms of what we'd studied and what we'd done in the past. He said, sounds interesting.

00:25:56.200 --> 00:26:00.660
[Guest 2]: Send me your CV. So I sent him my CV. And he called me for an interview, I was called

00:26:00.660 --> 00:26:04.800
[Guest 2]: for another couple of interviews, and they gave me a job. And that's how I became a corporate

00:26:04.800 --> 00:26:10.480
[Guest 2]: lawyer. And that's how and I never ever have appeared in court, even for one day. So what

00:26:10.480 --> 00:26:17.380
[Guest 2]: randomness is there is that your mother hints something to you, you call directory inquiry,

00:26:17.380 --> 00:26:22.240
[Guest 2]: this whole series of things happen, caller ID is a thing. And you become a corporate

00:26:22.240 --> 00:26:29.000
[Guest 2]: lawyer. I mean, so that valley call randomness is more speculative, because I was a kid and

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:34.960
[Guest 2]: God knows, I probably would have been, you know, more boring than I might have turned

00:26:34.960 --> 00:26:40.640
[Guest 2]: out to be. But I'm secretly happy I did not come first, because I don't know whether that

00:26:40.640 --> 00:26:44.360
[Guest 2]: that would have been the right signal for me that you know, this is something I probably

00:26:44.360 --> 00:26:49.840
[Guest 2]: would have crashed and burned in trying to achieve high academic glory later on, better

00:26:49.840 --> 00:26:54.580
[Guest 2]: to have sort of learnt this at age seven or eight, and moved on from there. But the randomness

00:26:54.580 --> 00:26:58.420
[Guest 2]: point like 100%. Yeah, I mean, that's, that's another chapter

00:26:58.420 --> 00:27:02.800
[Amit Varma]: title right there, the importance of caller ID. So just going back to those childhood

00:27:02.800 --> 00:27:07.360
[Amit Varma]: years in Delhi, tell me also about, like, on the one hand, this is a familiar social

00:27:07.360 --> 00:27:11.760
[Amit Varma]: circle. These are all your parents, friends there at home, you've met all the kids, you're

00:27:11.760 --> 00:27:16.280
[Amit Varma]: going over the world to play sports, natural habitat. But on the other hand, what kind

00:27:16.280 --> 00:27:19.640
[Amit Varma]: of sets you apart from all the other kids is that you were in Kashmir, you've gone to

00:27:19.640 --> 00:27:25.160
[Amit Varma]: school on a boat, you've probably had quieter moments than they did. So all of you had quieter

00:27:25.160 --> 00:27:29.040
[Amit Varma]: moments and kids today, because smartphones and all that you had a different layer to

00:27:29.040 --> 00:27:35.240
[Amit Varma]: your personality, in a sense. Do you, you know, when you look back now, how important

00:27:35.240 --> 00:27:39.280
[Amit Varma]: do you think was that layer? Did you notice it at that time? Did it kind of set you apart?

00:27:39.280 --> 00:27:43.680
[Amit Varma]: Because when you are in just one homogenous world, you can kind of take everything for

00:27:43.680 --> 00:27:47.320
[Amit Varma]: granted and that can constrain you in the way that you look at the world. But you also

00:27:47.320 --> 00:27:50.440
[Amit Varma]: had this other sort of layer behind that.

00:27:50.440 --> 00:27:55.640
[Guest 2]: Well, you know, at the time, it wasn't easy. Actually, I felt there was a degree to which

00:27:55.640 --> 00:28:02.400
[Guest 2]: I felt left out. I wasn't necessarily invited to all the parties that these guys were, but

00:28:02.400 --> 00:28:06.960
[Guest 2]: I had my colony friends, even though I had my time was, FOMO was a thing even then, right?

00:28:06.960 --> 00:28:12.780
[Guest 2]: So I felt a bit of FOMO, especially because my parents were going to these people's homes,

00:28:12.780 --> 00:28:16.520
[Guest 2]: but I wasn't in the in crowd. A lot of them also went to boarding school. So, you know,

00:28:16.520 --> 00:28:20.120
[Guest 2]: when you are in boarding school, when you come back from the holidays, you hang out

00:28:20.120 --> 00:28:26.040
[Guest 2]: with your boarding school guys. Also, one other thing was that, you know, you've spoken

00:28:26.040 --> 00:28:30.800
[Guest 2]: very often to other people and it's obviously very true about privilege and we were all

00:28:30.800 --> 00:28:35.880
[Guest 2]: terribly privileged, but there was no money. Privilege did not come with money, didn't

00:28:35.880 --> 00:28:41.100
[Guest 2]: come with any disposable income to do anything, but other people in that social circle possibly

00:28:41.100 --> 00:28:44.440
[Guest 2]: had it. So there were things that they were doing that I couldn't do. I just couldn't

00:28:44.440 --> 00:28:49.260
[Guest 2]: do. I didn't miss it in any fundamental sense, but it was there every now and then I'd think

00:28:49.260 --> 00:28:58.080
[Guest 2]: about it. But the flip side of that is that by the time I went to college, I was 18, I

00:28:58.080 --> 00:29:05.800
[Guest 2]: happened to live in college and I was in the hostel and almost all my closest new friends

00:29:05.800 --> 00:29:12.340
[Guest 2]: from college were not from this background. There were some who, there are a few who were,

00:29:12.340 --> 00:29:16.720
[Guest 2]: but I was friends with people who traditionally would be in the hostel of a college in Delhi

00:29:16.720 --> 00:29:22.240
[Guest 2]: University. So people who'd come from UP and Bihar and Andhra and other parts in the

00:29:22.240 --> 00:29:27.400
[Guest 2]: Northeast and other parts of the country. So if I had been accepted more and if I had

00:29:27.400 --> 00:29:34.080
[Guest 2]: been part of the social circle that I would, quote unquote, naturally have fallen into,

00:29:34.080 --> 00:29:40.520
[Guest 2]: I would not have had this completely other, you know, side to my exposure, which made

00:29:40.520 --> 00:29:45.520
[Guest 2]: me much, much more deeply aware about other parts of the country, what people were thinking,

00:29:45.520 --> 00:29:50.240
[Guest 2]: what was important, what was going on. I mean, if you do history in St. Stephen's College

00:29:50.240 --> 00:29:54.520
[Guest 2]: in the 80s, you are going to do the civil services. And why do you do the civil services?

00:29:54.520 --> 00:30:00.600
[Guest 2]: There's a whole cultural and social and economic reason behind that, which was not part of

00:30:00.600 --> 00:30:05.560
[Guest 2]: my socialization at all. My father went into the civil service to do good for the country,

00:30:05.560 --> 00:30:10.360
[Guest 2]: but he could afford to do that in some ways because he came from, you know, relative privilege

00:30:10.360 --> 00:30:15.680
[Guest 2]: and he went to good education, all the rest of it. But lots of my close friends didn't

00:30:15.680 --> 00:30:20.760
[Guest 2]: have that sort of background. And it made me, you know, I can't say that it was, I became,

00:30:20.760 --> 00:30:24.720
[Guest 2]: you know, a completely different person, but it gave me an insight into things I would

00:30:24.720 --> 00:30:30.640
[Guest 2]: not have had. So in the longer term, I'm certainly grateful for that. But that layer, I think,

00:30:30.640 --> 00:30:35.600
[Guest 2]: that you were talking about, that you started your question with, it was there. It was there.

00:30:35.600 --> 00:30:40.680
[Guest 2]: This is a small townness to you, which doesn't completely go away. It doesn't, it doesn't

00:30:40.680 --> 00:30:46.920
[Guest 2]: perhaps can manifest itself in small town thinking, but it just, it is another window

00:30:46.920 --> 00:30:51.240
[Guest 2]: that has opened up that other people haven't, just haven't experienced.

00:30:51.240 --> 00:30:56.160
[Amit Varma]: And another source for other layers, which other people would not have, were in a sense,

00:30:56.160 --> 00:31:00.040
[Amit Varma]: what you said about your parents being liberals in different ways, you know, having their

00:31:00.040 --> 00:31:03.200
[Amit Varma]: own set of concerns, like on the one hand, you're, you know, they're in government. So

00:31:03.200 --> 00:31:07.320
[Amit Varma]: there is that aspect of it. But on the other hand, they're also liberal, you get involved

00:31:07.320 --> 00:31:13.200
[Amit Varma]: in 1984, because of all of that happens. So tell me a little bit about how you are building

00:31:13.200 --> 00:31:17.560
[Amit Varma]: your frameworks of looking at the world. Because I guess one direction to go in is you go in

00:31:17.560 --> 00:31:21.740
[Amit Varma]: the same direction as your parents. The other direction to go in is that hey, kids are rebels,

00:31:21.740 --> 00:31:26.560
[Amit Varma]: you go in some other direction. It also kind of matters what your peers around you are

00:31:26.560 --> 00:31:32.900
[Amit Varma]: doing or reading like I remember when, I mean, my dad was also in the IAS. But I didn't really

00:31:32.900 --> 00:31:39.440
[Amit Varma]: have any sort of coherent framework of looking at the world till I was well into adulthood.

00:31:39.440 --> 00:31:44.520
[Amit Varma]: You know, not in college, because those are pre-internet days, you're not getting so much

00:31:44.520 --> 00:31:48.960
[Amit Varma]: knowledge and information enough to be able to form those frameworks. My peers around

00:31:48.960 --> 00:31:53.120
[Amit Varma]: me in Ferguson College in Pune didn't really we were just chilling, living our lives, having

00:31:53.120 --> 00:31:57.240
[Amit Varma]: vague notions about everything. I remember for a week I carried around Das Capital in

00:31:57.240 --> 00:32:01.920
[Amit Varma]: my rucksack when I was 17. Because I thought, hey, it's a cool thing to do, right? And till

00:32:01.920 --> 00:32:09.440
[Amit Varma]: I actually read it much later. So what was that sort of, how was that process of formulating

00:32:09.440 --> 00:32:15.880
[Amit Varma]: a way of looking at the world? Like, was your journey also something from a certain kind

00:32:15.880 --> 00:32:20.840
[Amit Varma]: of vagueness into, you know, getting sharpened a little bit more as time goes by? Were there

00:32:20.840 --> 00:32:26.400
[Amit Varma]: inheritances in a sense, or received wisdoms that you had to cast aside? Or did you early

00:32:26.400 --> 00:32:30.040
[Guest 2]: on find a groove that you could fit into? I liked what you just said, you know, received

00:32:30.040 --> 00:32:36.520
[Guest 2]: wisdoms to cast aside. It wasn't to cast them aside, but to reframe them in a way that was

00:32:36.520 --> 00:32:44.520
[Guest 2]: relevant to the person I became later on. So, my sister and I, we were never told that

00:32:44.520 --> 00:32:48.680
[Guest 2]: this is what you should do for a career at all, very, very far from it. But there was

00:32:48.680 --> 00:32:54.100
[Guest 2]: a very strong sense that you can't be doing things only for yourself, that there needs

00:32:54.100 --> 00:33:02.160
[Guest 2]: to be some part of public service in a vague sense. That's one. Secondly, there was this

00:33:02.160 --> 00:33:10.320
[Guest 2]: said and unsaid both implication that you can't have a non-intellectual life. Again,

00:33:10.320 --> 00:33:17.320
[Guest 2]: I have no criticism of this now, but you can't become a manager in a hotel, because that's

00:33:17.320 --> 00:33:20.480
[Guest 2]: not an intellectual life. Now, you can be a manager in a hotel and have a perfectly

00:33:20.480 --> 00:33:25.440
[Guest 2]: intellectual life, but it was very much that your intellectual life must be wrapped into

00:33:25.440 --> 00:33:31.760
[Guest 2]: what you do as your work, as whatever your primary work is. And do whatever you want,

00:33:31.760 --> 00:33:39.440
[Guest 2]: but work as hard as you can and enjoy it. And don't do something you don't enjoy. So,

00:33:39.440 --> 00:33:43.920
[Guest 2]: these are actually very difficult standards. Even though they are vague, it's easiest in

00:33:43.920 --> 00:33:50.000
[Guest 2]: some ways when someone says, go and join the IAS. So, you were then left with these ideas

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:55.800
[Guest 2]: and the pressure of finding a career that works for yourself or various parts of life,

00:33:55.800 --> 00:34:01.120
[Guest 2]: not just a career that work for you, that somehow build these things in because of the

00:34:01.120 --> 00:34:09.520
[Guest 2]: pressure of them. And at the same time, you're not being someone you are not. So, I think

00:34:09.520 --> 00:34:14.520
[Guest 2]: that's a process that continues till today actually. I don't think that it's, I'm still

00:34:14.520 --> 00:34:21.040
[Guest 2]: continuing to, as you said, shed some of those things, but I don't think in some of those

00:34:21.040 --> 00:34:26.880
[Guest 2]: basic values, I don't think have changed. I still enjoy, it goes up and down. Sometimes

00:34:26.880 --> 00:34:33.160
[Guest 2]: I just want to watch football, but I want an intellectual life. I want the work that

00:34:33.160 --> 00:34:38.640
[Guest 2]: I do to have some significance beyond just for me and my family. Those things remain

00:34:38.640 --> 00:34:44.240
[Guest 2]: and those things I still encourage other people to think about as well because they are fulfilling.

00:34:44.240 --> 00:34:48.720
[Guest 2]: And they can be fulfilling irrespective of what else, what the actual content of your

00:34:48.720 --> 00:34:54.760
[Guest 2]: work is. So, yeah, that's how that whole thing played out. But one big difference between

00:34:54.760 --> 00:35:03.480
[Guest 2]: my parents and me is that I don't have the view towards money that they had. It was very

00:35:03.480 --> 00:35:07.640
[Guest 2]: much like money and business is not such a good thing. And I, on the other hand, do not

00:35:07.640 --> 00:35:13.440
[Guest 2]: believe that at all, as you will have seen from the paper that we wrote. And we can obviously

00:35:13.440 --> 00:35:20.840
[Guest 2]: talk about that later. But I think that properly done, it's a really positive force. And that

00:35:20.840 --> 00:35:26.640
[Guest 2]: I worked in corporate law for most of the last 25 odd years. So I was helping people

00:35:26.640 --> 00:35:32.720
[Guest 2]: make money and making a little bit myself at the same time. So that's one big difference.

00:35:32.720 --> 00:35:39.560
[Guest 2]: But there are other things that you do that you hope has have that broader impact that

00:35:39.560 --> 00:35:45.200
[Amit Varma]: I believe that work should have. I agree entirely that I keep saying that the

00:35:45.200 --> 00:35:48.800
[Amit Varma]: best kind of social work is actually making a profit honestly, because the only way to

00:35:48.800 --> 00:35:55.960
[Amit Varma]: make a profit is to make someone better off. I was struck by what you said about kind of

00:35:55.960 --> 00:36:01.960
[Amit Varma]: finding yourself or trying to figure out who you were and all of that. And that again brings

00:36:01.960 --> 00:36:07.800
[Amit Varma]: me to that nebulous notion of the self, like when we are young, especially when we are

00:36:07.800 --> 00:36:13.040
[Amit Varma]: young, all our lives, but when we are young, especially, we are too often, you know, dealing

00:36:13.040 --> 00:36:18.080
[Amit Varma]: with the anxiety of what other people think of us or what they expect of us. And we start

00:36:18.080 --> 00:36:22.200
[Amit Varma]: shaping ourselves in those modes, like you spoke about the pressure that you had to had

00:36:22.200 --> 00:36:26.480
[Amit Varma]: an intellectual life, but at the same time, whatever career or calling you took had to

00:36:26.480 --> 00:36:30.760
[Amit Varma]: be authentic to that intellectual life, and they had to kind of go together. So one to

00:36:30.760 --> 00:36:37.400
[Amit Varma]: what extent is, you know, did you feel those anxieties and, you know, given to those pressures,

00:36:37.400 --> 00:36:42.240
[Amit Varma]: whatever they were, and to just a general question throughout the sweep of your life,

00:36:42.240 --> 00:36:47.440
[Amit Varma]: that how, you know, how difficult has it been for you to eventually get comfortable in your

00:36:47.440 --> 00:36:52.280
[Amit Varma]: own skin, you know, eventually to be able to kind of sit back and say that, okay, this

00:36:52.280 --> 00:36:55.880
[Amit Varma]: is who I am, these are the things I like doing, like, yes, intellectual life, but I want to

00:36:55.880 --> 00:37:01.400
[Amit Varma]: watch football also, or whatever. What's that kind of process been like, because, you know,

00:37:01.400 --> 00:37:05.480
[Amit Varma]: just looking at myself, and many of the guests I've spoken to, it's not smooth at all, you

00:37:05.480 --> 00:37:11.040
[Amit Varma]: kind of go through life with this kind of inertia, where you're rarely except in some

00:37:11.040 --> 00:37:16.600
[Amit Varma]: moments really making movement, either in terms of understanding yourself or doing things.

00:37:16.600 --> 00:37:19.040
[Amit Varma]: And it's just a process that can take a long time.

00:37:19.040 --> 00:37:24.520
[Guest 2]: No, it's ongoing. It's not at no point have I felt, okay, this is the perfect mean. And

00:37:24.520 --> 00:37:29.000
[Guest 2]: there are many other pressures in life beyond just work that that, you know, one has to

00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:33.240
[Guest 2]: do. It's not, I've never thought of it as anxiety. I've never been, it's not something

00:37:33.240 --> 00:37:38.040
[Guest 2]: I've been anxious about. But I'd be lying if I said that I didn't worry about what other

00:37:38.040 --> 00:37:42.960
[Guest 2]: people thought, I wish I could say I really don't care. I, but even that is a process

00:37:42.960 --> 00:37:47.720
[Guest 2]: I care much less now. And which is one of the reasons why I'm possibly able to say some

00:37:47.720 --> 00:37:54.240
[Guest 2]: of the things that I'm saying now than I would have 20 years ago. So I think it's a question

00:37:54.240 --> 00:38:00.080
[Guest 2]: of how confident you are, and how confident you are, for me is a function of what is it

00:38:00.080 --> 00:38:04.200
[Guest 2]: that you've done in the body of your life. And if you've ended up doing something which

00:38:04.200 --> 00:38:08.320
[Guest 2]: you think, okay, this is a bit worthwhile, then you can be a little more flamboyant and

00:38:08.320 --> 00:38:15.000
[Guest 2]: cavalier with the rest of it, I find. So that's, that process is ongoing.

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:19.240
[Amit Varma]: And what were the kind of books you read while growing up? I mean, I know you played a lot

00:38:19.240 --> 00:38:23.640
[Amit Varma]: of sports, jumping over walls itself seems like a sport to me, to actually jump over

00:38:23.640 --> 00:38:28.200
[Amit Varma]: a wall and then have the energy to do something else is not something I can imagine in myself.

00:38:28.200 --> 00:38:31.360
[Amit Varma]: But what were the kind of books that you were reading? Who were the people who influenced

00:38:31.360 --> 00:38:35.840
[Amit Varma]: you? Do you remember any early heroes at that time? And even sporting heroes are fine, but

00:38:35.840 --> 00:38:41.360
[Amit Varma]: who were your kind of heroes? And especially, did you have a notion of yourself in the sense

00:38:41.360 --> 00:38:45.800
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, when I am an adult, I want to be like this person, this is like the ideal

00:38:45.800 --> 00:38:47.000
[Guest 2]: kind of person to be like?

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:52.520
[Guest 2]: No, that I don't think I had with any one person. But my sporting hero growing up was

00:38:52.520 --> 00:38:57.960
[Guest 2]: Sunil Gavaskar. It was and I met him once in 1975, in a bookshop in Pune. And that was

00:38:57.960 --> 00:39:03.880
[Guest 2]: a high point in my life. But you know, it's very difficult to say what books shaped me

00:39:03.880 --> 00:39:08.120
[Guest 2]: because I read enormously. I mean, apart from sport, the only other thing you had to do

00:39:08.120 --> 00:39:13.280
[Guest 2]: was reading. My parents only, actually, my father and I sneaked out and bought a television

00:39:13.280 --> 00:39:18.520
[Guest 2]: in 1987 for the 1987 World Cup. Before that, there was no TV at home, we would go to my

00:39:18.520 --> 00:39:22.360
[Guest 2]: grandmother's house to watch bits of you know, highlights of sports and things like that.

00:39:22.360 --> 00:39:28.240
[Guest 2]: They were, my parents were against television. It wasn't just, that was a conscious decision.

00:39:28.240 --> 00:39:33.760
[Guest 2]: But so books were where it was and they were, the house was wall to wall with books. We

00:39:33.760 --> 00:39:39.920
[Guest 2]: used to, in my early, in my, you know, before I turned 10, Narnia was very, very big, the

00:39:39.920 --> 00:39:47.560
[Guest 2]: whole C.S. Lewis pantheon. I probably read Charlie and the Chocolate Factory 35 times

00:39:47.560 --> 00:39:53.640
[Guest 2]: in my life. I absolutely adore that book. It was, it was just warm and nice and wonderful.

00:39:53.640 --> 00:39:59.040
[Guest 2]: Later on, you know, then one of the things that we did when we came to Delhi is became

00:39:59.040 --> 00:40:04.440
[Guest 2]: members of the B.C. Roy Children's Library at ITO. So, you know, so we would actually,

00:40:04.440 --> 00:40:09.400
[Guest 2]: me and my cousin Nandika who lived with us at the time, we used to get onto a DTC bus

00:40:09.400 --> 00:40:14.240
[Guest 2]: from Bharti Nagar, go to ITO, go to B.C. Roy Library, borrow books. And that could be anything,

00:40:14.240 --> 00:40:18.480
[Guest 2]: you know, it could all sorts of different types of stuff. I read my first Alastair Maclean

00:40:18.480 --> 00:40:25.800
[Guest 2]: from there. I read all sorts of children's books, so maybe till the age of 14, 13, 14.

00:40:25.800 --> 00:40:29.960
[Guest 2]: But then there was a rapid switch where our parents sort of handed us a read this, read

00:40:29.960 --> 00:40:35.640
[Guest 2]: this, read this. And those could include, you know, Steinbeck. Steinbeck was a big influence

00:40:35.640 --> 00:40:41.040
[Guest 2]: in terms, I love the lyricism of his writing, where you can make the sound of running water

00:40:41.040 --> 00:40:46.040
[Guest 2]: sound like the most amazing thing on earth. So, mice and men and grapes of wrath and all

00:40:46.040 --> 00:40:51.720
[Guest 2]: of those. And then we then we started reading the existentialists relatively early. So,

00:40:51.720 --> 00:40:57.760
[Guest 2]: Gide and Camus and all of this. And there were a sufficient number of friends whose

00:40:57.760 --> 00:41:02.640
[Guest 2]: parents also were handing them the same book. So, we would quietly have that discussion

00:41:02.640 --> 00:41:05.880
[Guest 2]: amongst us, not talking to other people, because they would say, what is this rubbish, you're

00:41:05.880 --> 00:41:10.160
[Guest 2]: trying to be a sood. That word has gone out of favor. Now nobody calls anyone a sood anymore.

00:41:10.160 --> 00:41:12.400
[Guest 2]: Yeah, in fact, I'm hearing it after 20 years, I think.

00:41:12.400 --> 00:41:16.600
[Guest 2]: There you are. So, you know, maybe it's a good thing that sood is not a bad thing. But

00:41:16.600 --> 00:41:23.520
[Guest 2]: it was. So, you'd hide a bit of your intellectualism, because you would think that you're trying

00:41:23.520 --> 00:41:28.800
[Guest 2]: to be better than them. And James Baldwin, I loved as well. I mean, Another Country is

00:41:28.800 --> 00:41:32.840
[Guest 2]: one of my favorite books from the time. So, there was just, there was a lot. Also, there

00:41:32.840 --> 00:41:36.880
[Guest 2]: was and nobody, I haven't heard anyone else admit this, but I've not listened to all your

00:41:36.880 --> 00:41:47.240
[Guest 2]: shows. But also to, there was this whole range of slightly raunchy thrillers, where the pages

00:41:47.240 --> 00:41:51.880
[Guest 2]: where the raunchy bits were always a little more dog-eared than the other pages. And,

00:41:51.880 --> 00:41:56.880
[Guest 2]: you know, so those were, those were also there at home, and they were also out in the bookshelf.

00:41:56.880 --> 00:42:01.480
[Guest 2]: And, you know, we would read those. So, huge variety.

00:42:01.480 --> 00:42:06.200
[Amit Varma]: And you were, of course, the one dog-earing them. You know, before we move on beyond this

00:42:06.200 --> 00:42:11.560
[Amit Varma]: phase to studying and law and all of that, tell me a bit about how different was Delhi

00:42:11.560 --> 00:42:12.560
[Amit Varma]: in those days?

00:42:12.560 --> 00:42:22.600
[Guest 2]: Oh, you know, this, I'm telling you this, I said this in 1996 or 7, when I went to Lahore

00:42:22.600 --> 00:42:28.680
[Guest 2]: for the first time, that Lahore felt like Delhi 20 years ago, at that time. So, Delhi

00:42:28.680 --> 00:42:37.560
[Guest 2]: in the late 70s was, you know, this idyllic vision of lying out in a garden after a nice

00:42:37.560 --> 00:42:44.280
[Guest 2]: meat curry and rice lunch on a rug with the sun having a nap. That is one of my images

00:42:44.280 --> 00:42:50.200
[Guest 2]: of Delhi at that time, where the sky was blue, where birds were chirping. As I said, we used

00:42:50.200 --> 00:42:56.120
[Guest 2]: to go around everywhere by cycle and by bus, and there was no, nobody had a car or a driver

00:42:56.120 --> 00:43:01.040
[Guest 2]: to take you anywhere. So, obviously, that restricted the, you know, where you went.

00:43:01.040 --> 00:43:05.600
[Guest 2]: But we'd go on Sunday mornings, for example, to Sapru House to watch movies. Sapru House

00:43:05.600 --> 00:43:09.520
[Guest 2]: had children's movies on a Sunday morning, which were either free or cheap, I don't remember.

00:43:09.520 --> 00:43:13.320
[Guest 2]: And a whole bunch of us boys would get in and go there and watch a movie. North by Northwest,

00:43:13.320 --> 00:43:17.320
[Guest 2]: I remember watching there, being absolutely terrified as a 12-year-old because I'd been

00:43:17.320 --> 00:43:22.080
[Guest 2]: gone with some 15-year-olds. We'd also go, you'd go and, you know, wander around the

00:43:22.080 --> 00:43:26.960
[Guest 2]: ramparts of Purana Qila, walking again, walking or cycling. So, it was, there was a sense

00:43:26.960 --> 00:43:33.520
[Guest 2]: of, in a small space, utter freedom. So, the radius of where we did all of this stuff must

00:43:33.520 --> 00:43:38.840
[Guest 2]: have been five kilometers, but there was utter freedom in that five kilometers. And in fact,

00:43:38.840 --> 00:43:43.040
[Guest 2]: you know, as you know, I moved to Paris a year and a half ago, and one of the reasons

00:43:43.040 --> 00:43:47.680
[Guest 2]: to move was because I wanted to give my daughters that independence that I felt growing up,

00:43:47.680 --> 00:43:51.440
[Guest 2]: that they, it's very difficult to give any child in Delhi, much less girls, and I have

00:43:51.440 --> 00:43:57.040
[Guest 2]: four of them. So, so that's what Delhi, that's, that's sort of my image of Delhi at the time

00:43:57.040 --> 00:44:03.040
[Guest 2]: is just sunny winters is, you know, is my sort of idyllic image of Delhi then.

00:44:03.040 --> 00:44:06.920
[Amit Varma]: And my next question actually has something to do with both growing up and parenthood.

00:44:06.920 --> 00:44:10.360
[Amit Varma]: Like one of the recent guests on my show, I recorded with him a couple of days back,

00:44:10.360 --> 00:44:14.800
[Amit Varma]: I have no idea if his episode will release before or after yours, was the guitarist Warren

00:44:14.800 --> 00:44:20.320
[Amit Varma]: Mendonza, Blackstrat Blues. And one of his albums is called The Last Analog Generation.

00:44:20.320 --> 00:44:24.880
[Amit Varma]: And the reason he titled his album that way, was that he said, look, he just had a daughter.

00:44:24.880 --> 00:44:28.440
[Amit Varma]: And he said that, I realized that I am from the last analog generation, that the way my

00:44:28.440 --> 00:44:32.480
[Amit Varma]: daughter grows up will be so fundamentally different from mine. And that difference will

00:44:32.480 --> 00:44:38.520
[Amit Varma]: be much starker than between any two generations. And I just think that, you know, when I, you

00:44:38.520 --> 00:44:41.880
[Amit Varma]: know, you and I would have grown up, even though there's some difference, we, you know,

00:44:41.880 --> 00:44:45.760
[Amit Varma]: I'm in my late 40s, we would have grown up in pretty much the same kind of way. You're

00:44:45.760 --> 00:44:49.520
[Amit Varma]: going outdoors a lot, you're meeting friends, when you're bored, you either read a book

00:44:49.520 --> 00:44:53.560
[Amit Varma]: or you go out or whatever, or you look into space, which is perfectly respectable and

00:44:53.560 --> 00:44:58.600
[Amit Varma]: whatever. While today, kids are just surrounded by sensory influences. They're always on their

00:44:58.600 --> 00:45:03.220
[Amit Varma]: smartphones. You know, Jonathan Haidt once made this great point that's stuck with me,

00:45:03.220 --> 00:45:07.680
[Amit Varma]: so I keep mentioning it on the show. So it's become a bit of a cliche that people today,

00:45:07.680 --> 00:45:11.920
[Amit Varma]: even though they have all the wealth of knowledge available to them through human history, everybody

00:45:11.920 --> 00:45:16.980
[Amit Varma]: is actually consuming something that was produced in the last three days. Right? So you go from

00:45:16.980 --> 00:45:22.640
[Amit Varma]: immediate experience to immediate experience. There is no tear off, in a sense, there is

00:45:22.640 --> 00:45:28.560
[Amit Varma]: no reflection, no sitting back, you know, and in future, you may not be playing along

00:45:28.560 --> 00:45:32.760
[Amit Varma]: the ramparts of the Red Fort, in real life, but in the metaverse, you know, it's just

00:45:32.760 --> 00:45:36.920
[Amit Varma]: so, you know, as someone who's a father of four kids, and as someone who himself has

00:45:36.920 --> 00:45:40.680
[Amit Varma]: grown up the way that you did with relative freedom, and you said you wanted to be out

00:45:40.680 --> 00:45:45.320
[Amit Varma]: of here for that reason, what are sort of your thoughts on this? Like, obviously, there

00:45:45.320 --> 00:45:49.920
[Amit Varma]: are differences between how people will grow up when they're 30 years apart and so on.

00:45:49.920 --> 00:45:54.320
[Amit Varma]: But this seems to me to be really fundamental. What are your kind of thoughts from what you've

00:45:54.320 --> 00:45:55.320
[Amit Varma]: seen and experienced?

00:45:55.320 --> 00:46:00.800
[Guest 2]: I have two sets of thoughts. I think one is that there's no doubt that more and more life

00:46:00.800 --> 00:46:08.880
[Guest 2]: is going to be online. I'm just wondering, I'm wondering whether there's a bit, the worm

00:46:08.880 --> 00:46:15.640
[Guest 2]: is turning slightly, though, because when I look at my kids, they're not, they look

00:46:15.640 --> 00:46:20.040
[Guest 2]: at Instagram, and they've got their phones and all of that. But they're also doing other

00:46:20.040 --> 00:46:24.320
[Guest 2]: things. And they're not doing it just because, you know, of parental supervision, there's

00:46:24.320 --> 00:46:28.720
[Guest 2]: only so much you can do. And, but they even their friends, they might, you know, one of

00:46:28.720 --> 00:46:34.240
[Guest 2]: my daughters, the other weekend said, I'm going out, where are you going? I'm going

00:46:34.240 --> 00:46:38.480
[Guest 2]: to an exhibition, I'm going to a museum with a friend for an exhibition. I think it's also

00:46:38.480 --> 00:46:44.000
[Guest 2]: the context if you if you make these other experiences, cultural experiences easy to

00:46:44.000 --> 00:46:49.800
[Guest 2]: access. And if there's a culture within which they are valued, then kids will pick it up.

00:46:49.800 --> 00:46:54.120
[Guest 2]: And we force our kids sometimes on every weekend, we'll either go to a park, or we'll go to

00:46:54.120 --> 00:46:58.960
[Guest 2]: a museum or a dance performance or something or the other. And there'll always be a bit

00:46:58.960 --> 00:47:05.080
[Guest 2]: of mourning before you go. And there'll always be enjoyment once you've gone. And you can

00:47:05.080 --> 00:47:10.520
[Guest 2]: only hope that that will get picked up. And then they'll realize that these real experiences

00:47:10.520 --> 00:47:15.840
[Guest 2]: in the physical world interacting with human beings and the art that they produce or the

00:47:15.840 --> 00:47:21.800
[Guest 2]: various different kinds has a value that you don't get. And things like Instagram, my kids

00:47:21.800 --> 00:47:28.160
[Guest 2]: don't post on it anymore. They look and they use it as messaging. So, the consumption of

00:47:28.160 --> 00:47:32.520
[Guest 2]: content, you're saying in the last three days, I think there was a period, there's a high

00:47:32.520 --> 00:47:36.200
[Guest 2]: watermark of that. And I'm no expert on the digital world. So, I don't know whether that's

00:47:36.200 --> 00:47:40.520
[Guest 2]: still there or it's passed. But at least in for my kids, it seems to have passed a little

00:47:40.520 --> 00:47:45.680
[Guest 2]: bit. Because they are getting maybe it's because of what they study in school, then you have

00:47:45.680 --> 00:47:49.060
[Guest 2]: a question and you say, okay, let's go back and look at the Great Northern War or whatever

00:47:49.060 --> 00:47:54.800
[Guest 2]: it might be. And they will read the article. One of my daughters wrote a paper recently

00:47:54.800 --> 00:48:00.800
[Guest 2]: on the crown. And to say, you know, was it, you know, was it right for it not to for them

00:48:00.800 --> 00:48:05.360
[Guest 2]: to put out a disclaimer saying that there are this fictionalization over here. And in

00:48:05.360 --> 00:48:10.040
[Guest 2]: doing so, she had to go back and look at the history and did a bit of reading around it.

00:48:10.040 --> 00:48:16.200
[Guest 2]: And that's something that I think kids need a bit of guidance. And therefore, I'm not

00:48:16.200 --> 00:48:20.680
[Guest 2]: one of those people who let them do what they want. But there's that instinct and that spark

00:48:20.680 --> 00:48:26.880
[Guest 2]: is there. So, I can't comment on whether there's a massive change going on or whether we've

00:48:26.880 --> 00:48:31.120
[Guest 2]: reached the peak or not. But at least in my own limited experience, there's a bit of a

00:48:31.120 --> 00:48:35.920
[Guest 2]: change there. But life is there's lots of life that's online, which this was an option

00:48:35.920 --> 00:48:36.920
[Amit Varma]: for us.

00:48:36.920 --> 00:48:41.280
[Amit Varma]: And that leads me to the thought that is there one kind of scarcity in India, which doesn't

00:48:41.280 --> 00:48:45.640
[Amit Varma]: get talked about so much like when you said that, you know, your daughter's reputed museum

00:48:45.640 --> 00:48:49.760
[Amit Varma]: with a friend and all of that and you can do that in Paris, you have those rich cultural

00:48:49.760 --> 00:48:55.840
[Amit Varma]: experiences in the Western world, all around you. In India, do those rich cultural experiences

00:48:55.840 --> 00:49:00.680
[Amit Varma]: really exist? Like I think about the things that I would do in Bombay, for example, you

00:49:00.680 --> 00:49:05.280
[Amit Varma]: know, and actually, I'm probably being unfair by saying that because I in any case, you

00:49:05.280 --> 00:49:08.320
[Amit Varma]: know, I'm not a theater going person, for example, I'm sure there's a scene at Prithvi

00:49:08.320 --> 00:49:14.360
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. But in general, in India, certainly outside the big cities, is it then

00:49:14.360 --> 00:49:18.480
[Amit Varma]: something that never gets talked about that those kinds of cultural experiences are actually

00:49:18.480 --> 00:49:24.600
[Amit Varma]: lacking. So if kids are bored, if you're sitting in, say, Kanpur, or, you know, wherever any

00:49:24.600 --> 00:49:28.600
[Amit Varma]: small town anywhere, what do you do with your time? You know, you don't have those wholesome

00:49:28.600 --> 00:49:32.640
[Amit Varma]: experiences. So you go online, and you do whatever and that becomes a thing.

00:49:32.640 --> 00:49:38.440
[Guest 2]: No, and I don't think that's necessarily just a problem with India. I think it's a problem

00:49:38.440 --> 00:49:44.600
[Guest 2]: with any society. And France is the opposite of that, which doesn't value the cultural

00:49:44.600 --> 00:49:48.960
[Guest 2]: experience on a day to day basis. I mean, I've been going to France for many, many years.

00:49:48.960 --> 00:49:53.720
[Guest 2]: But it's only after living there that you realize how much of it is part of the fabric

00:49:53.720 --> 00:49:59.400
[Guest 2]: of day to day life. It's not, you would not be surprised to have a chat with the cab driver

00:49:59.400 --> 00:50:03.520
[Guest 2]: and him tell you what exhibition he was going to that he was some other thing that he was

00:50:03.520 --> 00:50:08.040
[Guest 2]: looking forward to, or listening to classical music while taking you from point A to point

00:50:08.040 --> 00:50:14.600
[Guest 2]: B. And every small town, the social compact is such that it is expected that one of the

00:50:14.600 --> 00:50:20.200
[Guest 2]: things that your tax euros are going to do is provide you access to culture. So if you

00:50:20.200 --> 00:50:23.800
[Guest 2]: I don't know if you picked up but during COVID, one of the biggest constituencies and there's

00:50:23.800 --> 00:50:28.240
[Guest 2]: a very large number of people involved in the sector that was hit very badly was the

00:50:28.240 --> 00:50:34.920
[Guest 2]: entire area of culture. And there was a lot of public support for people who were in the

00:50:34.920 --> 00:50:38.440
[Guest 2]: world of culture saying, look, these are the people who we depend on. So if you go to a

00:50:38.440 --> 00:50:43.080
[Guest 2]: museum, and you get a guide at the museum, somebody who's part of the museum staff, the

00:50:43.080 --> 00:50:48.000
[Guest 2]: chances that they the way to a PhD in art are reasonably high. So the society and I

00:50:48.000 --> 00:50:52.360
[Guest 2]: think this is probably true of some of the older cultures in Europe, certainly in non

00:50:52.360 --> 00:50:58.280
[Guest 2]: English speaking places, that this is valued, and money is put into it. And therefore, it's

00:50:58.280 --> 00:51:03.360
[Guest 2]: something that's available. So it's a, you know, there's a demand because there's a supply.

00:51:03.360 --> 00:51:08.360
[Guest 2]: And this is one of those situations where I think that, you know, as much as I believe

00:51:08.360 --> 00:51:15.560
[Guest 2]: that in sort of free markets, that you have to be a rich society in some ways to then

00:51:15.560 --> 00:51:18.400
[Guest 2]: say, okay, we're actually going to take some of the money that the free market generates

00:51:18.400 --> 00:51:22.600
[Guest 2]: and put it into this, because that's also essential for us as human beings. So you'll

00:51:22.600 --> 00:51:26.880
[Guest 2]: find that in a lot of Europe, I think. But there's no question that, you know, in India

00:51:26.880 --> 00:51:33.120
[Guest 2]: and in other places, this has just fallen off the band, the sort of horizon completely.

00:51:33.120 --> 00:51:36.320
[Guest 2]: And that's why you will find some of the more creativity that you will get out of these

00:51:36.320 --> 00:51:38.520
[Guest 2]: small places is, is on things like TikTok.

00:51:38.520 --> 00:51:44.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, TikTok getting banned was so tragic. I keep going on about that because

00:51:44.120 --> 00:51:49.680
[Amit Varma]: it's such an incredible cauldron of creativity, really. And I wonder whether it's a function

00:51:49.680 --> 00:51:53.640
[Amit Varma]: of poverty, that of course, we're a poor country. And that is why, you know, in our hierarchy

00:51:53.640 --> 00:51:58.080
[Amit Varma]: of needs, culture is like, way beyond people are more just focused on the immediate so

00:51:58.080 --> 00:52:02.840
[Amit Varma]: culture comes later. Or is there something deeper? I mean, you know, you do among privileged

00:52:02.840 --> 00:52:06.600
[Amit Varma]: sets of people, you do have a certain kind of cultural life, like the music festivals

00:52:06.600 --> 00:52:11.560
[Amit Varma]: in South India, for example, and so on and so forth. But in general, in the life of the

00:52:11.560 --> 00:52:15.000
[Amit Varma]: common person, like here, you will not find a taxi driver who's going to a museum, for

00:52:15.000 --> 00:52:21.840
[Amit Varma]: example, you know, so but that's I mean, that's neither here nor there. So tell me about the

00:52:21.840 --> 00:52:27.320
[Amit Varma]: so what, what's the next step then that you know, you've childhood in Delhi, you've done

00:52:27.320 --> 00:52:31.680
[Amit Varma]: your schooling and all of that. How did you start gravitating towards law? Like was it

00:52:31.680 --> 00:52:38.000
[Amit Varma]: kind of happenstance in a series of accidents? What was your conception of a future Akshay

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:43.120
[Guest 2]: at that age? What did you want to be? Well, actually, I thought of law relatively early

00:52:43.120 --> 00:52:49.800
[Guest 2]: during college years. Again, if you were in Delhi University in the 80s, there were three

00:52:49.800 --> 00:52:54.520
[Guest 2]: or four different types of careers that were available to you. If you're doing economics

00:52:54.520 --> 00:52:58.680
[Guest 2]: or maths or physics or one of those things, then you could possibly go to, you know, you'd

00:52:58.680 --> 00:53:03.520
[Guest 2]: go to one of the IIMs or one of the business schools, that was one route. The other route

00:53:03.520 --> 00:53:07.920
[Guest 2]: was this phalanx of people who would go and do the civil services exam. And the reason

00:53:07.920 --> 00:53:12.480
[Guest 2]: I did it was just didn't do it at all, didn't even look in that direction. It was very simply

00:53:12.480 --> 00:53:19.560
[Guest 2]: the value of my time was too much. So to spend potentially 1, 2, 3, 4 years of your life

00:53:19.560 --> 00:53:23.920
[Guest 2]: repeatedly studying for an exam in which your chances of success were very low, just didn't

00:53:23.920 --> 00:53:31.080
[Guest 2]: seem and for a career that I valued, appreciated, but wasn't mad about, I didn't see the point.

00:53:31.080 --> 00:53:34.200
[Guest 2]: So I didn't even look in that direction. And the third thing to do was to go abroad to

00:53:34.200 --> 00:53:40.840
[Guest 2]: study. So I chose this, that option because it wasn't sort of, I hadn't done maths, I

00:53:40.840 --> 00:53:46.020
[Guest 2]: did history in college and was not, you know, calculus was beyond me. And so I took that

00:53:46.020 --> 00:53:50.940
[Guest 2]: option and really it was because partly by default, partly because both my parents studied

00:53:50.940 --> 00:53:55.540
[Guest 2]: abroad and they talked about the wonderful things that it had done for them. So the one

00:53:55.540 --> 00:53:59.060
[Guest 2]: thing that you're not supposed to write in a personal statement, which is that I'm going

00:53:59.060 --> 00:54:04.360
[Guest 2]: abroad to expand my horizons. That was why I wanted to go abroad. I didn't know what

00:54:04.360 --> 00:54:08.720
[Guest 2]: I wanted to do with my degree. So I first went to, I went to Columbia to do a master's

00:54:08.720 --> 00:54:14.520
[Guest 2]: in international affairs. It was an area, it was sort of politics. It was interesting.

00:54:14.520 --> 00:54:20.380
[Guest 2]: I specialized in international law in that. And then I came, I did that for two years.

00:54:20.380 --> 00:54:25.080
[Guest 2]: And it was completely a horizon sort of opening experience. First time I'd, apart from that

00:54:25.080 --> 00:54:30.920
[Guest 2]: one year where the Liverpool love came, I'd never been abroad. I mean, we didn't, families

00:54:30.920 --> 00:54:35.120
[Guest 2]: at that time didn't have the money to go abroad for holidays. So all holidays were leave,

00:54:35.120 --> 00:54:39.720
[Guest 2]: travel, concession, piled into a train, going to see grandparents in Pune or whatever. That's

00:54:39.720 --> 00:54:45.080
[Guest 2]: what the rich, rich, rich, especially in lots of the country like that, but never been abroad.

00:54:45.080 --> 00:54:52.080
[Guest 2]: So lined up in New York in 1989, not knowing how to really operate a computer, done it

00:54:52.080 --> 00:54:57.760
[Guest 2]: once or twice. I typed my personal statements on a brother typewriter, never used a washing

00:54:57.760 --> 00:55:01.440
[Guest 2]: machine, learned how to cook a bit, knew how to cook a few things, but wasn't required

00:55:01.440 --> 00:55:06.960
[Guest 2]: to cook. So all of this stuff, plus doing a degree in which, I'm sure Ajay had a similar

00:55:06.960 --> 00:55:11.480
[Guest 2]: experience, doing a degree in which you had to do an enormous amount of reading every

00:55:11.480 --> 00:55:19.680
[Guest 2]: week. I was reading 12, 1500 pages and going to class, so much so that I got an ulcer which

00:55:19.680 --> 00:55:24.080
[Guest 2]: was diagnosed as a stress ulcer, but apparently ulcers are not caused by stress, they're caused

00:55:24.080 --> 00:55:29.080
[Guest 2]: by bacteria, because I was doing, trying to do as much of the reading in the reading list

00:55:29.080 --> 00:55:32.800
[Guest 2]: as possible. And I went to my supervisor and he said, how's it going? And I said, it's

00:55:32.800 --> 00:55:37.000
[Guest 2]: going fine, but you know, there's a lot of work. So he said, yeah, but you know, what's

00:55:37.000 --> 00:55:40.720
[Guest 2]: the problem? So I said, look at this reading list. He said, are you by any chance trying

00:55:40.720 --> 00:55:44.920
[Guest 2]: to read everything on the reading list? So I said, yes. He said, but you're not supposed

00:55:44.920 --> 00:55:47.920
[Guest 2]: to, you're supposed to pick and choose. And that's when I took the pressure off myself

00:55:47.920 --> 00:55:54.440
[Guest 2]: and then thoroughly enjoyed my degree. Fantastic university, the format where everything was

00:55:54.440 --> 00:55:59.600
[Guest 2]: not dependent on one exam. I'm a terrible examinee. So I did well enough again, but

00:55:59.600 --> 00:56:04.240
[Guest 2]: I had to study hard to do well in exams. I had to study hard to do okay in exams, class

00:56:04.240 --> 00:56:09.640
[Guest 2]: performance always okay. In fact, I was once in college thrown out of class for asking

00:56:09.640 --> 00:56:14.360
[Guest 2]: too many questions, but they were on the topic. So anyway, I was told by the tutor, you think

00:56:14.360 --> 00:56:18.160
[Guest 2]: that you know more than me? Because I said, he hadn't answered my question. You can leave

00:56:18.160 --> 00:56:23.160
[Guest 2]: the class, don't have to come back to for the rest of the term, I'll give you attendance.

00:56:23.160 --> 00:56:26.400
[Guest 2]: And at the end of my degree, I got a first in his paper, I went back to him and said,

00:56:26.400 --> 00:56:31.120
[Guest 2]: thank you, sir, you really helped me a lot. Anyway, there's a little, but it's so, so

00:56:31.120 --> 00:56:36.920
[Guest 2]: the big thing was that they were these fantastic sort of the ability to listen to these fantastic

00:56:36.920 --> 00:56:44.800
[Guest 2]: professors and have the freedom to question views. You know, I always say that our system,

00:56:44.800 --> 00:56:49.640
[Guest 2]: at least then maybe a little less now was, was basically based on what are the five causes

00:56:49.640 --> 00:56:55.160
[Guest 2]: for the decline of the Mughal Empire. That you have to give five, six are not required,

00:56:55.160 --> 00:56:59.400
[Guest 2]: four isn't enough. And there it was, you know, the questions were a completely different

00:56:59.400 --> 00:57:04.880
[Guest 2]: type. And there are people like Bhagwati and various others sort of teaching you luminary

00:57:04.880 --> 00:57:10.520
[Guest 2]: legal luminaries, people who were practitioners and going and doing human rights work in Africa

00:57:10.520 --> 00:57:16.360
[Guest 2]: and coming and teaching a course about that. So it was mind opening completely. So did

00:57:16.360 --> 00:57:21.440
[Guest 2]: that, came back to India, worked for a couple of years at TERI, which was where I started

00:57:21.440 --> 00:57:26.880
[Guest 2]: around 92, started working on the real climate convention, convention and did some paper

00:57:26.880 --> 00:57:31.200
[Guest 2]: writing and research and that sort of thing on that. And that's where the interest in

00:57:31.200 --> 00:57:35.840
[Guest 2]: this continuing interest sort of stems from here. We are 30 years after that. It's difficult

00:57:35.840 --> 00:57:41.380
[Guest 2]: to think of 1992 as 30 years ago, but there you are. And I have friendships and contacts

00:57:41.380 --> 00:57:47.200
[Guest 2]: from that period, which, you know, people who are now the top thinkers in that field

00:57:47.200 --> 00:57:52.480
[Guest 2]: in India. Yeah. So that's what, that was the next step. And then law was after that. So

00:57:52.480 --> 00:57:58.600
[Guest 2]: I came back and I signed up for evening classes because I was never happy with the idea of

00:57:58.600 --> 00:58:04.520
[Guest 2]: being an academic and just writing something and then it going into a paper or a report.

00:58:04.520 --> 00:58:10.320
[Guest 2]: There was one box from the world development report from 1990 that I wrote. That was just,

00:58:10.320 --> 00:58:14.600
[Guest 2]: you know, it was otherwise you wrote a paper, which is what I'm doing now. So it's a bit

00:58:14.600 --> 00:58:19.520
[Guest 2]: surprising that I'm saying that, but at that point, at a 25 year old me, it wasn't or 24

00:58:19.520 --> 00:58:25.200
[Guest 2]: year old me, it wasn't what I wanted to do. So I went back to the idea of doing law, enrolled

00:58:25.200 --> 00:58:29.100
[Guest 2]: in evening classes in Delhi University and had a fight with a tutor or the professor

00:58:29.100 --> 00:58:37.040
[Guest 2]: and left and didn't go back. Here's another coincidence. A friend's, a cousin's friend

00:58:37.040 --> 00:58:42.400
[Guest 2]: came and said, help me fill out my application form for Oxford because I'm going there. So

00:58:42.400 --> 00:58:47.400
[Guest 2]: I said, hey, let me photocopy it and let me also apply to do law. And that's how I applied

00:58:47.400 --> 00:58:51.880
[Guest 2]: to Oxford to do law. And then I got in and went. So again, a big, big coincidence. If

00:58:51.880 --> 00:58:55.240
[Guest 2]: he hadn't come, maybe I'd have just finished that degree and God knows what I would have

00:58:55.240 --> 00:58:56.240
[Amit Varma]: done after that.

00:58:56.240 --> 00:59:02.160
[Amit Varma]: What is crazy if he goes somewhere else that day or twists his ankle instead or whatever.

00:59:02.160 --> 00:59:07.000
[Amit Varma]: So you know, you just said 1992, 30 years, it's kind of hard to think of it as 30 years

00:59:07.000 --> 00:59:10.560
[Amit Varma]: ago, right? And one of the things that I've been thinking of recently is, you know, when

00:59:10.560 --> 00:59:18.320
[Amit Varma]: we are kids, time seems like, so sort of stretched out, you know, when you're 20, 30 seems like

00:59:18.320 --> 00:59:22.960
[Amit Varma]: really old, you know, you'll romanticize and say, oh, you know, bunch of people died at

00:59:22.960 --> 00:59:28.800
[Amit Varma]: 27, bunch of people died at 34. And it seems old enough. And then before you know it, the

00:59:28.800 --> 00:59:34.360
[Amit Varma]: decades pass, and you're suddenly in your 40s, 50s, whatever. And you realize that that

00:59:34.360 --> 00:59:38.040
[Amit Varma]: span of time, which when you were young, you thought was a lot, maybe three decades in

00:59:38.040 --> 00:59:41.960
[Amit Varma]: this case, isn't really a lot. And when you think of, you know, when you speak of history,

00:59:41.960 --> 00:59:46.920
[Amit Varma]: you think of something happening 200 years ago, right? When you're a kid, 200 years ago

00:59:46.920 --> 00:59:52.000
[Amit Varma]: is a long, long time ago. It's history, history. But I think when you're our age, it's not

00:59:52.000 --> 00:59:56.480
[Amit Varma]: really that long ago. It's like four or five times what has just passed in a flash almost

00:59:56.480 --> 01:00:03.760
[Amit Varma]: for us. And does that realization come to you and does that then shape the way you look

01:00:03.760 --> 01:00:08.760
[Amit Varma]: at the world in terms of your priorities and the way you might define happiness, for example,

01:00:08.760 --> 01:00:13.840
[Amit Varma]: the fact that, you know, time passes really quickly. I don't mean this just in the sense

01:00:13.840 --> 01:00:19.200
[Amit Varma]: of being more aware of your own mortality, but just you get it, time passes really fast

01:00:19.200 --> 01:00:22.680
[Amit Varma]: and does that. And it's really a question for both of you, I guess.

01:00:22.680 --> 01:00:27.520
[Guest 2]: I'm not bothered by it. I don't really think about that. I think about it a lot, but more

01:00:27.520 --> 01:00:33.920
[Guest 2]: from an interesting, you know, what does this period of time mean? So I was speaking to

01:00:33.920 --> 01:00:38.920
[Guest 2]: my mother just a couple of days ago. And I said, I just realized that I was born only

01:00:38.920 --> 01:00:46.040
[Guest 2]: 20 years after independence. So you think, you know, the India that I was born into would

01:00:46.040 --> 01:00:51.080
[Guest 2]: have been so dramatically different to the India today. I have only a child sense of

01:00:51.080 --> 01:00:56.360
[Guest 2]: it, not in 67, but the few years after that. But that it was such a fresh India, you know,

01:00:56.360 --> 01:01:01.440
[Guest 2]: in some ways, it was such a new India. And that was the India I was born into. And this

01:01:01.440 --> 01:01:06.480
[Guest 2]: is the India I'm living in. It's just those kinds of thoughts I find interesting to have

01:01:06.480 --> 01:01:11.120
[Guest 2]: every now and then and to just go into a bit of an indulgence, self-indulgence to think

01:01:11.120 --> 01:01:15.720
[Guest 2]: about what that means. But the other thing, the other type of thing I think of, and again,

01:01:15.720 --> 01:01:21.680
[Guest 2]: when you have kids, you realize that how different a period of time is for them than it is for

01:01:21.680 --> 01:01:29.320
[Guest 2]: you. Now, two years for a 16-year-old is an eighth of their life. And that's the COVID

01:01:29.320 --> 01:01:35.160
[Guest 2]: period. So an eighth of my elder daughter's life has been COVID. An eighth of my life

01:01:35.160 --> 01:01:40.720
[Guest 2]: is nothing. I mean, compared to that, it's a huge period. But for her, the importance

01:01:40.720 --> 01:01:51.360
[Guest 2]: of it, for me, this is just a two-fifty-fourth. So that's the kind of frame in which I tend

01:01:51.360 --> 01:01:53.640
[Guest 2]: to think of this. What about you, Ajay?

01:01:53.640 --> 01:01:58.560
[Guest 1]: Yeah, I've also thought precisely what you just described. The Second World War ended

01:01:58.560 --> 01:02:06.080
[Guest 1]: in 1945. India got freedom in 1947. And my birth year, 1966, is actually closer to those dates

01:02:06.080 --> 01:02:12.200
[Guest 1]: than we would otherwise think. So there's a freshness of that period and the way our

01:02:12.200 --> 01:02:19.400
[Guest 1]: parents talked about those events, of the freedom movement, of how I felt the day I

01:02:19.400 --> 01:02:24.000
[Guest 1]: heard Gandhiji was murdered, you know, those kinds of things. There's a freshness of experience

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:31.200
[Guest 1]: there, which would not strike a person growing up in today's world with that same level of

01:02:31.200 --> 01:02:36.040
[Guest 1]: proximity. Similarly, I often notice that I've spent a bigger fraction of my life in

01:02:36.040 --> 01:02:42.040
[Guest 1]: the 20th century than in the 21st century. In a fundamental way, I'm wired like a thinker

01:02:42.040 --> 01:02:49.120
[Guest 1]: of the 20th century. And it has lessons of its own. And it carries a drama on a stage

01:02:49.120 --> 01:02:54.240
[Guest 1]: of a cosmic scale of the kind of things that we don't think about in this world today.

01:02:54.240 --> 01:02:59.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, like, another aspect of this is like, sometimes I have to remind myself

01:02:59.520 --> 01:03:04.720
[Amit Varma]: that look, 60 or 70% of the country or whatever is born after liberalization, after this trip,

01:03:04.720 --> 01:03:10.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, 1992, which we now realize is so long ago. And it's striking because I realized

01:03:10.440 --> 01:03:14.200
[Amit Varma]: that in the way that I look at the world, for example, there are certain realities I

01:03:14.200 --> 01:03:19.080
[Amit Varma]: take completely for granted. They are solidified for me. One of them might be what the nation

01:03:19.080 --> 01:03:24.280
[Amit Varma]: state of India is, for example, the idea of India, I think many people our age, in fact,

01:03:24.280 --> 01:03:29.560
[Amit Varma]: are sort of having to reconsider the notion that the country is what they thought it was,

01:03:29.560 --> 01:03:32.320
[Amit Varma]: that maybe it's something different, and they were in their little bubbles, and they didn't

01:03:32.320 --> 01:03:37.400
[Amit Varma]: realize it. And similarly, there is that sense that young people today, don't have a lot

01:03:37.400 --> 01:03:44.160
[Amit Varma]: of that shared bedrock of understanding the world or looking at the world in the way that

01:03:44.160 --> 01:03:50.280
[Amit Varma]: we do now. And I think as communicators, also, I keep reminding myself that we can fall for

01:03:50.280 --> 01:03:53.520
[Amit Varma]: the curse of knowledge in the sense that we can assume that, you know, if the three of

01:03:53.520 --> 01:03:58.440
[Amit Varma]: us are talking, there are certain shared experiences, which we can just relate to just like that,

01:03:58.440 --> 01:04:03.080
[Amit Varma]: that you could say 84. And we all three of us know what you mean in a visceral level,

01:04:03.080 --> 01:04:07.280
[Amit Varma]: not just in terms of but to a young person, it may just be a date, they may not even make

01:04:07.280 --> 01:04:14.280
[Amit Varma]: that connection. You know, and that's kind of interesting, because I think we, you know,

01:04:14.280 --> 01:04:19.040
[Amit Varma]: are my or I'll speak for myself, my notion of the world to a large extent is based on

01:04:19.040 --> 01:04:25.080
[Amit Varma]: really a small sample size of things. Like what is a nation state like? What is democracy

01:04:25.080 --> 01:04:29.640
[Amit Varma]: like? What happens in autocracies? How do things happen? You look at trends, but actually,

01:04:29.640 --> 01:04:33.360
[Amit Varma]: it's a really small sample size of things happening just two, three, four centuries

01:04:33.360 --> 01:04:38.120
[Amit Varma]: long. And that's not enough to go on. And to assume that there is always a directionality

01:04:38.120 --> 01:04:42.440
[Amit Varma]: that say the arc of history will bend one way or the other. It might be an illusion

01:04:42.440 --> 01:04:47.320
[Amit Varma]: because we don't have enough data. We have not enough life has been lived. So it's not

01:04:47.320 --> 01:04:50.960
[Amit Varma]: something you ever kind of remind yourself, are there moments where you step back and

01:04:50.960 --> 01:04:56.280
[Amit Varma]: say that, wait a minute, you know, I'm, for example, taking the shape of India, you know,

01:04:56.280 --> 01:05:01.000
[Amit Varma]: woman with a sari in the map for granted. It wasn't like that, you know, 70, 80 years

01:05:01.000 --> 01:05:04.600
[Amit Varma]: ago, and it may not be like that 80 years ago, we just don't know, stuff like that.

01:05:04.600 --> 01:05:09.600
[Amit Varma]: I mean, even Kashmir, you know, all our certainties around Kashmir have had to change radically,

01:05:09.600 --> 01:05:10.600
[Guest 2]: right?

01:05:10.600 --> 01:05:17.880
[Guest 2]: Yeah, and I think it's, I think that's done by time and place. I was just reading recently

01:05:17.880 --> 01:05:26.040
[Guest 2]: about why we should try and think like a Russian citizen today, when we think about what's

01:05:26.040 --> 01:05:32.120
[Guest 2]: happening with respect to Ukraine and NATO. And, you know, Putin is obviously betting

01:05:32.120 --> 01:05:37.600
[Guest 2]: on the fact that what he's doing has resonance because his internal situation to him is more

01:05:37.600 --> 01:05:44.160
[Guest 2]: important, and perhaps more precarious than the external one. But if you are in St. Petersburg,

01:05:44.160 --> 01:05:51.920
[Guest 2]: and if someone is talking about Latvia and Lithuania and Estonia coming into NATO, you

01:05:51.920 --> 01:05:57.640
[Guest 2]: are thinking of a historical foe at your doorstep. So that is going to make you think about the

01:05:57.640 --> 01:06:04.080
[Guest 2]: world very differently than you would if you're sitting in Germany. And I think time has a

01:06:04.080 --> 01:06:08.560
[Guest 2]: similar kind of effect as where you are in that particular point in time. And one of

01:06:08.560 --> 01:06:14.320
[Guest 2]: my daughters, perhaps it's a failing on my part, but just a month ago said, and she's

01:06:14.320 --> 01:06:23.600
[Guest 2]: 13, she said, Dad, what's 9-11? So, you know, 9-11 is one of the defining things, international

01:06:23.600 --> 01:06:30.880
[Guest 2]: events of our lifetimes. But for her, she's heard about it. And I'm glad she didn't have,

01:06:30.880 --> 01:06:34.560
[Guest 2]: she wasn't like I probably would have been at her age, which is, oh, there's something

01:06:34.560 --> 01:06:38.640
[Guest 2]: it seems like I should know about and I don't, let me go and find out about it. She just

01:06:38.640 --> 01:06:42.840
[Guest 2]: asked me, I would never have done that. And I'm glad she's like that. And she asked me

01:06:42.840 --> 01:06:49.880
[Guest 2]: and then I had to go into an explanation of 9-11. But to an intelligent 13 year old without

01:06:49.880 --> 01:06:53.960
[Guest 2]: wanting to be condescending, this is something I learned from my father, who would always

01:06:53.960 --> 01:06:58.400
[Guest 2]: argue serious things with you, but without condescension at any age. It's a very, very

01:06:58.400 --> 01:07:02.560
[Guest 2]: tough thing to do, because you will know more than your child. I mean, that's you'd better

01:07:02.560 --> 01:07:07.160
[Guest 2]: otherwise, you probably shouldn't have had the child in the first place. And you have

01:07:07.160 --> 01:07:13.160
[Guest 2]: to go into an explanation, which is giving facts, which isn't giving too much editorial,

01:07:13.160 --> 01:07:18.320
[Guest 2]: but you want your kids to have your values. And there are sort of consequences. If you

01:07:18.320 --> 01:07:23.360
[Guest 2]: were explaining 9-11 to someone in the two years that followed it, you would have a very

01:07:23.360 --> 01:07:28.960
[Guest 2]: different story to tell about it, even someone like you or me, then we would have today because

01:07:28.960 --> 01:07:32.560
[Guest 2]: we realized that there were no weapons of mass destruction. At that point, even we would

01:07:32.560 --> 01:07:36.480
[Guest 2]: have thought, right now we'll turn around and say, look at the so and so that Bush was,

01:07:36.480 --> 01:07:40.000
[Guest 2]: at that point, we might have thought, yes, maybe they are, maybe it was still the wrong

01:07:40.000 --> 01:07:44.400
[Guest 2]: thing to do to invade Iraq, but maybe they are weapons of mass destruction. Today, we

01:07:44.400 --> 01:07:49.320
[Guest 2]: know that they weren't. So that point at time in which you look at something, I think is

01:07:49.320 --> 01:07:55.520
[Guest 2]: as important as where in the world are you looking at it from? So both, I think are important.

01:07:55.520 --> 01:07:59.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I'm also kind of glad that your daughter asked you that question instead of

01:07:59.160 --> 01:08:03.160
[Amit Varma]: putting it on social media, because the trend today, somebody would have screenshotted it

01:08:03.160 --> 01:08:06.600
[Amit Varma]: and 10 years later, they would have put it up and said this person didn't even know what

01:08:06.600 --> 01:08:11.280
[Amit Varma]: 9-11 was. Is she really capable of being a director at this museum for something she

01:08:11.280 --> 01:08:15.400
[Guest 2]: tweeted 30 years ago? Or they would have said today, they would have said, oh, Akshay Jaitley's

01:08:15.400 --> 01:08:21.480
[Guest 2]: daughter doesn't know what 9-11 is. Yeah, that too.

01:08:21.480 --> 01:08:26.680
[Guest 2]: No, but by the way, sorry, there's a story there. Kids have become very cautious about

01:08:26.680 --> 01:08:32.200
[Guest 2]: what they post. Younger folks are very, very cautious about what they post precisely because

01:08:32.200 --> 01:08:38.200
[Guest 2]: of being mocked, ridiculed, humiliated and all the rest of it. So, you know, query whether

01:08:38.200 --> 01:08:43.240
[Guest 2]: that's questioning, that's suppressing freedom of expression or not, or whether that is the

01:08:43.240 --> 01:08:48.240
[Guest 2]: right place or necessarily Twitter is the only place where you should be expressing

01:08:48.240 --> 01:08:50.800
[Guest 2]: your opinion, but that's definitely happening. No question.

01:08:50.800 --> 01:08:55.440
[Amit Varma]: No, I sometimes think about what would have happened if social media had been around when

01:08:55.440 --> 01:08:59.440
[Amit Varma]: I was young. And I would be like, I would have been cancelled 80 times by now, because

01:08:59.440 --> 01:09:02.560
[Amit Varma]: when you're young, you're thinking whatever you're experimenting, like I said, I carried

01:09:02.560 --> 01:09:07.080
[Amit Varma]: marks in my, you know, in my rucksack for a while to college, you're experimenting with

01:09:07.080 --> 01:09:10.440
[Amit Varma]: all kinds of ideas, you're saying all kinds of things, you know, the male brain doesn't

01:09:10.440 --> 01:09:14.880
[Amit Varma]: develop properly till you're 25. You know, which is why you have all this crazy male

01:09:14.880 --> 01:09:18.800
[Amit Varma]: teenage violence and all of that you're not socialized properly. And there's all this

01:09:18.800 --> 01:09:23.760
[Amit Varma]: shit going on. And we never had that pressure, we could just grow up in whatever way. You

01:09:23.760 --> 01:09:26.880
[Amit Varma]: know, maybe if you guys knew the person I was, when I was 20, you wouldn't want to know

01:09:26.880 --> 01:09:31.800
[Amit Varma]: me, we'd never start having conversations, right? And vice versa, for all I know. Is

01:09:31.800 --> 01:09:34.560
[Amit Varma]: it true Ajay that you were a punk rocker when you were 19?

01:09:34.560 --> 01:09:42.160
[Guest 1]: Yeah, I was clearly a weird person at 19. I agree with everything you said that I would

01:09:42.160 --> 01:09:48.560
[Guest 1]: have been all over social media in truly toxic ways that would have been damaging to me then

01:09:48.560 --> 01:09:57.480
[Guest 1]: to me now. So I'm like, just grateful that these technologies did not exist. It would

01:09:57.480 --> 01:10:03.160
[Guest 1]: have disproportionately influenced the way I think and then there would have been all

01:10:03.160 --> 01:10:10.120
[Guest 1]: kinds of angry people jumping at me. And this thing about storage of data is terrifying.

01:10:10.120 --> 01:10:16.440
[Guest 1]: So systems that capture store data that can be used against you at future dates, are really

01:10:16.440 --> 01:10:21.800
[Guest 1]: chilling the human mind. And I think, you know, we were just lucky that at a younger

01:10:21.800 --> 01:10:26.880
[Guest 1]: age, we have said all kinds of rubbish, and it has not been recorded.

01:10:26.880 --> 01:10:31.760
[Guest 2]: Little thought experiment here. That's the sort of, I agree with all of this, because

01:10:31.760 --> 01:10:35.640
[Guest 2]: that's that's the obvious answer to all the rubbish we would have said that if we would

01:10:35.640 --> 01:10:43.080
[Guest 2]: have all said rubbish, we would have all been called out for it. However, that was a time

01:10:43.080 --> 01:10:49.640
[Guest 2]: at which there was no cancellation. So we are assuming that we have the culture of today

01:10:49.640 --> 01:10:53.760
[Guest 2]: where there's cancellation with the words that we you and I would have had then which

01:10:53.760 --> 01:10:58.360
[Guest 2]: would probably should have should be should have been cancelled. But anyway, that's what

01:10:58.360 --> 01:11:04.320
[Guest 2]: we are assuming. If we'd said those things at that point where there wasn't a wider culture,

01:11:04.320 --> 01:11:12.440
[Guest 2]: which had become so divided, and so polarized, then maybe that you would have said it on

01:11:12.440 --> 01:11:17.720
[Guest 2]: social media then like you have, like you did in public, and maybe you would have got

01:11:17.720 --> 01:11:22.120
[Guest 2]: the same reaction because that's what you were saying it into. And maybe that would

01:11:22.120 --> 01:11:27.360
[Guest 2]: have led to people acknowledging that these things are said, and us not coming to the

01:11:27.360 --> 01:11:32.600
[Guest 2]: point where we have a cancel culture, because so many of the people who are doing cancel

01:11:32.600 --> 01:11:38.240
[Guest 2]: culture are either young or hypocritical. So you have, everybody has said rubbish, misogynistic

01:11:38.240 --> 01:11:42.920
[Guest 2]: things and all of we've all done it. We all think that today we think it wasn't the right

01:11:42.920 --> 01:11:48.480
[Guest 2]: thing to do. And we've grown up and that's the part of the process. But if, if that had

01:11:48.480 --> 01:11:54.600
[Guest 2]: been a time vacuum, or sort of, if it's sort of frozen time, then, then that might be true.

01:11:54.600 --> 01:11:58.680
[Guest 2]: But that itself would have had an impact on the culture, which would have then evolved

01:11:58.680 --> 01:11:59.680
[Guest 1]: to a different place.

01:11:59.680 --> 01:12:02.920
[Guest 1]: I'm worried about something else. I'm worrying about the human being. I want to use George

01:12:02.920 --> 01:12:08.040
[Guest 1]: Orwell's phrase, political speech. Okay, so there are two kinds of speech in the world

01:12:08.040 --> 01:12:14.960
[Guest 1]: you speak the truth, or you speak very carefully, it is a move in a chess game. It's a part

01:12:14.960 --> 01:12:20.200
[Guest 1]: of a chess combination that is intended to influence the world in certain ways that fulfill

01:12:20.200 --> 01:12:26.800
[Guest 1]: some ulterior objectives. The guarded, careful conversations that we know how to do as adults

01:12:26.800 --> 01:12:33.760
[Guest 1]: in recorded spheres, such as this one, are not a complete fulfillment of being a human

01:12:33.760 --> 01:12:41.920
[Guest 1]: being. And I fear that in the modern world, it's just becoming the only kind of communication

01:12:41.920 --> 01:12:48.000
[Guest 1]: that people learn to do. So it has a chilling effect that there is a very important role

01:12:48.000 --> 01:12:54.760
[Guest 1]: for the human mind to speak the truth, there should be safe spaces to be able to speak

01:12:54.760 --> 01:13:01.080
[Guest 1]: honestly with each other to do heretical, controversial expression. And that is how

01:13:01.080 --> 01:13:04.360
[Guest 1]: we grapple with ideas. That is how we play with ideas. That is how we make mistakes.

01:13:04.360 --> 01:13:10.880
[Guest 1]: That is how we fumble. That is how we learn. And for all of us here, we know the unique

01:13:10.880 --> 01:13:17.400
[Guest 1]: deadness of the prose that is written in public life on a government file. I fear so much

01:13:17.400 --> 01:13:23.260
[Guest 1]: of the oral expression of the world has become that. Whereas earlier, we used to be hypocritical

01:13:23.260 --> 01:13:27.640
[Guest 1]: about it, that we would speak honestly in a certain way, when there was no microphone.

01:13:27.640 --> 01:13:32.640
[Guest 1]: And then there was everything else that we did in front of recordings. I fear a world

01:13:32.640 --> 01:13:39.320
[Guest 1]: in which everything is recorded. It will stunt the development of the human mind and the

01:13:39.320 --> 01:13:40.320
[Guest 1]: imagination.

01:13:40.320 --> 01:13:47.680
[Amit Varma]: A couple of other aspects also like one aspect is that not only does your data get captured,

01:13:47.680 --> 01:13:52.600
[Amit Varma]: and you can be cancelled later or whatever, but you also get solidified into those positions.

01:13:52.600 --> 01:13:58.120
[Amit Varma]: I take a position X, 30 people attack me, and then I double down on it. And then I become

01:13:58.120 --> 01:14:03.400
[Amit Varma]: associated with X. And then that's who I am. That's who I become as well. Whereas otherwise

01:14:03.400 --> 01:14:07.680
[Amit Varma]: I might say X today, I might say Y tomorrow, I might, you know, you play around and you

01:14:07.680 --> 01:14:12.480
[Amit Varma]: kind of discover and all of that. So I fear that just in the shaping of the self, it's

01:14:12.480 --> 01:14:13.480
[Amit Varma]: a problem.

01:14:13.480 --> 01:14:17.140
[Amit Varma]: And the other issue, you know, you quoted Orwell, and that's also true, the need not

01:14:17.140 --> 01:14:21.640
[Amit Varma]: just to be careful about what you say, because it can be used against you. But the need to

01:14:21.640 --> 01:14:26.520
[Amit Varma]: also make your speech idiot proof, because you know that there are people out there who

01:14:26.520 --> 01:14:32.400
[Amit Varma]: are looking for gotcha moments in bad faith, who will misinterpret everything you say.

01:14:32.400 --> 01:14:37.920
[Amit Varma]: So you've not just got to, you know, be careful about what you say, but even how you say it,

01:14:37.920 --> 01:14:42.120
[Amit Varma]: and make sure it's not misinterpreted. And the point is, if so much of your time goes

01:14:42.120 --> 01:14:47.120
[Amit Varma]: into the framing of your thought, then that much less time goes into the thinking of thoughts

01:14:47.120 --> 01:14:54.560
[Amit Varma]: itself. And it's a chilling effect. It's a paralyzing effect to thought. It's scary.

01:14:54.560 --> 01:15:00.320
[Guest 2]: Again, I'm wondering whether we might have reached peak that. Because if I look at my

01:15:00.320 --> 01:15:08.420
[Guest 2]: 13 year olds, and my 12 year old niece, who's with us at the moment, they seem to be beginning

01:15:08.420 --> 01:15:16.600
[Guest 2]: to have an instinctive reaction to, for want of a better word, wokeness. They're not necessarily

01:15:16.600 --> 01:15:21.320
[Guest 2]: disagreeing with the underlying principle, which again, many people who've been accused

01:15:21.320 --> 01:15:25.520
[Guest 2]: of, who have been cancelled for not being woken up, are not disagreeing with the underlying

01:15:25.520 --> 01:15:30.360
[Guest 2]: principle. They're just saying, allow me to say this in a certain way. And I feel that

01:15:30.360 --> 01:15:37.320
[Guest 2]: there's at least at that age, young teenagers, in my very limited experience, are beginning

01:15:37.320 --> 01:15:44.000
[Guest 2]: to say, look, doesn't matter if you say it, but are you actually like this? And perhaps

01:15:44.000 --> 01:15:49.240
[Guest 2]: it's because, and this is just thinking out loud over here, perhaps it's because they're

01:15:49.240 --> 01:15:55.960
[Guest 2]: now seeing a lot more of what we heard about. So for instance, there are two girls in my

01:15:55.960 --> 01:15:59.800
[Guest 2]: daughter's class who are going out with each other at the age of 13. So it's completely

01:15:59.800 --> 01:16:04.440
[Guest 2]: normalized for them. We still have to think about it, internalize it, and intellectualize

01:16:04.440 --> 01:16:09.520
[Guest 2]: it and say, yes, that's fine. For them, it's just fine. They don't have to think about

01:16:09.520 --> 01:16:15.440
[Guest 2]: it. So then their attitude towards that, when that is normal, then they don't have to be

01:16:15.440 --> 01:16:21.800
[Guest 2]: woke about it in order to just consider it to be normal. So maybe you're reaching, beginning

01:16:21.800 --> 01:16:25.880
[Guest 2]: to reach that point. I'd like to believe that you're reaching that point. But on the speech

01:16:25.880 --> 01:16:30.800
[Guest 2]: front, Ajay, I completely agree with you. And funnily enough, one of my girls, I talk

01:16:30.800 --> 01:16:34.960
[Guest 2]: a lot about my girls, by the way. So I was writing an essay on exactly that paragraph

01:16:34.960 --> 01:16:39.760
[Guest 2]: and we were talking about it. And you know, this, the same discussion came up about what

01:16:39.760 --> 01:16:45.560
[Guest 2]: you say and who you say it to, that it matters. But that you should be free to say in where

01:16:45.560 --> 01:16:49.880
[Guest 2]: you think you're, you're free to say something, you should, you should say it. And I was made

01:16:49.880 --> 01:16:58.000
[Guest 2]: by my parents to read 1984, before 1984. So I finished it in December 1983.

01:16:58.000 --> 01:17:05.440
[Amit Varma]: What a fantastic story. Yeah, that's another chapter in your autobiography, 1984 before 1984.

01:17:05.440 --> 01:17:12.960
[Amit Varma]: So you go on to study the law. Now, did studying the law also change the way you think about

01:17:12.960 --> 01:17:18.840
[Amit Varma]: stuff? Because I would imagine, from an outsider's perspective, not having studied or known law

01:17:18.840 --> 01:17:25.400
[Amit Varma]: myself, that it trains you to think in a systematic way, in a rigorous way, you're reading a lot,

01:17:25.400 --> 01:17:30.240
[Amit Varma]: it will also give you habits of research of thinking through arguments and all of that.

01:17:30.240 --> 01:17:34.880
[Amit Varma]: And if you if it, if you apply all of those habits to your study of law, you will also

01:17:34.880 --> 01:17:39.920
[Amit Varma]: then begin to apply it to any place else. And now one way of looking at it could be

01:17:39.920 --> 01:17:44.720
[Amit Varma]: that someone who already thinks like that, who has those habits of mind will naturally

01:17:44.720 --> 01:17:49.520
[Amit Varma]: make a good lawyer. But the other way is that it can also go the other way, that just studying

01:17:49.520 --> 01:17:55.160
[Amit Varma]: the law makes you look at the world more rigorously look for frameworks that you can apply and,

01:17:55.160 --> 01:17:59.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, go from point A to B to C and all of that. So do you think you were naturally

01:17:59.480 --> 01:18:04.000
[Amit Varma]: a thinker of that sort? Or do you think that's the happenstance of studying the law with

01:18:04.000 --> 01:18:09.040
[Amit Varma]: all the happy accidents that led to it sort of led you to the point where and changed

01:18:09.040 --> 01:18:14.640
[Guest 2]: you? I don't know the answer to that. But I sort

01:18:14.640 --> 01:18:19.680
[Guest 2]: of qualify the question a little bit. And then I will give you an answer, which might

01:18:19.680 --> 01:18:24.640
[Guest 2]: be somewhat interesting, which is it's not so much the study of the law, but the practice

01:18:24.640 --> 01:18:31.480
[Guest 2]: of it. Because when you study law, at least the way that I was taught it, you're taught

01:18:31.480 --> 01:18:36.200
[Guest 2]: in a very specific method in Oxford and in Cambridge, which is the tutorial system. You

01:18:36.200 --> 01:18:40.240
[Guest 2]: go in, basically you're not taught anything, you have to go off and do a bunch of reading

01:18:40.240 --> 01:18:44.200
[Guest 2]: and come back and discuss the answer to a question in front of your tutor. And what

01:18:44.200 --> 01:18:47.840
[Guest 2]: they're looking for is for you to find ways to defend whatever argument you're coming

01:18:47.840 --> 01:18:53.160
[Guest 2]: up with, which is what law ultimately is about. But that same method is applied to philosophy,

01:18:53.160 --> 01:18:59.600
[Guest 2]: English literature, the classics, anything. So it's particularly useful for the law. So

01:18:59.600 --> 01:19:05.120
[Guest 2]: I studied law there and this method was used. And I think it's something that helped me

01:19:05.120 --> 01:19:11.480
[Guest 2]: in the longer term. But it's when you start practicing law that your mind starts, the

01:19:11.480 --> 01:19:15.880
[Guest 2]: way that your mind works starts changing. And sometimes not necessarily in a good way

01:19:15.880 --> 01:19:20.520
[Guest 2]: for the rest of your life, but it's very effective. You need to think in that way as a lawyer,

01:19:20.520 --> 01:19:25.000
[Guest 2]: which is a very risk averse way. You need to, and in fact, you have to do, it's a positive

01:19:25.000 --> 01:19:30.360
[Guest 2]: attribute while you're practicing as a lawyer, to be able to pass words and to think hard

01:19:30.360 --> 01:19:34.160
[Guest 2]: about what the potential meanings of what you're writing down could be, the placement

01:19:34.160 --> 01:19:40.000
[Guest 2]: of a comma, all the rest of it is all really important because there are implications to

01:19:40.000 --> 01:19:44.800
[Guest 2]: your clients for getting it wrong. So you become risk averse, but then what you find

01:19:44.800 --> 01:19:50.320
[Guest 2]: yourself doing is in your normal conversation, you try and say something in a way where they

01:19:50.320 --> 01:19:55.040
[Guest 2]: couldn't be another interpretation, whereas normal people don't do that. They say whatever

01:19:55.040 --> 01:19:58.240
[Guest 2]: things in whatever way they want. And if there's someone doesn't understand, they'll clarify

01:19:58.240 --> 01:20:03.400
[Guest 2]: it. But I find myself, I found myself many, many times over the years thinking really

01:20:03.400 --> 01:20:09.000
[Guest 2]: hard about a sentence or something that I'm writing in a non-legal context to make sure

01:20:09.000 --> 01:20:14.080
[Guest 2]: that there could not be two possible interpretations of that. And that no doubt that changes the

01:20:14.080 --> 01:20:22.040
[Guest 2]: plasticity of your brain and you become slightly more boring, if you like, in the way that

01:20:22.040 --> 01:20:26.040
[Guest 2]: you apply your analytical ability. Now, if you continue to be engaged with the rest of

01:20:26.040 --> 01:20:31.200
[Guest 2]: the world and you read other stuff and you have friends from different walks of life,

01:20:31.200 --> 01:20:36.360
[Guest 2]: then that tempers that a bit, which sort of leads me to a question that Ajay and I were

01:20:36.360 --> 01:20:40.160
[Guest 2]: talking about earlier is that I'm opposed to this five-year law school thing in some

01:20:40.160 --> 01:20:45.280
[Guest 2]: ways because you're telling 16-year-olds to start thinking like that, 17-year-olds only

01:20:45.280 --> 01:20:49.760
[Guest 2]: with other people who are studying law. So, you, your whole, not only are you thinking

01:20:49.760 --> 01:20:53.440
[Guest 2]: just like that, but everybody, your close friends, a lot of closest, our closest friends

01:20:53.440 --> 01:20:59.920
[Guest 2]: are from college days. They are, they're all lawyers. So, the argument for some of these

01:20:59.920 --> 01:21:04.880
[Guest 2]: national law schools to become broader universities, I think is really strong. And Ajay tells me

01:21:04.880 --> 01:21:10.200
[Guest 2]: that one or two of them are potentially thinking about that, but to be surrounded by, to be

01:21:10.200 --> 01:21:15.000
[Guest 2]: surrounded by people studying political science and economics, et cetera, will make, not only,

01:21:15.000 --> 01:21:18.720
[Guest 2]: you know, give you a different outlook on life, would make you a better lawyer because

01:21:18.720 --> 01:21:22.480
[Guest 2]: ultimately you're practicing in the world. You're not practicing in a vacuum. So, the

01:21:22.480 --> 01:21:25.800
[Guest 2]: best lawyers that I've come across are people who have a really good understanding of the

01:21:25.800 --> 01:21:32.280
[Guest 2]: rest of the world and can place their legal analysis and work within that. So, I've gone

01:21:32.280 --> 01:21:35.720
[Amit Varma]: all over the place a little bit over there. No, no, that's a fantastic answer. Much food

01:21:35.720 --> 01:21:40.080
[Amit Varma]: for thought. And there's an orthogonal question that I sometimes think about. I might even

01:21:40.080 --> 01:21:46.360
[Amit Varma]: have discussed it with Ajay separately, but it's about the nature of our education system

01:21:46.360 --> 01:21:50.200
[Amit Varma]: and how it's ripe for disruption, but not in the way that it is happening right now.

01:21:50.200 --> 01:21:55.240
[Amit Varma]: Today, what we see is all of this so-called edtech and these disruptive influences are

01:21:55.240 --> 01:21:59.320
[Amit Varma]: disruptive in terms of delivery, how they deliver it to you. But what is being taught

01:21:59.320 --> 01:22:04.480
[Amit Varma]: to you is the same. The thinking behind what education is, is essentially the same. And

01:22:04.480 --> 01:22:08.840
[Amit Varma]: I've been thinking for a long time that, you know, our way of teaching, that you have ten

01:22:08.840 --> 01:22:13.080
[Amit Varma]: standards in school and then another couple, and then these are the different streams that

01:22:13.080 --> 01:22:17.040
[Amit Varma]: you go into. And if you're so many years old, you'll be in this class and these are the

01:22:17.040 --> 01:22:21.520
[Amit Varma]: exams you will do and you will all learn together. And these are really notions which solidified

01:22:21.520 --> 01:22:26.600
[Amit Varma]: in the early 19th century. And they were okay for that time. They were okay in an instrumental

01:22:26.600 --> 01:22:30.880
[Amit Varma]: way, that you're training kids to grow up and be a particular thing, maybe a bureaucrat

01:22:30.880 --> 01:22:36.720
[Amit Varma]: and a cog, or maybe a particular kind of person. And today, largely, they don't apply, but

01:22:36.720 --> 01:22:41.880
[Amit Varma]: through inertia, we've just stuck with it. And, you know, so many of us, all the really

01:22:41.880 --> 01:22:45.640
[Amit Varma]: important things that we have learned, much more in my case, and you guys, obviously,

01:22:45.640 --> 01:22:50.960
[Amit Varma]: but much more in my case, or something outside of the system, right? So I just, and you referred

01:22:50.960 --> 01:22:57.800
[Amit Varma]: to one aspect of it, you know, and I sometimes think that at some point at a deeper fundamental

01:22:57.800 --> 01:23:03.920
[Amit Varma]: level as a society, we just need to rethink this whole education itself, this template

01:23:03.920 --> 01:23:08.280
[Amit Varma]: in our head, that you have 10 classes and 10 standards, and you do these six subjects

01:23:08.280 --> 01:23:13.040
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth. And then you go into these separate fields, which are kept separate.

01:23:13.040 --> 01:23:17.720
[Amit Varma]: If you're doing law, you only do law, and blah, blah, blah. And even if one were to

01:23:17.720 --> 01:23:22.600
[Amit Varma]: be able to conceive of alternatives, how those alternatives would come about is something

01:23:22.600 --> 01:23:27.640
[Amit Varma]: that kind of beats me a little. And that's the kind of disruption I'd like to see beyond,

01:23:27.640 --> 01:23:31.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, the disruption of delivery that okay, we'll do online classes, but the syllabus

01:23:31.920 --> 01:23:37.640
[Amit Varma]: is still ICSE, CBSE. You have any thoughts about this?

01:23:37.640 --> 01:23:42.920
[Guest 2]: I think there's some experimentation with this that I've experienced with my children,

01:23:42.920 --> 01:23:49.680
[Guest 2]: which is that they've put people in, say, grade five with kids from grade seven together

01:23:49.680 --> 01:23:54.440
[Guest 2]: to learn certain things, and they're learning from each other. I think the problem here

01:23:54.440 --> 01:24:01.160
[Guest 2]: is at least in our country is from the concept or the phenomenon that I call the Delhi auntie.

01:24:01.160 --> 01:24:05.320
[Guest 2]: The Delhi auntie doesn't want change. The Delhi auntie doesn't want her kid to go to

01:24:05.320 --> 01:24:10.480
[Guest 2]: school during COVID times, irrespective of what is doing, forget about or to all the

01:24:10.480 --> 01:24:14.840
[Guest 2]: poorer kids who don't have access to online and all of that, and are doing it, answering

01:24:14.840 --> 01:24:18.400
[Guest 2]: questions with a phone or going to school once a week, getting a sheet and filling it

01:24:18.400 --> 01:24:24.200
[Guest 2]: out and giving it back, but even on their own kids, because there's just this shoehorning

01:24:24.200 --> 01:24:33.560
[Guest 2]: into thinking in a particular way. I think it's on the demand side that the real resistance

01:24:33.560 --> 01:24:37.480
[Guest 2]: is coming and who is going to sort of turn around and say, no, I'm going to take the

01:24:37.480 --> 01:24:43.040
[Guest 2]: risk of antagonizing all these people from whom I'm making a fantastic living by collecting

01:24:43.040 --> 01:24:48.320
[Guest 2]: large fees. Who's going to take that risk? I don't know. But I think with the IB system,

01:24:48.320 --> 01:24:51.840
[Guest 2]: there's a bit of a change in that they encourage analytical thinking at least in the last two

01:24:51.840 --> 01:24:57.000
[Guest 2]: or three years of school. And more and more schools are switching to that. You know, perhaps

01:24:57.000 --> 01:25:03.360
[Guest 2]: the change is going to come at least in that end of school kind of level by the fact, and

01:25:03.360 --> 01:25:07.680
[Guest 2]: this is only true for richer kids, by the fact that more and more people are going abroad.

01:25:07.680 --> 01:25:13.920
[Guest 2]: And what abroad is asking for, what universities abroad are requiring is more analytical thinking.

01:25:13.920 --> 01:25:20.640
[Guest 2]: So you're going to have to produce it on the supply side. So maybe that's one way in which

01:25:20.640 --> 01:25:24.320
[Guest 2]: it would change. But I have to say that this is not an area of my specialization. Ajay

01:25:24.320 --> 01:25:26.560
[Guest 2]: probably knows more than I do.

01:25:26.560 --> 01:25:34.000
[Guest 1]: Yeah, as somebody that has been in the machine all my life of taking and teaching and courses

01:25:34.000 --> 01:25:39.600
[Guest 1]: and exams and all that rubbish, I've just become profoundly skeptical about the machine

01:25:39.600 --> 01:25:46.520
[Guest 1]: that I feel what works in learning is reading and thinking and debating and exploring the

01:25:46.520 --> 01:25:52.800
[Guest 1]: world in a more open ended and unstructured way. I think apprenticeships are a great method

01:25:52.800 --> 01:25:59.400
[Guest 1]: through which things are learned. I think whatever I learned, well, I learned myself.

01:25:59.400 --> 01:26:03.440
[Guest 1]: And I think whatever good things I did for other people in their learning journey was

01:26:03.440 --> 01:26:09.160
[Guest 1]: more in an apprenticeship model, rather than in the machinery of a classroom and exams

01:26:09.160 --> 01:26:14.520
[Guest 1]: and all that. So I'm just like very underwhelmed at the machine. I think we've tried to industrialize

01:26:14.520 --> 01:26:19.200
[Guest 1]: something which really should be artisanal, it should be proudly artisanal.

01:26:19.200 --> 01:26:27.360
[Guest 2]: Yeah, I mean, my thoughts are just going back to my teenage years in Delhi, where our home

01:26:27.360 --> 01:26:31.640
[Guest 2]: was a place where people would come and go, all kinds of people would come and go, not

01:26:31.640 --> 01:26:36.600
[Guest 2]: just for meals in the evening, but come and stay for like few days, which was very much

01:26:36.600 --> 01:26:43.000
[Guest 2]: an open house. And the kinds of people that I interacted with as a teenager in those years

01:26:43.000 --> 01:26:47.280
[Guest 2]: who I had conversations with, more sort of overheard conversations, sometimes when you

01:26:47.280 --> 01:26:51.240
[Guest 2]: were not supposed to, you're supposed to be asleep, and then you'd hear all sorts of interesting

01:26:51.240 --> 01:26:59.120
[Guest 2]: things was a very important influence in how I learned things, how I, the fact that you

01:26:59.120 --> 01:27:03.640
[Guest 2]: had these views and views should be debated, and you should respect other people's opinions.

01:27:03.640 --> 01:27:08.920
[Guest 2]: So not just the content, but the how of it were really important. I mean, people like

01:27:08.920 --> 01:27:15.000
[Guest 2]: Arun Shourie and Mani Shankar Iyer and Farooq Dhondi, the journalist and Mrinalini Sarabhai

01:27:15.000 --> 01:27:19.640
[Guest 2]: and all these sorts of people would come in and out of the house. And it was, I had no

01:27:19.640 --> 01:27:27.600
[Guest 2]: sense of what how rich my, this sort of quote unquote education was, but it was as important

01:27:27.600 --> 01:27:33.080
[Guest 2]: if not more as any other any word I learned in school. So I think, absolutely, I agree

01:27:33.080 --> 01:27:34.080
[Guest 2]: completely.

01:27:34.080 --> 01:27:39.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, Arun Shourie, by the way, is one of my sort of when I started this show, I had

01:27:39.400 --> 01:27:43.440
[Amit Varma]: a list of five or six names that I have to have these people on the show. And Arun Shourie

01:27:43.440 --> 01:27:48.440
[Amit Varma]: was right on top and I got everyone else, but he keeps turning me down. I mean, if someone

01:27:48.440 --> 01:27:53.920
[Amit Varma]: who knows him well is listening to this, kindly convince him we can have a nice 10 hour conversation.

01:27:53.920 --> 01:27:57.880
[Guest 1]: And if Valli Kaul is listening to the show, please find Akshay somehow.

01:27:57.880 --> 01:28:01.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you know, when he was talking about his college years, when Akshay was talking

01:28:01.640 --> 01:28:05.400
[Amit Varma]: about his college years, I immediately thought that if it was made into a web series now,

01:28:05.400 --> 01:28:10.080
[Amit Varma]: not just a book, then you could have this fictionalized episode where he is looking

01:28:10.080 --> 01:28:13.960
[Amit Varma]: into a book in a cafe and the waitress comes up to him and he looks up and he sees this

01:28:13.960 --> 01:28:16.960
[Amit Varma]: Valli Kaul, which would be...

01:28:16.960 --> 01:28:20.840
[Guest 2]: You know, Netflix would really be scraping at the bottom of the barrel if they were making

01:28:20.840 --> 01:28:22.160
[Guest 2]: a web series about me.

01:28:22.160 --> 01:28:26.800
[Amit Varma]: No, you know, I'll tell you something, Netflix has completely lost it in India, the kind

01:28:26.800 --> 01:28:32.240
[Amit Varma]: of garbage they are commissioning simply because their whole thinking is to go to Bollywood,

01:28:32.240 --> 01:28:35.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, not looking thinking outside the box at all. I think in fact, Prime is doing

01:28:35.920 --> 01:28:40.440
[Amit Varma]: a better job. So actually if Netflix did a series on your life, and I would gladly volunteer

01:28:40.440 --> 01:28:46.160
[Amit Varma]: to be showrunner, I'm sure it would be quite a success. But leaving that aside, so let's,

01:28:46.160 --> 01:28:50.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, as much as you are a lawyer, you also at this point in time, then eventually

01:28:50.720 --> 01:28:54.480
[Amit Varma]: ended up becoming an entrepreneur. So tell me a bit about that journey.

01:28:54.480 --> 01:28:58.880
[Guest 2]: Well, actually, being becoming, I say this quite often, but becoming an entrepreneur

01:28:58.880 --> 01:29:05.120
[Guest 2]: probably extended my legal career by at least a decade, in the sense that, you know, I'm

01:29:05.120 --> 01:29:11.240
[Guest 2]: I'm not a lawyer's lawyer, I enjoy the law, I love the law. I love the work that I did

01:29:11.240 --> 01:29:16.840
[Guest 2]: for a long time. But this sort of upbringing and the fact that I did a policy degree, and

01:29:16.840 --> 01:29:23.400
[Guest 2]: I worked in policy for a bit, it was always there. And just if I had continued working,

01:29:23.400 --> 01:29:27.120
[Guest 2]: I worked with an English law firm for five, six years before coming back to India. If

01:29:27.120 --> 01:29:30.680
[Guest 2]: I'd continue to do that, I don't think I would have remained a lawyer, I would have done

01:29:30.680 --> 01:29:36.720
[Guest 2]: something different, what that something different would have been no idea. But it was the fact

01:29:36.720 --> 01:29:43.160
[Guest 2]: that there was more to it than the, you know, the nuts and bolts of the daily job. There's

01:29:43.160 --> 01:29:51.320
[Guest 2]: no doubt that that was a source of incredible sort of satisfaction and engagement, just

01:29:51.320 --> 01:29:56.000
[Guest 2]: engagement. I mean, the fact that very early on when we, you know, I think we're talking

01:29:56.000 --> 01:30:02.160
[Guest 2]: about setting up tri-legal and all of that, very early on those parts of it, the firm

01:30:02.160 --> 01:30:07.120
[Guest 2]: building, institution building parts of it was something that I really sort of was engaged

01:30:07.120 --> 01:30:13.160
[Guest 2]: by and gravitated towards, while enjoying the legal work. I mean, I loved for many,

01:30:13.160 --> 01:30:18.400
[Guest 2]: many years, I love the technical bits of drafting a complex, you know, construction contract

01:30:18.400 --> 01:30:24.520
[Guest 2]: or a concession or whatever. And I enjoyed dotting my I's and crossing my T's and making

01:30:24.520 --> 01:30:28.960
[Guest 2]: sure the cross-referencing was done and all of it, which is part of the job, but I enjoyed

01:30:28.960 --> 01:30:34.640
[Guest 2]: it actually. But at the same time, we were, you know, the firm was becoming bigger and

01:30:34.640 --> 01:30:39.160
[Guest 2]: we were doing more and more of management and the kind of management that you do in

01:30:39.160 --> 01:30:44.240
[Guest 2]: what was essentially a startup, which is just building things and seeing what would happen

01:30:44.240 --> 01:30:50.800
[Guest 2]: was incredibly interesting and no idea where it would go, what it would become, or that

01:30:50.800 --> 01:30:55.600
[Guest 2]: we were entrepreneurs. We didn't think, we didn't have these words really to, we set

01:30:55.600 --> 01:30:59.880
[Guest 2]: up right in the beginning of the dot-com bust, so not the best time to do it, but it probably

01:30:59.880 --> 01:31:03.400
[Guest 2]: gave us a little time to step back and think and I wrote some policies and

01:31:03.400 --> 01:31:05.240
[Guest 1]: Who is we?

01:31:05.240 --> 01:31:15.840
[Guest 2]: We. So, we is, there were six of us who set up the firm in the year 2000. So, it's now

01:31:15.840 --> 01:31:23.000
[Guest 2]: 22 years. Rahul Mathan and Prem Ayyappa in Bangalore, Karan Singh and Sridhar Gorthi

01:31:23.000 --> 01:31:28.960
[Guest 2]: in Bombay and myself and Anand Prasad in Delhi. And the tri-legal came from the fact that

01:31:28.960 --> 01:31:32.200
[Guest 2]: we set up in three offices at the same time and not the fact that there were three of

01:31:32.200 --> 01:31:37.560
[Guest 2]: us. There were six of us plus a few associates and we, from the very beginning, we had three

01:31:37.560 --> 01:31:45.920
[Guest 2]: offices or three cities and I met Rahul Mathan first. Rahul was the quote-unquote Indian

01:31:45.920 --> 01:31:50.480
[Guest 2]: lawyer on a transaction where I was the English lawyer when I was still in England and both

01:31:50.480 --> 01:31:54.600
[Guest 2]: of us thought that the other guy was vastly more experienced than we actually were. So,

01:31:54.600 --> 01:31:59.880
[Guest 2]: we were obviously playing a good game, talking a good game, but we were both two, three years

01:31:59.880 --> 01:32:03.840
[Guest 2]: qualified and we were, we'd been put onto this transaction that our bosses weren't particularly

01:32:03.840 --> 01:32:09.400
[Guest 2]: interested in. Small deal and we'd talk on the phone and exchange notes and all of that.

01:32:09.400 --> 01:32:14.880
[Guest 2]: And at one point, India was playing Australia or Pakistan in Bangalore and early internet,

01:32:14.880 --> 01:32:18.320
[Guest 2]: I couldn't get the score and I called, I picked up the phone, couldn't resist. I picked up

01:32:18.320 --> 01:32:23.600
[Guest 2]: the phone, called Rahul on the client's account, probably I shouldn't be admitting that, and

01:32:23.600 --> 01:32:27.920
[Guest 2]: said, Rahul, what's the score? And that broke the ice between us and then we realized that

01:32:27.920 --> 01:32:33.080
[Guest 2]: we were both a bunch of kids, a pair of kids with wet behind their ears who didn't know

01:32:33.080 --> 01:32:37.280
[Guest 2]: what we were really talking about. But a few years later, we closed the same deal together.

01:32:37.280 --> 01:32:40.880
[Guest 2]: It took a long time. We had to get the law changed, by the way, to close the deal. It

01:32:40.880 --> 01:32:46.200
[Guest 2]: was in foreign exchange broking, which wasn't recognized as an NBFC activity. So, when we

01:32:46.200 --> 01:32:50.800
[Guest 2]: did the FIPB application, they said, what is this? And it's a foreign exchange trading.

01:32:50.800 --> 01:32:54.400
[Guest 2]: No, no, no, it's not trading, it's broker. Somebody wants to buy, somebody wants to sell,

01:32:54.400 --> 01:32:59.320
[Guest 2]: I'm the guy in between. And then it took us six, eight, ten months to get a notification

01:32:59.320 --> 01:33:04.560
[Guest 2]: to have it put onto the list so that an approval could be given. So, anyway, brief aside. So,

01:33:04.560 --> 01:33:09.640
[Guest 2]: when we were closing this deal, we both got very drunk here in Bombay in either the Oberoi

01:33:09.640 --> 01:33:16.600
[Guest 2]: or the Taj, I think it was the Oberoi. And we said, what are you going to do? This must

01:33:16.600 --> 01:33:23.360
[Guest 2]: have been late 97. What are you going to do in the future? And I said, well, I want to

01:33:23.360 --> 01:33:27.140
[Guest 2]: come back to India. I'm not an immigrant. I want to come back to India and do something

01:33:27.140 --> 01:33:30.520
[Guest 2]: on my own. And he said, I want to leave the firm I'm with and do something. And so, let's

01:33:30.520 --> 01:33:35.400
[Guest 2]: do it together. And in the spirit of our 17th glass of wine, we said, yeah, yeah, let's

01:33:35.400 --> 01:33:40.360
[Guest 2]: do this. And I went off to Tokyo to rejoin the English firm in Tokyo for a couple of

01:33:40.360 --> 01:33:45.960
[Guest 2]: years and he carried on. And then, long story short, two years later, we set up. We continued

01:33:45.960 --> 01:33:50.040
[Guest 2]: talking. We got the other guys involved as well. Rahul broke off a little earlier from

01:33:50.040 --> 01:33:55.680
[Guest 2]: his firm, the firm that he was with then set up. And we just, you know, whatever little

01:33:55.680 --> 01:34:02.440
[Guest 2]: savings we had, we had a basement in which we called a lower ground floor in Delhi. We

01:34:02.440 --> 01:34:09.760
[Guest 2]: had a tiny, the whole office, Amit, must have been the size in Bombay of this room. And

01:34:09.760 --> 01:34:14.160
[Guest 2]: we had, it was out of Rahul's house in Bangalore. And that's how we started. And I had 10,000

01:34:14.160 --> 01:34:19.280
[Guest 2]: pounds, which then cost was six lakhs of rupees as savings, which was put into buying books.

01:34:19.280 --> 01:34:22.320
[Guest 2]: Other people had similar amounts that they'd saved. And that's how we started. None of

01:34:22.320 --> 01:34:27.120
[Guest 2]: us had family backgrounds in the law, other than Sridhar, whose father was the judge advocate

01:34:27.120 --> 01:34:31.840
[Guest 2]: general, but his clients are soldiers. So, you know, you can't, there are no clients

01:34:31.840 --> 01:34:37.840
[Guest 2]: being handed to us. And we just got going and got on with it.

01:34:37.840 --> 01:34:42.960
[Amit Varma]: So you know, what were those early days like where, you know, you started this and like

01:34:42.960 --> 01:34:46.320
[Amit Varma]: you mentioned, it's common for family firms to come up and your dad is someone and your

01:34:46.320 --> 01:34:51.040
[Amit Varma]: uncle is someone and all of that, but you're just a bunch of entrepreneurs, perhaps not

01:34:51.040 --> 01:34:56.800
[Amit Varma]: using that term. And you've sort of started this up. And there are six of you. And I imagine

01:34:56.800 --> 01:35:01.440
[Amit Varma]: that early on, you know, did people take you seriously? Did you have self-doubt? Did you

01:35:01.440 --> 01:35:04.080
[Amit Varma]: have imposter syndrome? How did all that work out?

01:35:04.080 --> 01:35:08.880
[Guest 2]: Funnily enough, we didn't have imposter syndrome and self-doubt at that point. We just thought

01:35:08.880 --> 01:35:13.440
[Guest 2]: we'll just do this. The work will come, we'll do it. And worst comes to worst, if it doesn't

01:35:13.440 --> 01:35:19.200
[Guest 2]: work, somebody will give us a job. None of us have had a job since so it did work. But

01:35:19.200 --> 01:35:24.720
[Guest 2]: there was a lot of winging it. We were the most experienced of us had five years in the

01:35:24.720 --> 01:35:29.600
[Guest 2]: profession, which is not what you should have when you, you know, set up a law firm.

01:35:30.480 --> 01:35:36.320
[Guest 2]: So the way we got around that was we discussed things intensely amongst us. We debated,

01:35:36.320 --> 01:35:40.960
[Guest 2]: we questioned, we reviewed each other's work all the time so that we'd at least have two

01:35:40.960 --> 01:35:44.880
[Guest 2]: sets of or three sets of opinions if we didn't, you know, didn't have someone who had 20 years

01:35:44.880 --> 01:35:51.440
[Guest 2]: of experience. And that's something that's really sort of, I'm sure for the others as

01:35:51.440 --> 01:35:56.160
[Guest 2]: well, but certainly for me, the fact that I've not had a mentor, I've never had, I haven't

01:35:56.160 --> 01:36:02.160
[Guest 2]: had a boss since, you know, I was in my early 30s. It's something that sort of really shaped,

01:36:02.160 --> 01:36:06.560
[Guest 2]: it gave us some degree of insecurity, but it also gave us the confidence once we were

01:36:06.560 --> 01:36:11.760
[Guest 2]: slightly successful that, hey, this is doable. But we had to do all kinds of stuff. So I,

01:36:11.760 --> 01:36:17.760
[Guest 2]: you know, getting clients wasn't easy. One of the subterfuges I adopted was,

01:36:18.320 --> 01:36:24.000
[Guest 2]: I wrote to one of the trade journals, trade magazines in England, from a fictitious email

01:36:24.000 --> 01:36:29.440
[Guest 2]: address, which was a composite of the two senior partners of two well-known Delhi law firms,

01:36:30.800 --> 01:36:34.240
[Guest 2]: composed an email address, and it was Hotmail Day, so still from hotmail.com,

01:36:35.040 --> 01:36:39.040
[Guest 2]: saying that, oh, do you know that this associate from this well-known English firm has gone to

01:36:39.040 --> 01:36:44.720
[Guest 2]: India and set up a firm, and you may, anonymously, and you may want to contact him. So two weeks

01:36:44.720 --> 01:36:49.120
[Guest 2]: later, the phone rings and the magazine contacts me and they wrote a little blurb about me.

01:36:49.120 --> 01:36:52.480
[Guest 2]: And a month after that, somebody said, oh, we read this blurb about you and we have a deal

01:36:52.480 --> 01:36:58.960
[Guest 2]: to give you. So that was, you know, one of, those are the kinds of things that,

01:36:58.960 --> 01:37:06.000
[Guest 2]: some of the kinds of things we did. And then through a contact, we got, we landed this

01:37:06.000 --> 01:37:11.600
[Guest 2]: really big transaction, which was Power Grid wanted to wrap telecom cable around its electrical lines,

01:37:11.600 --> 01:37:16.800
[Guest 2]: and it was complicated because we had to deal with telecom law and electricity law,

01:37:16.800 --> 01:37:21.760
[Guest 2]: and we were working with this big English firm. So this partner from this big English firm,

01:37:21.760 --> 01:37:26.640
[Guest 2]: a guy called Chris Watson, came and worked with us in our office for a week, and our office was

01:37:26.640 --> 01:37:31.360
[Guest 2]: really pokey, and we tried to get him to do all the meetings with us in hotels so that we wouldn't

01:37:31.360 --> 01:37:35.440
[Guest 2]: have to show him a miserable small office. But he said, no, no, no, I'll come to your office.

01:37:35.440 --> 01:37:43.360
[Guest 2]: It's a great spot. And at that time, we had a terrible loo. And we, across the hall from us

01:37:43.360 --> 01:37:48.240
[Guest 2]: was a Kashmiri carpet seller, and his loo was all right. So we told him, oh, our loo is sort of

01:37:48.240 --> 01:37:54.320
[Guest 2]: broken. And he had to go across the street to the Kashmiri carpet seller's office or showroom to go

01:37:54.320 --> 01:37:59.200
[Guest 2]: to the loo. But to give him credit, he worked with us for a week and said, look, I had a fantastic

01:37:59.200 --> 01:38:04.080
[Guest 2]: time working with you guys. You gave me great advice and all of that. But I should stay on,

01:38:04.080 --> 01:38:11.040
[Guest 2]: but I have to go. Because there's the results of this audition that my daughter went to that

01:38:11.040 --> 01:38:16.880
[Guest 2]: coming out and she's possibly going to get a role in a movie. So I have to be there for that. So he

01:38:16.880 --> 01:38:21.200
[Guest 2]: said, no, no, you must go. And he went and his daughter got the role and she's Emma Watson.

01:38:22.960 --> 01:38:23.840
[Guest 2]: What a story.

01:38:23.840 --> 01:38:28.960
[Guest 2]: So Chris still remains a friend and all of that. But you know, so these are the sorts of lots of

01:38:28.960 --> 01:38:34.160
[Guest 2]: stories of this kind that, you know, date from the early times. But there was this sense, you know,

01:38:34.160 --> 01:38:40.320
[Guest 2]: I think it's true for a lot of people who were getting more closely involved. Ajay,

01:38:40.320 --> 01:38:43.600
[Guest 2]: it probably happened with you in government, you were in government at the same time.

01:38:43.600 --> 01:38:47.920
[Guest 2]: There was this sense that kuch ho raha hai India mein, the economy is taking off,

01:38:47.920 --> 01:38:53.920
[Guest 2]: there are all sorts of opportunities, just get stuck in and the future is sort of limitless.

01:38:53.920 --> 01:38:59.200
[Guest 2]: There's this sense of Wild West almost out there that we were writing contracts for the first time.

01:38:59.200 --> 01:39:03.840
[Guest 2]: Nobody had done a wind contract in India before one landed on my desk and I wrote a contract for

01:39:03.840 --> 01:39:08.640
[Guest 2]: a wind farm. These sorts of amazing things were happening in the first decade of this century.

01:39:08.640 --> 01:39:14.480
[Guest 2]: And so, you know, we really went with the flow. And there is just no question that we had so much

01:39:14.480 --> 01:39:19.360
[Guest 2]: luck while doing it. The fact that the right person called you at the right time and you had

01:39:19.360 --> 01:39:24.000
[Guest 2]: a friend who happened to be there who was looking for a lawyer and somebody was conflicted and

01:39:24.000 --> 01:39:29.840
[Guest 2]: this happened and that happened. There was so much luck. But the only thing I'd sort of,

01:39:30.480 --> 01:39:34.720
[Guest 2]: the only thing I'd give ourselves credit for is that we stayed together. And, you know,

01:39:34.720 --> 01:39:39.680
[Guest 2]: for all this time in a situation, in an economy where people sort of brothers fall apart,

01:39:39.680 --> 01:39:44.480
[Guest 2]: we stayed together for, you know, forever. And that's what allowed us to build,

01:39:44.480 --> 01:39:50.720
[Amit Varma]: part of what allowed us to build what we built. So, I keep having arguments about Mahatma Gandhi

01:39:50.720 --> 01:39:54.640
[Amit Varma]: on my show with people who admire him a lot. And of course, I admire him a lot as well.

01:39:54.640 --> 01:39:59.360
[Amit Varma]: But he contained multitudes and one of the many things he rails against in Hind Swaraj

01:39:59.360 --> 01:40:04.720
[Amit Varma]: is lawyers. Of course, he thinks doctors are bad and railways are bad and modern medicine is bad.

01:40:04.720 --> 01:40:10.320
[Amit Varma]: But he hates lawyers as well. And people do have this negative view of lawyers that for money,

01:40:10.320 --> 01:40:15.600
[Amit Varma]: they will sort of defend anything, take any side. Now, I understand the intellectual excitement

01:40:15.600 --> 01:40:19.920
[Amit Varma]: of working in a new environment. And let's say you're framing certain kinds of contracts like

01:40:19.920 --> 01:40:25.520
[Amit Varma]: the wind contracts you described for the first time, and that just must be so exciting. But if

01:40:25.520 --> 01:40:32.080
[Amit Varma]: you look at sort of the common criticisms, folkish and criticisms of the law, for example,

01:40:32.080 --> 01:40:35.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, it could be said that at one level, it's a form of narrative manipulation,

01:40:35.440 --> 01:40:39.440
[Amit Varma]: you don't care about what the truth is, you've got a client, you've got to go with your client,

01:40:39.440 --> 01:40:44.160
[Amit Varma]: you've got to go with your client. And in a sense, therefore, your lawyer is much like say,

01:40:44.160 --> 01:40:48.160
[Amit Varma]: the political consultant of a political party, how do we frame the narrative, obviously,

01:40:48.160 --> 01:40:53.440
[Amit Varma]: your audience is different. And that can have a deadening effect on how you view the truth.

01:40:53.440 --> 01:40:57.600
[Amit Varma]: Another way of looking at it could be that sociopaths would make good lawyers. Now,

01:40:58.320 --> 01:41:02.720
[Amit Varma]: I don't know the data on this. I wrote a column on sociopathy a few years ago, and it's of course,

01:41:02.720 --> 01:41:06.800
[Amit Varma]: a condition of the brain where the amygdala is damaged. So your sense of empathy goes down.

01:41:06.800 --> 01:41:14.240
[Amit Varma]: And sociopaths are well represented in prisons, as you would expect, and among bankers, I think,

01:41:14.240 --> 01:41:19.440
[Amit Varma]: and a couple of other professions, I don't recall if the law was among them. But so what's your

01:41:19.440 --> 01:41:24.880
[Amit Varma]: sense of that? Like, were you ever in a position where you feel a certain dilemma? Do you

01:41:24.880 --> 01:41:29.840
[Amit Varma]: automatically, if you're working with a client, always just become the client's person and just

01:41:29.840 --> 01:41:34.560
[Amit Varma]: see that point of view? Sometimes do you take pause and you say, why am I doing this really?

01:41:34.560 --> 01:41:44.560
[Guest 2]: Well, easier answer for a corporate lawyer, harder for a litigator. It's a big, big question

01:41:44.560 --> 01:41:50.160
[Guest 2]: for litigators at times. There is one sort of ethical answer to that, which is that if

01:41:50.160 --> 01:41:54.480
[Guest 2]: you believe in the rule of law, then you believe that everyone needs representation. And you can

01:41:54.480 --> 01:42:00.640
[Guest 2]: have a view on what the truth might be. But until you have a case that's argued, you don't really

01:42:00.640 --> 01:42:05.840
[Guest 2]: know what the truth is. So, both sides need representation, even a murder, all of that.

01:42:05.840 --> 01:42:12.640
[Guest 2]: That's one side of it. But the other, so that's why for litigators, it matters more. But for

01:42:12.640 --> 01:42:17.440
[Guest 2]: corporate lawyers, the one big difference is that you're both representing, both sides are

01:42:17.440 --> 01:42:23.280
[Guest 2]: representing companies. So, you're representing people with money. There isn't usually a David

01:42:23.280 --> 01:42:29.200
[Guest 2]: and Goliath kind of situation. So, prima facie, you're not getting into that dilemma. And then

01:42:29.200 --> 01:42:33.040
[Guest 2]: you're saying, you know, there are rules that govern the way that lawyers must function. You

01:42:33.040 --> 01:42:37.360
[Guest 2]: should not have an interest in your client's matter and all of that. So, there are sort of

01:42:37.360 --> 01:42:44.800
[Guest 2]: certain guardrails that the regulations themselves present. And also, there's a big sort of factor

01:42:44.800 --> 01:42:49.600
[Guest 2]: that relates to what your reputation is going to be. If you play hard, fast and loose with someone

01:42:49.600 --> 01:42:54.720
[Guest 2]: today, and if you try and slip something in, I mean, I've been in a situation where, for instance,

01:42:54.720 --> 01:43:00.080
[Guest 2]: where the lawyer on the other side made a mistake on a certain provision massively to the advantage

01:43:00.080 --> 01:43:07.440
[Guest 2]: of my client. And I took my client aside and I said, look, we need to tell them about this mistake

01:43:07.440 --> 01:43:11.040
[Guest 2]: because that's not what they intended. You know that that's not what they intended. This is going

01:43:11.040 --> 01:43:14.960
[Guest 2]: to, I didn't even say this is the right thing to do. I just said, this is going to cause a dispute.

01:43:14.960 --> 01:43:18.720
[Guest 2]: You don't want a dispute. You're getting into a joint venture. You don't want to cause a dispute.

01:43:18.720 --> 01:43:24.000
[Guest 2]: So, what that does is that you get the right outcome. You avoid a dispute, but it also helps

01:43:24.000 --> 01:43:30.880
[Guest 2]: your reputation. Your client realizes that if the opposite situation existed, you would do the right

01:43:30.880 --> 01:43:36.960
[Guest 2]: thing by him if he was on the other side. And the reputation of being someone who does things

01:43:36.960 --> 01:43:42.080
[Guest 2]: the right way matters in this profession. It matters in any profession, but particularly

01:43:42.080 --> 01:43:46.320
[Guest 2]: because, why do corporate lawyers get paid a lot of money? They get paid a lot of money because

01:43:46.320 --> 01:43:53.360
[Guest 2]: they protect people's money, because they manage risk. So, if you want to continue to do that,

01:43:53.360 --> 01:43:59.680
[Guest 2]: people are not going to allow you to do that if you act unethically. It doesn't mean people don't,

01:43:59.680 --> 01:44:03.840
[Guest 2]: but I would suggest that the most successful ones and the people with lasting reputations

01:44:04.400 --> 01:44:10.240
[Guest 2]: either are very, very good at managing that situation, which is hard, or they are basically

01:44:10.240 --> 01:44:16.160
[Guest 2]: in the larger scheme of things ethical. So, I think that there is, of course,

01:44:16.160 --> 01:44:23.360
[Guest 2]: the suits image of this, but that's utterly unrepresentative of the way that things work.

01:44:24.560 --> 01:44:28.640
[Guest 2]: Mainly because all the files, I don't know if you've noticed, but all the files in suits,

01:44:28.640 --> 01:44:34.320
[Guest 2]: it's one folder with one sheet of paper. And Harvey Specter looks at one sheet of paper and says,

01:44:34.320 --> 01:44:38.960
[Guest 2]: I know what the answer is, and the deal flips. I mean, we are used to dealing with stacks and

01:44:38.960 --> 01:44:45.360
[Guest 2]: stacks and stacks of boring files. So, the reality is quite different and you're part

01:44:45.360 --> 01:44:50.160
[Guest 2]: of a community or part of a profession, reputation matters. And tell me a little bit about how

01:44:50.720 --> 01:44:56.160
[Amit Varma]: this habit that you have to, you know, develop by force of reading a lot, of taking in a lot

01:44:56.160 --> 01:45:01.600
[Amit Varma]: of information, assimilating it, organizing it in your head, how does it affect then other periods

01:45:01.600 --> 01:45:06.080
[Amit Varma]: of your life? Like, you know, when you're not lawyering so much, for example, like now when

01:45:06.080 --> 01:45:10.880
[Amit Varma]: you're working on all these other disparate interests and all of that, how does it help you

01:45:10.880 --> 01:45:15.120
[Amit Varma]: look at all of these other things, not just in terms of the frameworks that you might have had of

01:45:15.120 --> 01:45:20.720
[Amit Varma]: how you approach a subject, but just these habits that it's okay, I can read like 300 pages in a

01:45:20.720 --> 01:45:25.680
[Amit Varma]: day, I can organize that information, I can take it in. You know, do you have any habits in terms

01:45:25.680 --> 01:45:29.520
[Amit Varma]: of or apps that you use in terms of knowledge management and so on?

01:45:29.520 --> 01:45:34.160
[Guest 2]: Well, I'm, you know, you've talked a number of times about Roam, and I use it a bit,

01:45:34.160 --> 01:45:39.600
[Guest 2]: I use it very inefficiently, but I can see the promise of it. So, one thing, one thing is that,

01:45:39.600 --> 01:45:46.400
[Guest 2]: you know, I, my knowledge management system for 20, 20 odd years was my colleagues, and the firm

01:45:46.400 --> 01:45:52.160
[Guest 2]: and juniors who you say, okay, I remember this from that go and do some research, let's see if

01:45:52.160 --> 01:45:56.880
[Guest 2]: there's something new on it. And so, you know, the number of times when you actually pull out

01:45:56.880 --> 01:46:02.000
[Guest 2]: stuff and read it yourself, without some without having asked someone to get it for you is very

01:46:02.000 --> 01:46:07.840
[Guest 2]: is not that often. So I'm having to sort of retrain myself now, because I don't have a phalanx of

01:46:07.840 --> 01:46:12.960
[Guest 2]: people helping me. And I don't, and the kinds of stuff I'm looking at is different. So Ajay,

01:46:12.960 --> 01:46:18.480
[Guest 2]: for example, told me about Google Scholar, which I never had to ever think about, because I just

01:46:18.480 --> 01:46:22.480
[Guest 2]: had to go and pick up the articles and the articles were in legal journals, we knew where to look.

01:46:23.360 --> 01:46:27.680
[Guest 2]: When you broaden your framework, and when you're, you know, working on your own,

01:46:27.680 --> 01:46:32.000
[Guest 2]: then you need the knowledge management tools. But I was always, always a big note taker,

01:46:32.000 --> 01:46:38.480
[Guest 2]: even in even in my early days. And partly, once I was in a was called into a very big meeting,

01:46:38.480 --> 01:46:46.480
[Guest 2]: a negotiation between multiple banks and power producers in Pakistan and contractors in Korea

01:46:46.480 --> 01:46:51.920
[Guest 2]: and Japan, so multifaceted meeting. And I was very happy to be called as very junior,

01:46:51.920 --> 01:46:56.400
[Guest 2]: I listened to the thing I put up my hand made a point at one at some point, and you know,

01:46:56.400 --> 01:47:00.320
[Guest 2]: people nodded and I was very happy. At the end of the day, the partner who I was working with,

01:47:00.320 --> 01:47:04.560
[Guest 2]: she said, Okay, now, Akshay, go back and just type up your notes for today's meeting.

01:47:05.360 --> 01:47:10.480
[Guest 2]: So I sort of looked blankly at her and said, what notes? She said, you weren't taking notes,

01:47:10.480 --> 01:47:14.000
[Guest 2]: you said, you think I called you in for the legal advice, you're going to give it this meeting.

01:47:14.000 --> 01:47:19.200
[Guest 2]: And from then onwards, I just kept notes of everything that I did. When I read something,

01:47:19.200 --> 01:47:26.960
[Guest 2]: I write on the margin, I put do post-its and I don't have a great memory. So I have to find,

01:47:26.960 --> 01:47:34.240
[Guest 2]: you know, tools and tricks to remember things. But I can see and I'm recommending it to Ajay as

01:47:34.240 --> 01:47:39.440
[Guest 2]: well. I can see how something like Roam would be super, super useful. Because of the fact that it

01:47:39.440 --> 01:47:46.080
[Guest 2]: works basically, like your personal Wikipedia. Yeah, yeah. Zoom, did I say Zoom? That's because

01:47:46.080 --> 01:47:51.680
[Amit Varma]: I was thinking of Zettelkasten, which Roam is based on. Yes. Yeah. So Zoom is a complete game

01:47:51.680 --> 01:47:55.920
[Amit Varma]: changer for me. And I'd also recommend it highly. So take me through this last part of your journey

01:47:55.920 --> 01:48:00.400
[Amit Varma]: then. From Trilegal, the firm becomes successful to where you are today, like you're living in

01:48:00.400 --> 01:48:04.400
[Amit Varma]: Paris, how did that happen? What are your current interests? And what are you moving towards?

01:48:05.360 --> 01:48:10.240
[Guest 2]: Well, a number of things happened. One is that my interest in doing the day to day transactional

01:48:10.880 --> 01:48:17.360
[Guest 2]: work waned. I was not as interested in drafting the contracts, I particularly started dreading

01:48:17.360 --> 01:48:23.520
[Guest 2]: negotiations, especially negotiations on contracts, because you have the same people who are arguing

01:48:23.520 --> 01:48:27.760
[Guest 2]: in the same way about the same points. And I just feel like, you know, putting my arm around the

01:48:27.760 --> 01:48:30.960
[Guest 2]: shoulders of the person and saying, let's go to the next room. These are your three important

01:48:30.960 --> 01:48:37.120
[Guest 2]: points. These are mine. Let's fight about those. And let's not argue about all the crap. And I just

01:48:37.120 --> 01:48:44.320
[Guest 2]: got bored. It was a waste of my time. But I think a pivotal moment for me came when my, in 2014,

01:48:44.320 --> 01:48:50.560
[Guest 2]: started then. When I was with my father in hospital, he'd had surgery. And I was sitting

01:48:50.560 --> 01:48:54.800
[Guest 2]: on the windowsill looking out while he was in bed. And I just said to myself, you know,

01:48:54.800 --> 01:49:00.560
[Guest 2]: I want to spend more time with people that I want to spend time with. And those aren't the other

01:49:00.560 --> 01:49:06.160
[Guest 2]: side in a negotiation. Not that they are perfect. I've made friends like that. But that's not my

01:49:06.160 --> 01:49:10.880
[Guest 2]: choice. I want to spend time in a different way. So from then onwards, I sort of started thinking

01:49:10.880 --> 01:49:16.960
[Guest 2]: about how am I going to devise a strategy to not let this thing that I've created or been part of

01:49:16.960 --> 01:49:22.400
[Guest 2]: creating down. Because I love, I mean, whenever I talk about tri-legal now, even though I'm not a

01:49:22.400 --> 01:49:27.520
[Guest 2]: partner anymore, I will say we. And there will be no other firm that I can ever work for. And I'm

01:49:27.520 --> 01:49:31.360
[Guest 2]: still have a role with the firm as an advisor. And I'm on the board. And you know, I love the

01:49:31.360 --> 01:49:36.240
[Guest 2]: people and some of my closest friends in the world are there and all of that. And I'll be involved

01:49:36.240 --> 01:49:41.600
[Guest 2]: with them into the future. But I just knew that I had to do things. And so I started creating,

01:49:41.600 --> 01:49:46.400
[Guest 2]: first, I looked at sort of doing some policy and advisory work. And after two or three years,

01:49:46.400 --> 01:49:49.840
[Guest 2]: after two or three years of trying that, I realized that doing through the front door

01:49:49.840 --> 01:49:55.120
[Guest 2]: lobbying to change policies for the good of everybody is a very tough thing to do in India.

01:49:55.120 --> 01:50:00.000
[Guest 2]: It's very hard to do that. Your interlocutors in government don't always know what you're

01:50:00.000 --> 01:50:04.960
[Guest 2]: talking about. Sometimes intentions are very good. Sometimes people are very smart. But if

01:50:04.960 --> 01:50:09.040
[Guest 2]: you've done 10 years of renewable energy, and they've done it for the last six months, you're

01:50:09.040 --> 01:50:13.360
[Guest 2]: not having the same conversation. After having tried to do that for a bit, I said, look, I'd

01:50:13.360 --> 01:50:18.640
[Guest 2]: rather not do that. I'd rather not go through the pain of doing that. Let me think of another way.

01:50:18.640 --> 01:50:24.640
[Guest 2]: And then I sort of, that was one thought. And then as I said earlier, the fact that I wanted my kids

01:50:24.640 --> 01:50:30.880
[Guest 2]: to have both my wife and I wanted to have them the freedom of growing up independently, taking

01:50:30.880 --> 01:50:35.840
[Guest 2]: their own decisions, taking their own risks, and not being driven around with in car driver, didi,

01:50:35.840 --> 01:50:40.960
[Guest 2]: you know, all of that as you have in Delhi. That was one other reason. And this is something that

01:50:40.960 --> 01:50:46.160
[Guest 2]: people laugh about and scoff at, but pollution. I mean, if you are a rational human being,

01:50:46.160 --> 01:50:51.360
[Guest 2]: you should not live in Delhi, if you have a choice. And then finally, my wife is French.

01:50:51.360 --> 01:50:54.480
[Guest 2]: And we'd always had this thing where at some point, we'll go and live in France,

01:50:54.480 --> 01:50:59.200
[Guest 2]: let the kids have access to that part of their life and culture and aunts and cousins and all

01:50:59.200 --> 01:51:03.840
[Guest 2]: of that. So those were all the reasons and it had been planned long before the pandemic,

01:51:03.840 --> 01:51:09.280
[Guest 2]: and it was announced well in advance and within the firm and people kept it quiet.

01:51:09.280 --> 01:51:12.320
[Guest 2]: And then we said, okay, what is the role that I'm going to have? How am I going to work with

01:51:12.320 --> 01:51:16.880
[Guest 2]: the firm? So, continued to figure that out. And then I landed up there and I, you know,

01:51:16.880 --> 01:51:21.040
[Guest 2]: frankly, all the stuff that I was supposed to do, I couldn't do. Because of the pandemic,

01:51:21.040 --> 01:51:26.800
[Guest 2]: I was supposed to help get new clients for the firm to do business development, to do client

01:51:26.800 --> 01:51:32.480
[Guest 2]: relationship management, and no one is going to do a Zoom meeting for a vague kind of,

01:51:32.480 --> 01:51:37.840
[Guest 2]: this is who we are pitch. So, I couldn't do anything for a while. And I was doing a bit

01:51:37.840 --> 01:51:43.760
[Guest 2]: of strategic advisory work. So, advising people on what the implications of changes in FDI policy

01:51:43.760 --> 01:51:49.120
[Guest 2]: on China are going to be on your business, or your investment on the power grid in VIT,

01:51:49.120 --> 01:51:56.560
[Guest 2]: on what the potential impact of Biden is going to be on Indo-US economic relations. And the

01:51:56.560 --> 01:52:00.960
[Guest 2]: methodology I follow is I develop a set of questions, speak to a bunch of people who

01:52:00.960 --> 01:52:06.560
[Guest 2]: know about it, add my own analysis around it and do it as a report. It's fun work. There was some

01:52:06.560 --> 01:52:14.480
[Guest 2]: of that. But then I saw an irritating piece of law, an irritating decision, an irritating

01:52:14.480 --> 01:52:21.680
[Guest 2]: circumstance on it in relation to the Chandigarh Discom. And I wrote a LinkedIn post on it saying

01:52:21.680 --> 01:52:28.720
[Guest 2]: this is crap. And, you know, or I did a Substack article. And Menaka Doshi at Bloomberg Quint saw

01:52:28.720 --> 01:52:33.040
[Guest 2]: it and she said, would you like to, can I reprint this? And would you like to do a column? So,

01:52:33.040 --> 01:52:37.120
[Guest 2]: I said, yeah, sounds interesting. And I started doing a column. And that's when I joined your

01:52:37.120 --> 01:52:42.240
[Guest 2]: course to try and rediscover how I, the hint of how I used to write before I became a lawyer and

01:52:42.240 --> 01:52:48.160
[Guest 2]: became boring in my writing. And that column, you know, that column sort of people started getting

01:52:48.160 --> 01:52:53.520
[Guest 2]: a bit interested in it. And one of the pieces, and that might be a good segue into the next part of

01:52:53.520 --> 01:52:59.120
[Guest 2]: the conversation, one of the pieces I was writing was on solar manufacturing policy, where there's

01:52:59.120 --> 01:53:03.600
[Guest 2]: a combination of customs duty and production linked incentives. And I just read Ajay's book.

01:53:04.480 --> 01:53:12.320
[Guest 2]: And I said, everything that's wrong with this policy is theoretically anticipated by the Kelkar

01:53:12.320 --> 01:53:18.320
[Guest 2]: and Shah book. So, I, but I not being an economist and not wanting to make a fool of myself, which

01:53:18.320 --> 01:53:23.360
[Guest 2]: has always been a big theme in my life, that I don't want to make a fool of myself, failed

01:53:23.360 --> 01:53:29.520
[Guest 2]: spectacularly, not trying not to be made a fool of myself many times. I sent the article to Ajay

01:53:29.520 --> 01:53:35.040
[Guest 2]: and I said, look, am I on the right track? Are there any mistakes? And is it theoretically correct?

01:53:35.040 --> 01:53:40.720
[Guest 2]: So, he said, read it and said, yeah, it's fine. But what do you think? Grand question is, I think

01:53:40.720 --> 01:53:46.240
[Guest 2]: only he can. He said, I'm worrying about India's energy transition. India's, how is India going to

01:53:46.240 --> 01:53:50.240
[Guest 2]: deal with climate change? Do you have some thoughts? And I thought, boy, do I have some

01:53:50.240 --> 01:53:54.000
[Guest 2]: thoughts? I've been working on this damn thing for 10, 12 years from the beginning of the

01:53:54.000 --> 01:53:59.760
[Guest 2]: renewable sector. I've seen all kinds of things that could have been better. So, I went away and

01:53:59.760 --> 01:54:05.520
[Guest 2]: thought about it for a few weeks. And he said, let's connect again. Came back with four points

01:54:05.520 --> 01:54:11.360
[Guest 2]: to say, this is what we should do. And he said, I agree with you. Let's write a paper.

