01:56:12.160 --> 01:56:16.320
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit, I mean, you've already kind of taken me through a bit of the origin story,

01:56:16.320 --> 01:56:20.560
[Amit Varma]: share where you, you know, you wrote to Ajay and Ajay said, Yeah, this is great. Do you know

01:56:20.560 --> 01:56:26.160
[Amit Varma]: something about this field? And then you got back with your thoughts. And so how was it then deciding

01:56:26.160 --> 01:56:31.600
[Amit Varma]: to work together? Like in the sense that at one level, it's an intellectual exploration. But

01:56:31.600 --> 01:56:37.360
[Amit Varma]: beyond that, what is this? What was your conception of what this is going to be and where this is

01:56:37.360 --> 01:56:45.040
[Guest 1]: going? So we set up a video call, and Akshay had a clean articulation around four steps on how to

01:56:45.040 --> 01:56:52.400
[Guest 1]: think about this. And I come from the research community. So I know the machine of how we think

01:56:52.400 --> 01:56:57.680
[Guest 1]: about problems and turn them into research products. So I said to him, there should be a

01:56:57.680 --> 01:57:05.840
[Guest 1]: paper. And he said, Who, what, how? And I said, I'm happy to help you midwife it. And it's your

01:57:05.840 --> 01:57:11.360
[Guest 1]: ideas. And you know, it's your paper, and I'm happy to help you to build it. So that's how

01:57:11.360 --> 01:57:18.160
[Amit Varma]: we got going on this. And what were the shared beliefs in this? And what were you know,

01:57:18.160 --> 01:57:23.280
[Amit Varma]: the points where, for example, you Akshay said, Okay, I'm bringing this or Ajay says, I'm bringing

01:57:23.280 --> 01:57:27.520
[Amit Varma]: this. Were there areas like that? Were there different strengths that you brought to it? Or

01:57:27.520 --> 01:57:32.080
[Amit Varma]: was it just one subject? And you said, Hey, you know, I, we both really care about this. Let's

01:57:32.080 --> 01:57:40.240
[Guest 2]: just do it and take it from there. It was pretty iterative. I think it wasn't for me, that is,

01:57:40.240 --> 01:57:44.480
[Guest 2]: you heard Ajay's bit about how it started my when he said, Okay, let's do this together. And you

01:57:44.480 --> 01:57:48.400
[Guest 2]: have intellectual leadership. I didn't quite know what that meant. I didn't want to have

01:57:48.400 --> 01:57:52.960
[Guest 2]: intellectual leadership. So I've got these four points. And now you're the scholar, why don't you

01:57:52.960 --> 01:57:57.280
[Guest 2]: do something with them? And I'll hold on to your coattails and go along with it, which is partly

01:57:57.280 --> 01:58:04.160
[Guest 2]: what, what I feel at least that I've done. It was extremely gratifying. The whole process has been

01:58:04.160 --> 01:58:10.880
[Guest 2]: wonderful for me. And those first that initial period where, you know, just I had not gone away

01:58:10.880 --> 01:58:18.400
[Guest 2]: and thought as freely about a subject for a long time, because my all the all the deep thinking

01:58:18.400 --> 01:58:23.040
[Guest 2]: that I was required to do was with respect to a very specific problem. And of course, you bring

01:58:23.040 --> 01:58:29.280
[Guest 2]: lots of divergent tools to bear upon that problem. But the problem is, is very sharp boundaries,

01:58:29.280 --> 01:58:34.160
[Guest 2]: and you're using the tool of the law, right? And the tools of the law, so your question is sharp,

01:58:34.160 --> 01:58:39.360
[Guest 2]: and you know what the bag full of tools that you have are. Now, here, the question is vast,

01:58:39.360 --> 01:58:43.440
[Guest 2]: and everything is a tool potentially that you can, you know, there are all sorts of things,

01:58:44.000 --> 01:58:51.760
[Guest 2]: disciplines you can bring to bear to deal with the overall question of how India should do an

01:58:51.760 --> 01:58:58.160
[Guest 2]: energy transition in a climate transition. So, I went back, I basically dug into my own

01:58:58.720 --> 01:59:04.960
[Guest 2]: practical experience. And, you know, I have to, you know, hasten to say that I'm not an expert

01:59:04.960 --> 01:59:11.280
[Guest 2]: on climate change. I'm not an expert on even the electricity sector. I've done, I'm just,

01:59:11.280 --> 01:59:18.640
[Guest 2]: I've just done a large number of transactions in the sector, in which I've acted largely for

01:59:18.640 --> 01:59:24.240
[Guest 2]: investors, or broadly for people who manage, who need risk management. And what is it that

01:59:24.240 --> 01:59:31.120
[Guest 2]: you're managing risk around? You're managing risk largely around regulation, around some market

01:59:31.120 --> 01:59:38.080
[Guest 2]: stuff, but basically around the huge dense regulatory architecture of the electricity sector

01:59:38.080 --> 01:59:44.160
[Guest 2]: and the power sector, more broadly in the renewable sector specifically. And a year or two

01:59:44.160 --> 01:59:48.640
[Guest 2]: before that, I'd written a chapter in a book by, which was edited by Devesh Kapoor and Madhav

01:59:48.640 --> 01:59:54.640
[Guest 2]: Khosla, in which Ajay also had a chapter, which was on the regulatory state in India and where

01:59:54.640 --> 01:59:59.440
[Guest 2]: that was going. And I wrote a chapter on renewable energy talking about how it was like an oasis of

01:59:59.440 --> 02:00:05.760
[Guest 2]: lighter regulation within the more heavily regulated power sector, and why it was like that,

02:00:05.760 --> 02:00:11.280
[Guest 2]: why it needed to be like that, and why it was a good thing. So, the instincts there were, without

02:00:11.280 --> 02:00:17.440
[Guest 2]: me having thought about it in that way, whether that this lighter regulation, this freedom of

02:00:17.440 --> 02:00:23.040
[Guest 2]: people to do things, this support from the state in the right kind of areas is a good thing, because

02:00:23.040 --> 02:00:29.040
[Guest 2]: I'd experienced that by doing all these transactions. But in doing those transactions,

02:00:29.040 --> 02:00:33.760
[Guest 2]: I effectively came to the conclusion that when I did the first wind contract that I did

02:00:33.760 --> 02:00:42.080
[Guest 2]: in the early, in around 2010, the 10 issues that I discussed with the lending bank as the 10 risks,

02:00:42.080 --> 02:00:47.760
[Guest 2]: if I were to get into a room today with someone, I would have the same 10 risks. The locus of that

02:00:47.760 --> 02:00:52.480
[Guest 2]: risk has changed, the degree of the risk has changed a bit in some transactions or in some

02:00:52.480 --> 02:00:57.600
[Guest 2]: regulatory frameworks, there's a little less risk, but effectively, fundamentally, those things are

02:00:57.600 --> 02:01:03.920
[Guest 2]: still problems. So, and I'd advocated reform a few times, you know, when I was trying to do the

02:01:03.920 --> 02:01:08.080
[Guest 2]: policy advisory work that I was talking about on behalf of chambers of commerce, going and presenting

02:01:08.080 --> 02:01:12.480
[Guest 2]: white papers to government saying, here are things you need to do. And this is what your investors

02:01:12.480 --> 02:01:18.640
[Guest 2]: are asking you for. This is people who are putting dollars on the table or not, or bidding higher on

02:01:18.640 --> 02:01:22.880
[Guest 2]: something because the risk is higher as opposed to bidding lower, or having a fewer number of bidders

02:01:22.880 --> 02:01:28.880
[Guest 2]: in a bid. And this is across not just renewables, or the power sector, but across the infrastructure

02:01:28.880 --> 02:01:35.040
[Guest 2]: sector. We don't know how, we haven't understood at a structural level of the Indian state,

02:01:35.680 --> 02:01:42.800
[Guest 2]: how private investors perceive risk and how capital flows then mirror the perception of risk.

02:01:42.800 --> 02:01:47.200
[Guest 2]: So, this was sort of having presented these white papers and on the same topics.

02:01:47.200 --> 02:01:52.880
[Guest 2]: When I got the opportunity to think more freely about this, I basically said, you know, this

02:01:52.880 --> 02:01:57.920
[Guest 2]: incremental reform that even I've been advocating saying, do this, have a little more payment

02:01:57.920 --> 02:02:03.600
[Guest 2]: security. Why is all this happening? This is all happening because it's all controlled by the state

02:02:03.600 --> 02:02:08.720
[Guest 2]: and the state does not have the right capacity to understand the problems, or to be the right

02:02:08.720 --> 02:02:13.840
[Guest 2]: contracting counterparty or the right interlocutor for people who are doing business. So, you've

02:02:13.840 --> 02:02:20.400
[Guest 2]: garnered this whole regulatory space for yourself, and you don't know how to manage it. So, we have

02:02:20.400 --> 02:02:26.480
[Guest 2]: to, this is broken, and it needs to be broken down and fixed. So, I came up with these four

02:02:26.480 --> 02:02:32.240
[Guest 2]: points. The four points were, one, that you have to sell everything. Two, the biggest problem in

02:02:32.240 --> 02:02:36.400
[Guest 2]: selling everything is the political economy, and that's why privatization hasn't happened to the

02:02:36.400 --> 02:02:41.440
[Guest 2]: degree it has had. So, and there is only one way to deal with this, you have to deal with this

02:02:41.440 --> 02:02:46.800
[Guest 2]: like you did for the successful Bombay slum redevelopments, which is pay everybody,

02:02:46.800 --> 02:02:51.200
[Guest 2]: pay them in the form of a new flat. If someone's stealing electricity, give them a connection and

02:02:51.200 --> 02:02:55.920
[Guest 2]: give them free vouchers. But there's a bigger problem to be solved. So, don't take a moral

02:02:55.920 --> 02:03:01.120
[Guest 2]: view that he is a thief and he should be punished. Pay everybody off. For that, you have to map

02:03:01.680 --> 02:03:06.160
[Guest 2]: very closely the political economy state by state, who are the winners, who are the losers,

02:03:06.160 --> 02:03:11.760
[Guest 2]: and devise a strategy to sell them, sorry, to compensate them. That is the second. The third was,

02:03:12.640 --> 02:03:18.960
[Guest 2]: in a privatized system, regulation becomes much more important. So, you need to change the

02:03:19.520 --> 02:03:23.360
[Guest 2]: regulators, you need to, somebody coming out of a business school or a law school,

02:03:23.360 --> 02:03:27.840
[Guest 2]: the top law schools, they should want to go and be a regulator for five years because the experience

02:03:27.840 --> 02:03:32.320
[Guest 2]: they get at a reasonable wage would be something that would get them a really high paying job in

02:03:32.320 --> 02:03:36.720
[Guest 2]: a law firm in five years' time because that experience is invaluable. And thirdly, I took

02:03:36.720 --> 02:03:44.080
[Guest 2]: a very simplistic approach to say that unless you're going to bring down the grid, there should

02:03:44.080 --> 02:03:50.480
[Guest 2]: be no reason why any electricity transaction in this country should be regulated. If I want to,

02:03:50.480 --> 02:03:54.880
[Guest 2]: if I've got a rooftop, you're my neighbor, I want to sell you solar power, I should be able to sell

02:03:54.880 --> 02:04:00.560
[Guest 2]: it to you as long as technical standards are maintained. Let the government collect 18% GST.

02:04:00.560 --> 02:04:06.960
[Guest 2]: If you want to buy power at a hundred rupees a unit, what goes of your father? So, those were

02:04:06.960 --> 02:04:15.120
[Guest 2]: the four simple ideas that I had and said that basically everything is captured, that I think of

02:04:15.120 --> 02:04:20.640
[Guest 2]: as problems is captured as some aspect of this. And if you, now that you've read the paper and

02:04:20.640 --> 02:04:28.400
[Guest 2]: if you were to unroll the sort of carpet of those ideas, to use a terrible metaphor, then Ajay,

02:04:28.400 --> 02:04:33.920
[Guest 2]: what he did was he took it and said, okay, what do we mean by making all transactions open? It is

02:04:33.920 --> 02:04:40.320
[Guest 2]: bringing the price system. That was sort of economists speak for that slightly intuitive

02:04:40.320 --> 02:04:47.760
[Guest 2]: idea. What does it mean to say that only regulate for preventing the grid to come down? It means

02:04:47.760 --> 02:04:52.000
[Guest 2]: regulate only for market failure. So, you got a market failure, you know, four points on market

02:04:52.000 --> 02:04:56.720
[Guest 2]: failure in the paper. And on the privatization point and on the political economy point,

02:04:56.720 --> 02:05:02.400
[Guest 2]: we would, he just said, yes, that just goes, you know. So, we had a starting point of

02:05:02.400 --> 02:05:09.040
[Guest 2]: deep agreement and, you know, I, for me, I hadn't thought of it in terms of the price system and

02:05:09.040 --> 02:05:14.400
[Guest 2]: the fact that you need to allow all transactions to have a clearing price. I hadn't framed it like

02:05:14.400 --> 02:05:18.400
[Guest 2]: that, but the minute it was framed like that to me, I just said, you know, you have this deep

02:05:18.400 --> 02:05:22.480
[Guest 2]: sigh of relief and say, okay, you know, this is what I've been talking about. I just have the

02:05:22.480 --> 02:05:27.440
[Guest 2]: right language for it now. So, that's what that initial period for me was. Then, you know, then

02:05:27.440 --> 02:05:35.440
[Guest 2]: there's the, what I'd been unused to many years of being a slightly more senior lawyer and within my

02:05:35.440 --> 02:05:40.000
[Guest 2]: firm was to have the ideas and then tell someone to go and do the work. I had to have the ideas

02:05:40.000 --> 02:05:45.280
[Guest 2]: and start doing the work myself this time after a long time, which was a muscle that I had to sort

02:05:45.280 --> 02:05:51.760
[Guest 2]: of bring out and start using again. That's how it all started. Reading your paper, it struck me,

02:05:51.760 --> 02:05:56.160
[Amit Varma]: and that struck me even more while you guys were speaking just now, is that it's like a perfect

02:05:56.160 --> 02:06:00.880
[Amit Varma]: marriage of two things, that on the other hand, there is this deep knowledge of this domain,

02:06:00.880 --> 02:06:06.640
[Amit Varma]: where you get into the sector and you understand all the fault lines, and you get that sort of

02:06:06.640 --> 02:06:12.400
[Amit Varma]: granular knowledge of different kinds of things that can go wrong. And at the same time, there

02:06:12.400 --> 02:06:16.640
[Amit Varma]: is this broad conceptual framework, which makes complete sense. And I don't want to simplify,

02:06:16.640 --> 02:06:20.560
[Amit Varma]: both of you obviously would have had some conceptual clarity and some deep knowledge,

02:06:20.560 --> 02:06:24.480
[Amit Varma]: but it would strike me, Akshay, that you would have had more of the deep knowledge of the nuances

02:06:24.480 --> 02:06:29.360
[Amit Varma]: of individual particular things that can go wrong. And Ajay would have come at it from that

02:06:29.360 --> 02:06:36.000
[Amit Varma]: conceptual framework of free market, the price system rather, of having that price system,

02:06:36.000 --> 02:06:41.680
[Amit Varma]: the information that gives you how the incentives play a part, and then these two kind of get

02:06:41.680 --> 02:06:46.320
[Amit Varma]: married without necessarily stereotyping what you brought to the table. But at a larger level,

02:06:46.320 --> 02:06:53.440
[Amit Varma]: then that brings to mind two questions, that how much was your understanding of this domain

02:06:53.440 --> 02:06:58.240
[Amit Varma]: enhanced by having that conceptual clarity, like do things then start falling into place and you

02:06:58.240 --> 02:07:03.600
[Amit Varma]: say, yeah, okay, it all makes sense. And the second part to that question is almost a converse,

02:07:03.600 --> 02:07:09.200
[Amit Varma]: that you can at an abstract level have conceptual clarity that, you know, Hayek, use of knowledge

02:07:09.200 --> 02:07:14.400
[Amit Varma]: in society, the price system is the one thing that works and so on and so forth, get the incentives

02:07:14.400 --> 02:07:20.400
[Amit Varma]: right and all of that. But when you actually apply it to a concrete field, like what I saw here was

02:07:20.400 --> 02:07:26.000
[Amit Varma]: really an application of Hayek's insights about how the price system works. And suddenly seeing

02:07:26.000 --> 02:07:32.960
[Amit Varma]: that my god at every level at every detail, this makes so much sense to me. So, you know, so these

02:07:32.960 --> 02:07:38.720
[Amit Varma]: are the two questions that one, how much is that detailed knowledge of all the nooks and crannies

02:07:38.720 --> 02:07:44.720
[Amit Varma]: enhanced by applying that conceptual framework to it? And two, in terms of, you know, the conceptual

02:07:44.720 --> 02:07:49.120
[Amit Varma]: framework coming to life in this way, you know, what, how was that process like?

02:07:49.840 --> 02:07:57.520
[Guest 1]: So, I think that if you start from the Indian electricity sector, it is shouting to you that

02:07:57.520 --> 02:08:03.280
[Guest 1]: we don't have the price system, we don't have the incentives, there's just a lack of buyer and

02:08:03.280 --> 02:08:09.520
[Guest 1]: seller clearing around a price, and then the price sending out incentives to reshape the demand side

02:08:09.520 --> 02:08:15.040
[Guest 1]: and reshape the supply side. The Indian electricity sector is just central planning, end to end,

02:08:15.040 --> 02:08:23.040
[Guest 1]: it's completely central planning. The price system doesn't tell the automobile industry

02:08:23.040 --> 02:08:27.200
[Guest 1]: that your cars need to be more efficient, the government makes a regulation and says,

02:08:27.200 --> 02:08:31.360
[Guest 1]: the cars need to be more efficient. So, the central planning is just all over the landscape.

02:08:31.360 --> 02:08:37.280
[Guest 1]: So, that's the first thing that is a weird feature of this field. Like many other fields in India,

02:08:37.280 --> 02:08:45.520
[Guest 1]: there is a deep government interference in the system and a lack of the price system.

02:08:46.080 --> 02:08:51.680
[Guest 1]: That said, this field is a little harder than many. So, I want to be careful in what we say

02:08:51.680 --> 02:08:57.680
[Guest 1]: in this paper and what we see as the journey ahead. What we're saying in this paper is that

02:08:57.680 --> 02:09:03.600
[Guest 1]: the way to solve the problems of the sector is to get the price system to work. And of course,

02:09:03.600 --> 02:09:09.600
[Guest 1]: the main framing of the paper is around climate change, carbon tax, electricity sector. Because

02:09:09.600 --> 02:09:14.720
[Guest 1]: that's a very interesting juxtaposition of the paper that we're going to have to do something

02:09:14.720 --> 02:09:20.960
[Guest 1]: about the pollutant that is carbon dioxide. The cleanest way to deal with that is a carbon tax

02:09:20.960 --> 02:09:25.280
[Guest 1]: and not detailed regulatory interventions. A government saying that at this place,

02:09:25.280 --> 02:09:30.400
[Guest 1]: you will have a solar plant. At this place, we will force this industry to accept this efficiency

02:09:30.400 --> 02:09:35.840
[Guest 1]: standard. Just let prices work. So, fine. You want to stop carbon dioxide? Tax it. But beyond that,

02:09:35.840 --> 02:09:43.120
[Guest 1]: let society figure out what's an appropriate use of carbon dioxide in society. And then that takes

02:09:43.120 --> 02:09:49.040
[Guest 1]: you to electricity. The most important site of the climate transition is the electricity sector,

02:09:49.040 --> 02:09:56.960
[Guest 1]: partly because today it produces a lot of CO2. And because tomorrow, when cooking and mobility

02:09:56.960 --> 02:10:01.760
[Guest 1]: move to electric, that heavy lifting will have to be done in the electricity sector.

02:10:01.760 --> 02:10:06.880
[Guest 1]: So, that's the clean argument of the paper that there is a climate transition problem. The best

02:10:06.880 --> 02:10:11.920
[Guest 1]: way to do it is a carbon tax. For the carbon tax to do its magic, the electricity sector has to be

02:10:12.480 --> 02:10:17.120
[Guest 1]: under the benign influence of the price system and not a bureaucratically controlled,

02:10:17.120 --> 02:10:23.600
[Guest 1]: centrally planned system. However, this is a field that is truly hard. So, now let me turn upside

02:10:23.600 --> 02:10:30.560
[Guest 1]: down and talk about this in a more traditional electricity engineer worldview and electricity

02:10:30.560 --> 02:10:36.080
[Guest 1]: expert worldview. The consumer is a little spoiled in that the consumer expects that when I flick

02:10:36.080 --> 02:10:41.600
[Guest 1]: the switch, the electricity will flow and that the price will be broadly stable and predictable.

02:10:41.600 --> 02:10:46.800
[Guest 1]: Consumers are not ready for price fluctuations. And the price fluctuations that are required in

02:10:46.800 --> 02:10:53.120
[Guest 1]: the modern world are kind of extreme. So, demand has a very high time of day pattern and the

02:10:53.120 --> 02:11:00.560
[Guest 1]: renewables revolution generates intermittency in production. So, the solar production happens only

02:11:00.560 --> 02:11:05.840
[Guest 1]: when the sun is shining. And as the evening comes, when people switch on a lot of appliances,

02:11:05.840 --> 02:11:10.640
[Guest 1]: you actually lose solar capacity and wind is inherently intermittent.

02:11:10.640 --> 02:11:18.960
[Guest 1]: So, it is a leap for us to think that there will be a day and I am 100% convinced that there will

02:11:18.960 --> 02:11:26.640
[Guest 1]: be a day that before we choose to flick on the air conditioner, there'll be a little LCD display

02:11:26.640 --> 02:11:31.360
[Guest 1]: unit on the wall showing us the present price of electricity. And we'll think about it. That

02:11:31.360 --> 02:11:37.360
[Guest 1]: will weave prices into our thinking when we make decisions like flicking on an air conditioner.

02:11:37.360 --> 02:11:44.560
[Guest 1]: But that's a big change in society and we are not there today. For an analogy, all the way until

02:11:44.560 --> 02:11:51.120
[Guest 1]: Nixon abandoned the gold standard, the world believed that 35 ounces of gold was the dollar

02:11:51.120 --> 02:11:55.360
[Guest 1]: and there were fixed exchange rates all around. And at that time, if you tried to say to people

02:11:55.360 --> 02:12:00.640
[Guest 1]: that, you know, there should be a market for the exchange rate and Milton Friedman was this

02:12:00.640 --> 02:12:06.400
[Guest 1]: amazing pioneer in talking about floating exchange rates. It was a big leap and people

02:12:06.400 --> 02:12:12.080
[Guest 1]: would just get irritated at what? You want exchange rates to change every day, every hour,

02:12:12.080 --> 02:12:18.800
[Guest 1]: and every importer, every exporter, every capital flows transaction will have to think about

02:12:18.800 --> 02:12:25.680
[Guest 1]: currency risk. And at this price, does it make sense for me to buy this? Yeah, we did that.

02:12:25.680 --> 02:12:29.680
[Guest 1]: We've come here. Today, exchange rates are floating. Exchange rates fluctuate every day

02:12:29.680 --> 02:12:33.360
[Guest 1]: and we've all learned to live with it. I think that similar intellectual transformation is

02:12:33.360 --> 02:12:38.560
[Guest 1]: required in the electricity sector. So, a lot of buyers and sellers are spoiled by the very fixity

02:12:38.560 --> 02:12:45.280
[Guest 1]: of prices and human beings always want to declutter their minds. So, you think I want to flick on the

02:12:45.280 --> 02:12:51.280
[Guest 1]: switch and some fairly fixed price electricity will flow, but that is a very negation of the

02:12:51.280 --> 02:12:56.560
[Guest 1]: price system. You want prices, you want price fluctuations, you want price flexibility,

02:12:56.560 --> 02:13:02.480
[Guest 1]: but this is a very difficult field to do that. When the wind is blowing and the windmills are

02:13:02.480 --> 02:13:06.880
[Guest 1]: making electricity and if the demand is not there at that point, the price can go to zero.

02:13:06.880 --> 02:13:11.120
[Guest 1]: The price can even become negative. There have been days in Germany where the price of electricity

02:13:11.120 --> 02:13:15.520
[Guest 1]: has gone to zero or to slightly negative numbers because actually for the grid operator, you're

02:13:15.520 --> 02:13:21.200
[Guest 1]: doing a favor by consuming a little bit of electricity at that time. It's a very different

02:13:21.200 --> 02:13:27.120
[Guest 1]: world. It's not easy to store electricity and the renewables generation is highly intermittent.

02:13:27.120 --> 02:13:34.000
[Guest 2]: Just to button slightly at that point, I think that's the key difference in the electricity

02:13:34.000 --> 02:13:38.880
[Guest 2]: sector compared to any other commodity product, which is that you have to consume it as soon

02:13:38.880 --> 02:13:46.800
[Guest 2]: as it's produced. You can't store it. And one, that is changing. Two, you can still think of a

02:13:46.800 --> 02:13:53.920
[Guest 2]: system where you take that factor into account and design a system which is still largely

02:13:53.920 --> 02:14:00.640
[Guest 2]: functioning on the price system and providing technically for the fact that there's going

02:14:00.640 --> 02:14:05.760
[Guest 2]: to be fluctuation in the supply of electricity into the system. What we are trying to do at a

02:14:05.760 --> 02:14:12.480
[Guest 2]: very high level over here is to say, okay, we understand that that's the case, but your thinking

02:14:12.480 --> 02:14:18.480
[Guest 2]: has been in the planning mode and you've been moving incrementally away from that. What we are

02:14:18.480 --> 02:14:23.840
[Guest 2]: saying is your thinking needs to be in the price system and you need to move as far away from that

02:14:23.840 --> 02:14:29.360
[Guest 2]: as is necessary to take into account the fact that this is a flowing commodity which has to

02:14:29.360 --> 02:14:35.520
[Guest 2]: be consumed as soon as it's created. So, what we're trying to do on the basis of some strong

02:14:35.520 --> 02:14:40.960
[Guest 2]: intuitions, one about the way that the market works, prices work, and the second about what

02:14:40.960 --> 02:14:47.120
[Guest 2]: hasn't worked in the Indian electricity sector to put those two together to say, how do we then

02:14:47.120 --> 02:14:52.800
[Guest 2]: start thinking about this in a very different way? And really, Amit, this is the beginning of a

02:14:52.800 --> 02:15:00.160
[Guest 2]: process for us. We are learning the details of how this whole transition could take place,

02:15:00.160 --> 02:15:06.000
[Guest 2]: but we're convinced about the direction, convinced about the fact that that's where we need to

02:15:06.000 --> 02:15:10.000
[Guest 2]: reach. And what's going to happen over the next year or two or three or four, whatever,

02:15:10.000 --> 02:15:14.080
[Guest 2]: is we're going to learn more about this and figure out how we can then suggest something

02:15:14.080 --> 02:15:18.480
[Guest 2]: which is really concrete, which is grounded in the price system, but accounts for the fact that

02:15:18.480 --> 02:15:24.080
[Guest 2]: for the moment, we largely don't have storable electricity.

02:15:24.720 --> 02:15:30.640
[Amit Varma]: And what I'm struck by was, Ajay, what you said about how getting used to that new paradigm,

02:15:30.640 --> 02:15:36.480
[Amit Varma]: where before I flick on my AC, I can see, you know, what the price is. And I agree that that

02:15:36.480 --> 02:15:41.600
[Amit Varma]: is something that can inevitably happen. But I also agree that there will be a time where we

02:15:41.600 --> 02:15:45.920
[Amit Varma]: won't need it because the price of electricity will simply be so low. And you know, you mentioned

02:15:45.920 --> 02:15:50.640
[Amit Varma]: renewables coming in the form of wind or sun or whatever. And I think the future in a sense is

02:15:50.640 --> 02:15:54.560
[Amit Varma]: unknown unknowns, God knows where they'll come from. Like, we were talking earlier earlier about

02:15:54.560 --> 02:15:58.880
[Amit Varma]: nuclear and we'll come back to it maybe later after we finish talking about this paper. But

02:15:58.880 --> 02:16:03.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, maybe that is a source that takes care of the whole problem. But what I find

02:16:03.280 --> 02:16:08.240
[Amit Varma]: illuminating in your paper is how do you create a framework where in this future of unknown

02:16:08.240 --> 02:16:13.600
[Amit Varma]: unknowns, you know, in a centrally planned world, these unknown unknowns might just remain unknown.

02:16:13.600 --> 02:16:18.400
[Amit Varma]: But where you have where individuals have the incentives to go out there and to try to solve

02:16:18.400 --> 02:16:25.520
[Guest 1]: problems, there can be new and innovative ways of sort of... I want to push on the idea of technical

02:16:25.520 --> 02:16:32.320
[Guest 1]: change, innovation and risk taking. What happens a lot in government systems is that there is

02:16:32.320 --> 02:16:38.400
[Guest 1]: extreme bureaucratic and policymaker risk aversion. It's a filter that kills off a lot of

02:16:38.400 --> 02:16:44.000
[Guest 1]: the possibilities. Something very failsafe is done, which is typically, you know, 10, 20, 30

02:16:44.000 --> 02:16:49.920
[Guest 1]: years after it should have been done. And that's the way bureaucratically controlled systems work.

02:16:49.920 --> 02:16:54.480
[Guest 1]: And, you know, for instance, in the field of space exploration, there is a lot of criticism about

02:16:54.480 --> 02:16:59.280
[Guest 1]: the way a NASA approaches it, because they have to overdesign it because they are a government,

02:16:59.280 --> 02:17:04.400
[Guest 1]: because they're a bureaucracy, because failure is not tolerated. Whereas the essence of this field

02:17:04.400 --> 02:17:12.720
[Guest 1]: is going to be innovation. OK, so I have been an excited observer of the technological developments

02:17:12.720 --> 02:17:21.280
[Guest 1]: around solar energy and around energy storage over the last 10, 20 years. What private initiative

02:17:21.280 --> 02:17:27.120
[Guest 1]: and innovation supported by state funding for R&D has done is nothing short of miraculous. It's

02:17:27.120 --> 02:17:32.080
[Guest 1]: amazing the kind of changes that have come today. If you had told me 20 years ago that this is what

02:17:32.080 --> 02:17:38.160
[Guest 1]: this is what will be feasible standing in 2022, I would have said no way. It's beyond my wildest

02:17:38.160 --> 02:17:44.720
[Guest 1]: dreams. But that's what the great free market innovation machine does, that when there is a

02:17:44.720 --> 02:17:50.400
[Guest 1]: price system and there are profits to be made, people take risks, people invent stuff, people

02:17:50.400 --> 02:17:56.640
[Guest 1]: try 20 solutions, many of them will fail. That's absolutely essential in our climate transition

02:17:56.640 --> 02:18:02.960
[Guest 1]: story. So the world is facing a big, hairy, audacious goal of getting the carbon out.

02:18:02.960 --> 02:18:07.200
[Guest 1]: We don't know enough about the world to centrally plan it. We don't know enough

02:18:07.200 --> 02:18:11.840
[Guest 1]: about low carbon technologies, about living in a low carbon society to think it through and have

02:18:11.840 --> 02:18:16.800
[Guest 1]: it imposed by any central planner, even if we were willing to believe that central planner is

02:18:16.800 --> 02:18:22.880
[Guest 1]: benevolent. So it's back to the fundamental vocabulary of having something that is designed

02:18:22.880 --> 02:18:27.920
[Guest 1]: versus having a process of discovery. What we need around the climate transition is that process of

02:18:27.920 --> 02:18:34.560
[Guest 1]: discovery. And that's the beauty of a carbon tax, saying I recognize that this thing is a pollutant

02:18:34.560 --> 02:18:39.200
[Guest 1]: and we will keep raising taxes until we get the right carbon trajectory. But after that,

02:18:39.200 --> 02:18:44.480
[Guest 1]: have a light touch and not try to have a government that is specifying the technical

02:18:44.480 --> 02:18:50.640
[Guest 1]: detail about how society is structured. Rather, let the energy of the capitalism do it. Let the

02:18:50.640 --> 02:18:56.080
[Guest 1]: financial firms do it. Look at the way venture capital and private equity has played in the

02:18:56.080 --> 02:19:01.920
[Guest 1]: transformative changes that have taken place in renewables, in energy storage of the last 20 years.

02:19:01.920 --> 02:19:07.520
[Guest 1]: That's really the template for how this story will unfold. So we should create that process

02:19:07.520 --> 02:19:12.560
[Guest 1]: of risk taking, of making mistakes, there should be bankruptcies. Okay, and no official is going

02:19:12.560 --> 02:19:15.680
[Guest 1]: to do that risk taking where they put up some plant and then they went bankrupt.

02:19:15.680 --> 02:19:21.440
[Guest 2]: I'll give you a couple of examples. We talked a little bit earlier about not being able to

02:19:21.440 --> 02:19:27.040
[Guest 2]: sell you the electricity of my roof. But that's a bit of a rustic kind of example, but it's

02:19:27.040 --> 02:19:32.240
[Guest 2]: relatable. But it's slightly more sophisticated. You know that electricity is consumed in peaks

02:19:32.240 --> 02:19:38.960
[Guest 2]: and troughs, right? So there are times of the day where all the industries in a certain SEZ

02:19:38.960 --> 02:19:46.080
[Guest 2]: will turn on the switch on their processes. Now, in any industrial process, energy is used

02:19:46.080 --> 02:19:51.200
[Guest 2]: in a certain way. Some of it must be used at a certain time, but there are other processes which

02:19:51.200 --> 02:19:57.440
[Guest 2]: are basically sort of neutral to when that process works. So there are people who are in the business

02:19:57.440 --> 02:20:02.640
[Guest 2]: of what is called flexibility aggregation, where what they will do is they'll go to an SEZ

02:20:02.640 --> 02:20:08.560
[Guest 2]: and they'll say, okay, I'm going to place an IoT device on your process such that it will switch

02:20:08.560 --> 02:20:16.240
[Guest 2]: on the power when the price is low. And it'll turn it on and it'll also smoothen out the peak

02:20:16.240 --> 02:20:21.200
[Guest 2]: because the prices are higher when there is a peak. It'll smoothen out the peak. And because

02:20:21.200 --> 02:20:25.840
[Guest 2]: of the way that the Indian electricity sector works, this is actually a saving made by the

02:20:25.840 --> 02:20:30.560
[Guest 2]: DISCOM because the DISCOM is buying the power from various people at various different times.

02:20:32.320 --> 02:20:37.520
[Guest 2]: This business model works if this person who's doing the flexibility aggregation

02:20:37.520 --> 02:20:44.080
[Guest 2]: can share the upside with the DISCOM. So if 100 rupees is saved, he says, okay, I'll give you

02:20:44.080 --> 02:20:49.200
[Guest 2]: DISCOM, I'll give you 80, I'll keep 20, that's my profit. You can't do this deal in India today.

02:20:49.200 --> 02:20:55.120
[Guest 2]: It's not possible. You have another kind of situation where say Google says, I want to be

02:20:55.120 --> 02:21:01.680
[Guest 2]: a good corporate customer. I want you to renew power to put 100 megawatts of renewables into

02:21:01.680 --> 02:21:05.680
[Guest 2]: the grid. If you do, and you're putting it into the grid, I might not be consuming it,

02:21:05.680 --> 02:21:09.680
[Guest 2]: but you're putting it into the grid, which is being consumed more generally and an electron

02:21:09.680 --> 02:21:16.240
[Guest 2]: is an electron regardless of what the source might be. I'll pay you 3 rupees a unit for that,

02:21:16.240 --> 02:21:22.480
[Guest 2]: what you put in. If you get 3 rupees for that, fine. If you get 310, you can keep the upside or

02:21:22.480 --> 02:21:26.800
[Guest 2]: you can have an upside sharing. If you get 290, I'll pay you the difference. So this is a con

02:21:26.800 --> 02:21:30.400
[Guest 2]: and they want to do it because this is part of their mandate. They want to be a good corporate

02:21:30.400 --> 02:21:36.960
[Guest 2]: customer, etc. Their shareholders are asking for this. This becomes what is called a contract for

02:21:36.960 --> 02:21:43.600
[Guest 2]: differences and then it becomes regulated by SEBI. So there was until very recently,

02:21:43.600 --> 02:21:47.760
[Guest 2]: this transaction was illegal. Now you can say, okay, now they've made it illegal or they made

02:21:47.760 --> 02:21:52.880
[Guest 2]: it more possible. But this is deal by deal, business by business, business model by business

02:21:52.880 --> 02:21:58.400
[Guest 2]: model. You need to tweak the regulation to allow something to happen. So instead, if there are

02:21:58.400 --> 02:22:05.120
[Guest 2]: private people doing deals with private people, that's all you need because these deals and 50

02:22:05.120 --> 02:22:09.520
[Guest 2]: others, as you said, the unknown unknowns, the ones we can't even imagine at the moment, all

02:22:09.520 --> 02:22:14.320
[Guest 2]: sorts of other stuff will happen and this isn't even on the technology side. This is just on the

02:22:14.320 --> 02:22:19.440
[Guest 2]: business model side. You add technological innovation to this. Arguably, placing IoT

02:22:19.440 --> 02:22:24.400
[Guest 2]: devices is an innovation, but it's been happening for a while now. You'll have this combination of

02:22:24.400 --> 02:22:29.760
[Guest 2]: business model and technology being able to be used to deliver value. And right now, there are

02:22:29.760 --> 02:22:35.280
[Guest 2]: so many ways in which this cannot be done. And the way to solve this is not to say, okay,

02:22:35.280 --> 02:22:39.280
[Guest 2]: I'm now going to deregulate this, then I'll come up with guidelines how this is to be done.

02:22:39.280 --> 02:22:43.600
[Guest 2]: And then there will be a process of verification and you will sign up for this and whatnot,

02:22:43.600 --> 02:22:46.880
[Guest 2]: as opposed to saying just do the deal. As long as the grid isn't coming down,

02:22:46.880 --> 02:22:53.680
[Amit Varma]: I'll just take my tax on it. Fascinating. So, you know, before we go deeper into the solution,

02:22:53.680 --> 02:22:57.920
[Amit Varma]: I want to go deeper into the problem because for many of my listeners, and even for me while

02:22:57.920 --> 02:23:03.680
[Amit Varma]: reading this paper, it was great that you know, right at the start, you sort of set out first

02:23:03.680 --> 02:23:09.600
[Amit Varma]: what the problem is. And I'm going to ask you about that at two levels. One is, tell me about

02:23:09.600 --> 02:23:14.240
[Amit Varma]: the problem at the climate change level at the global level, in terms of the push towards

02:23:14.240 --> 02:23:20.800
[Amit Varma]: decarbonisation. You know, you've used in your paper, all these phrases like COP26, COP21,

02:23:20.800 --> 02:23:25.280
[Amit Varma]: Paris Accords, all of which kind of went over my head, I had to Google to figure out what's going

02:23:25.280 --> 02:23:31.680
[Amit Varma]: on. So give me, you know, a sort of a beginner's guide to this world of how people, you know,

02:23:31.680 --> 02:23:36.080
[Amit Varma]: international community is trying to mitigate climate change. And after that, we can talk about

02:23:36.080 --> 02:23:41.120
[Amit Varma]: the scenario in India, what's wrong, the central planning, what's wrong at the level of discoms,

02:23:41.120 --> 02:23:45.360
[Amit Varma]: what's wrong at the level of the incentives for the private players, and how that changes

02:23:45.360 --> 02:23:49.200
[Amit Varma]: because of the international environment. But first, I just want to understand that broader

02:23:49.200 --> 02:23:53.920
[Amit Varma]: subject a little better, that, you know, what are the efforts that have been made, you know,

02:23:53.920 --> 02:23:58.080
[Amit Varma]: you've spoken of our Prime Minister, you know, making different kinds of commitments and different

02:23:58.080 --> 02:24:02.720
[Amit Varma]: kinds of forum and all that. Give me a sense of what is the problem in terms of carbon emissions

02:24:02.720 --> 02:24:08.560
[Amit Varma]: and whatever, and what are the different mitigating steps that have been taken? And you know, where's

02:24:08.560 --> 02:24:11.520
[Amit Varma]: India in that scheme of things? And what is the challenge before us?

02:24:11.520 --> 02:24:18.960
[Guest 2]: Well, you know, not wanting to go too back into the past, but 1992 is an important date,

02:24:18.960 --> 02:24:23.680
[Guest 2]: because of the Rio Climate Change Convention, where the world decided that this problem that

02:24:24.640 --> 02:24:29.840
[Guest 2]: everyone knew existed needed a concerted, cooperative international solution. And

02:24:30.720 --> 02:24:35.760
[Guest 2]: for that was followed by the Kyoto Protocol a few years later, which put into place certain

02:24:35.760 --> 02:24:42.800
[Guest 2]: mechanisms to try and reduce the problem of carbon emissions into the atmosphere.

02:24:43.440 --> 02:24:49.120
[Guest 2]: And they were financing mechanisms, they were cap and trade mechanisms that were suggested,

02:24:49.120 --> 02:24:53.440
[Guest 2]: there were various different types of mechanisms internationally that were

02:24:53.440 --> 02:24:58.960
[Guest 2]: suggested to address the issue. Now, that whole process, the COP is the conference of the parties,

02:24:58.960 --> 02:25:04.720
[Guest 2]: it's the conference of the parties of the original Rio Convention. And COP26 is just the 26th one,

02:25:04.720 --> 02:25:11.760
[Guest 2]: which we just had at Glasgow last year. Cutting a slightly long story short, there was an intense

02:25:11.760 --> 02:25:17.280
[Guest 2]: amount of negotiation that led up to COP21. And what's known as the Paris Agreement, where

02:25:17.280 --> 02:25:22.560
[Guest 2]: people said, look, we have to now arrest climate change at no more than two degrees this century.

02:25:22.560 --> 02:25:28.880
[Guest 2]: And we ideally have to do that, ideally, it should be 1.5 degrees. And that not only that,

02:25:28.880 --> 02:25:35.840
[Guest 2]: but that the world in that historically, the and even at, you know, in today's levels,

02:25:35.840 --> 02:25:40.480
[Guest 2]: most of the of the pollution of the carbon has been generated by the developed countries.

02:25:40.480 --> 02:25:44.960
[Guest 2]: And it's not fair for the developing countries that they be asked to stop their path of

02:25:44.960 --> 02:25:48.960
[Guest 2]: development, the path of development that has led to wealth creation in the West,

02:25:48.960 --> 02:25:55.200
[Guest 2]: stop that in order to solve this global problem. So, the burden disproportionately is falling on

02:25:55.200 --> 02:26:00.320
[Guest 2]: the poorer countries. So, they came up with this, the principle of common but differentiated

02:26:00.320 --> 02:26:06.240
[Guest 2]: responsibilities, in accordance with your ability to say that this principle already existed,

02:26:06.240 --> 02:26:12.480
[Guest 2]: but it took the mechanism to say they will actually be transfers of technology and transfers of

02:26:12.480 --> 02:26:18.400
[Guest 2]: finance from the developed world to the developing world in order to make this happen. Now, the

02:26:18.400 --> 02:26:23.920
[Guest 2]: number that was talked about was 100 billion a year. To be fair, the West has been abysmal in

02:26:23.920 --> 02:26:28.720
[Guest 2]: fulfilling that commitment. And it's not always been completely clear how much of that is coming

02:26:28.720 --> 02:26:33.520
[Guest 2]: from private sources, how much of that is coming from G2G, government to government sources.

02:26:33.520 --> 02:26:38.080
[Guest 2]: So, are governments going to give the money or are private companies going to be involved in

02:26:38.080 --> 02:26:43.200
[Guest 2]: making these investments? You know, my view is that this is not going to come from governments,

02:26:43.200 --> 02:26:47.600
[Guest 2]: it's going to come from, you know, private companies. And India is very well placed to

02:26:47.600 --> 02:26:51.200
[Guest 2]: receive a lot of these investments, because the dollar of investment that will come there

02:26:51.200 --> 02:26:58.080
[Guest 2]: will get you arguably more mitigation of CO2 in India, because it's cheaper than it would in the

02:26:58.080 --> 02:27:05.440
[Guest 2]: West. But we don't have an investable power sector, or we don't have a sufficiently investable power

02:27:05.440 --> 02:27:11.600
[Guest 2]: sector. So, that's the link. But going back to the Paris Agreement, the mechanisms in the Paris

02:27:11.600 --> 02:27:17.760
[Guest 2]: Agreement that were put into place, as I said, haven't been followed through. So, in COP26,

02:27:17.760 --> 02:27:24.720
[Guest 2]: renewed commitments were made to say we will come to net zero emissions by, the date has been 2050,

02:27:24.720 --> 02:27:31.600
[Guest 2]: by net zero emissions by 2050. And this was discussed even earlier in COP21 and following

02:27:31.600 --> 02:27:37.280
[Guest 2]: that. And to come in and to get as many countries as possible to make specific commitments in

02:27:37.280 --> 02:27:42.320
[Guest 2]: relation to getting to that. So, that's where, you know, our Prime Minister went and said,

02:27:42.320 --> 02:27:49.760
[Guest 2]: we will do this by 2070. And we will also make sure that by 2030, that we have 40%

02:27:49.760 --> 02:27:55.040
[Guest 2]: renewable installed capacity, that emissions intensity is brought down by 40%, all of that

02:27:55.040 --> 02:28:01.120
[Guest 2]: sort of thing. So, that's where the world is right now. Now, there's this tension between the fact

02:28:01.120 --> 02:28:07.200
[Guest 2]: that there is this noble objective, which is an existential threat, frankly, you know, I think

02:28:07.200 --> 02:28:12.080
[Guest 2]: people should be having sleepless nights about this, which is what originally led Ajay to ask

02:28:12.080 --> 02:28:16.640
[Guest 2]: me the question to say, you know, what are you, are you worried about this? And I said, yes.

02:28:17.840 --> 02:28:24.880
[Guest 2]: So, that's where the world is at the moment. And what India's, India's in this position where we

02:28:24.880 --> 02:28:30.640
[Guest 2]: have a reasonably, decently growing renewable energy sector, although it's a drop in the ocean

02:28:30.640 --> 02:28:36.960
[Guest 2]: in terms of what we get in terms of international investment to just give you one set of numbers

02:28:36.960 --> 02:28:44.400
[Guest 2]: in 2020. And there'll be new numbers out for 2021. And 2020, it was the second best year ever for

02:28:44.400 --> 02:28:50.960
[Guest 2]: renewable energy investment worldwide, despite the pandemic. It's about 300 billion, 86 billion,

02:28:50.960 --> 02:28:57.200
[Guest 2]: approximately in the EU, a similar number in China, and India got 6 billion of that.

02:28:57.200 --> 02:29:02.640
[Guest 2]: And this is not just foreign investment, this is domestic and foreign. So, 6 billion is a big

02:29:02.640 --> 02:29:06.240
[Guest 2]: number. And we talk about how well our sector is doing and all of that, but it's a drop in the

02:29:06.240 --> 02:29:12.480
[Guest 2]: ocean in terms of what's happening elsewhere and what could happen in India. So, we are well placed

02:29:12.480 --> 02:29:18.160
[Guest 2]: to get much more investment provided we have a more investable sector. And that's where we are

02:29:18.160 --> 02:29:24.400
[Amit Varma]: at the moment. And, you know, as we proceed, I just, you know, people keep sort of telling me

02:29:24.400 --> 02:29:28.800
[Amit Varma]: to do episodes on climate change and all that, which I haven't done yet, because partly because

02:29:29.520 --> 02:29:33.280
[Amit Varma]: there's just so much information that I'd have to take in just to prep for it that I

02:29:33.280 --> 02:29:39.120
[Amit Varma]: haven't bothered starting. But I just like to sort of point out my perspective on it, which I think

02:29:39.120 --> 02:29:43.600
[Amit Varma]: you guys would broadly share, tell me if you do or not, which is that, number one, you know, I of

02:29:43.600 --> 02:29:47.440
[Amit Varma]: course, have no time for deniers, climate change is a real thing, it's caused by humans, and we

02:29:47.440 --> 02:29:52.800
[Amit Varma]: have to do something about it. At the same time, I'm a little skeptical of some of the more alarmist

02:29:52.800 --> 02:29:58.080
[Amit Varma]: scenarios out there, partly because they come from forces which are incentivized to be as

02:29:58.080 --> 02:30:03.520
[Amit Varma]: alarmist as possible. And we have seen that alarmists of the past have invariably been wrong.

02:30:03.520 --> 02:30:07.840
[Amit Varma]: So having said that, where is the line in between where I stand? I don't know. But my

02:30:07.840 --> 02:30:12.960
[Amit Varma]: stance would be that it's, you know, the climate change is real, it's going to affect us,

02:30:12.960 --> 02:30:19.360
[Amit Varma]: we need to, you know, do things about it. And I'm broadly optimistic that given the right incentives,

02:30:19.360 --> 02:30:24.800
[Amit Varma]: that we are, you know, resourceful and innovative enough to find our way out of it, you know, and

02:30:24.800 --> 02:30:29.040
[Amit Varma]: to get away from fossil fuels as we have in the past. I mean, you look at the history of humanity,

02:30:29.040 --> 02:30:35.280
[Amit Varma]: we used to rely on water for energy, on wood for energy, on coal for energy, at various things,

02:30:35.280 --> 02:30:40.560
[Amit Varma]: you put the right incentives in place, and you move away. So because of human ingenuity, no

02:30:40.560 --> 02:30:46.000
[Amit Varma]: matter how real climate change is, I am kind of optimistic. But at the same time, when we look at,

02:30:46.000 --> 02:30:49.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, the difficulty of getting these incentives in place, which is partly what your

02:30:49.440 --> 02:30:54.960
[Amit Varma]: paper is about, you know, that kind of makes me wonder and think about the urgency and the

02:30:54.960 --> 02:30:59.920
[Amit Varma]: necessity to, you know, get that in place right away. So broadly, would you sort of agree with

02:30:59.920 --> 02:31:02.720
[Amit Varma]: my summation, which comes from a non expert place?

02:31:02.720 --> 02:31:09.040
[Guest 1]: I would like to put three things into this reasoning. The first is that I am very worried

02:31:09.040 --> 02:31:17.120
[Guest 1]: about the imprecision of climate modeling. So I think that we are all acting as if there is a

02:31:17.120 --> 02:31:24.000
[Guest 1]: truth and we are able to make good forecasts using modern atmospheric models that peer into 2050 and

02:31:24.000 --> 02:31:31.120
[Guest 1]: 2100. I feel that the state of human knowledge is much weaker than that. Also, perhaps because of

02:31:31.120 --> 02:31:37.360
[Guest 1]: nonlinear science, that level of future is unknowable. There is a possibility of tipping

02:31:37.360 --> 02:31:43.200
[Guest 1]: points of feedback loops developing. So as an example, a famous feedback loop that we should

02:31:43.200 --> 02:31:47.760
[Guest 1]: be thinking about is that a lot of the sunlight that's coming in the northern hemisphere because

02:31:47.760 --> 02:31:52.480
[Guest 1]: of the angle of the earth, a lot of the sunlight that comes in the northern hemisphere reflects off

02:31:52.480 --> 02:32:00.000
[Guest 1]: this ice. Now, when the permafrost starts melting, the color turns from white to either green or

02:32:00.000 --> 02:32:07.120
[Guest 1]: brown, and then it absorbs more. So once warming commences, the earth absorbs more and that gives

02:32:07.120 --> 02:32:12.560
[Guest 1]: you a vicious cycle. It gives you a feedback loop that the warmer you are, the warmer you become.

02:32:12.560 --> 02:32:19.680
[Guest 1]: The rate of change of heating goes up and the level of climate science is primitive when faced

02:32:19.680 --> 02:32:25.760
[Guest 1]: with this level of complexity. So as a card-carrying quantitative researcher, I am very worried about

02:32:25.760 --> 02:32:31.200
[Guest 1]: the level of imprecision of the global state of the art models. We only dimly understand this. So

02:32:31.200 --> 02:32:36.560
[Guest 1]: the models are good and useful as illustrations. So just like you would not take macroeconomic

02:32:36.560 --> 02:32:41.520
[Guest 1]: modeling seriously, macroeconomic modeling is not intended to be used as a realistic, careful,

02:32:41.520 --> 02:32:46.160
[Guest 1]: meaningful forecast of what's going to happen in the next 10 years. It's illustrative. It builds

02:32:46.160 --> 02:32:51.920
[Guest 1]: intuition. In that case, we should be very worried because there can well be a class of events which

02:32:51.920 --> 02:32:57.760
[Guest 1]: comes together and gives us pretty bad dramatic change. Maybe not Hollywood movie versions,

02:32:57.760 --> 02:33:02.160
[Amit Varma]: but pretty gruesome stuff. So that's the first point. I mean, I buy that. But just to sort of

02:33:02.160 --> 02:33:06.960
[Amit Varma]: the models that we've seen in the past have often been wrong and they've often been wrong to the

02:33:06.960 --> 02:33:11.200
[Amit Varma]: extent of being too alarmist. They haven't actually been borne out to that extent by history.

02:33:11.200 --> 02:33:15.600
[Guest 1]: Now you have to think like a risk manager, that what are the scenarios we think about? What are

02:33:15.600 --> 02:33:20.160
[Guest 1]: those probabilities? Can we do things that will rule out really bad scenarios? Okay, we all pay

02:33:20.160 --> 02:33:23.600
[Guest 1]: a certain price. So, you know, imagine there is an asteroid out there that's going to slam

02:33:23.600 --> 02:33:28.000
[Guest 1]: into the earth. We'd be willing to put in some amount of resource to buy insurance against that.

02:33:28.000 --> 02:33:28.400
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

02:33:28.400 --> 02:33:33.920
[Guest 1]: We should think of this field in that risk manager's way. And I just want to say to everybody

02:33:33.920 --> 02:33:39.360
[Guest 1]: who's listening that don't believe the climate models that you see because this stuff is too hard.

02:33:39.360 --> 02:33:45.360
[Guest 1]: And, you know, it is beyond human and scientific genius to make precise claims about 50 years out

02:33:45.360 --> 02:33:49.840
[Guest 1]: and 100 years out. These systems are too complex. My second point is I agree with everything you

02:33:49.840 --> 02:33:55.440
[Guest 1]: said about incentives. And those incentives are created and shaped by states. And that's where

02:33:55.440 --> 02:34:00.400
[Guest 1]: we hit the problem, which is that there's a free rider problem here. Any one country finds it

02:34:00.400 --> 02:34:05.680
[Guest 1]: efficient to emit and it is monumentally difficult for all the countries of the world to agree.

02:34:05.680 --> 02:34:10.720
[Guest 1]: There's an incentive for every one country to cheat. And it's hard to find enforcement mechanisms

02:34:10.720 --> 02:34:16.320
[Guest 1]: that will bring people together. My third concern runs on climate mitigation. So,

02:34:17.200 --> 02:34:25.040
[Guest 1]: let's play the game that we've lost the game and the temperatures have started going up and the

02:34:25.040 --> 02:34:32.240
[Guest 1]: seas have started rising and climate patterns change substantially. Now the game will turn

02:34:32.240 --> 02:34:37.200
[Guest 1]: on state capacity and state capability. So, you know, if I was Germany, I'd be reasonably optimistic.

02:34:37.200 --> 02:34:41.600
[Guest 1]: I mean, I know they had some really incredibly terrible floods recently, but by and large,

02:34:41.600 --> 02:34:46.720
[Guest 1]: if I'm Germany, I'd be reasonably optimistic that they'd be able to grapple with a changing world

02:34:46.720 --> 02:34:53.920
[Guest 1]: and think about it. And I worry the most about a place like India, where the Indian state is beset

02:34:53.920 --> 02:34:59.040
[Guest 1]: with a large number of problems, is only dimly able to grapple with all the difficulties that

02:34:59.040 --> 02:35:05.040
[Guest 1]: are going on. And these difficulties will be dealt with badly. It could lead to high levels of social

02:35:05.040 --> 02:35:12.960
[Guest 1]: stress and unhappy outcomes. I worry that significant parts of India will become outright

02:35:12.960 --> 02:35:20.640
[Guest 1]: uninhabitable. So just a little anecdote last year, I think, yeah, in 2020 or 2021, the temperature

02:35:20.640 --> 02:35:26.080
[Guest 1]: in Jacobabad, which is in Sindh, went up to 52 degrees. And there was an article in the Guardian

02:35:26.080 --> 02:35:30.080
[Guest 1]: about this, where there was a sentence that just struck me. The sentence was that this is like a

02:35:30.080 --> 02:35:37.120
[Guest 1]: lockdown, that nobody steps out of the house when the temperature goes to 52C. Well, we should worry

02:35:37.120 --> 02:35:44.000
[Guest 1]: about parts of our, you know, the Indian interior, the Hindi heartland, where under conditions of

02:35:44.000 --> 02:35:50.240
[Guest 1]: significant increase in global temperatures, we will get heat waves, we will get the destruction

02:35:50.240 --> 02:35:56.560
[Guest 1]: of economic activity comparable to a lockdown when those heat waves happen. The present

02:35:56.560 --> 02:36:01.760
[Guest 1]: distribution of population in India is shaped by the benign climate of the last 5000 years.

02:36:02.720 --> 02:36:08.400
[Guest 1]: When climate change takes place and the patterns of rainfall and peak temperature change, we will

02:36:08.960 --> 02:36:13.600
[Guest 1]: really be down to only one answer, which is population movements of hundreds of millions

02:36:13.600 --> 02:36:18.800
[Guest 1]: of people. And that straightaway should set off alarm bells that given the difficulties of Indian

02:36:18.800 --> 02:36:22.640
[Guest 1]: society, we don't have a working land market, people will be stuck to the land because they

02:36:22.640 --> 02:36:27.440
[Guest 1]: won't sell the land, there'll be refugees, the recipient states will have nativism, you know.

02:36:27.440 --> 02:36:35.360
[Guest 1]: So juxtaposing the welfare consequences of significant climate change upon Indian society

02:36:35.360 --> 02:36:42.640
[Guest 1]: and the weaknesses of Indian state capacity is not pretty. So this is why this field is important.

02:36:42.640 --> 02:36:46.000
[Guest 1]: And, you know, we should apply our minds and think about how best to play this.

02:36:46.000 --> 02:36:51.920
[Guest 2]: I'll just add that if you were to trawl through all the articles and papers that have been written

02:36:51.920 --> 02:36:59.520
[Guest 2]: in the last 10-15 years on this issue, there aren't a lot of them that say, oh, we were wrong

02:36:59.520 --> 02:37:04.560
[Guest 2]: and the numbers aren't as bad as they were. Most of them were saying warming is a little more than

02:37:04.560 --> 02:37:12.560
[Guest 2]: expected. The permafrost isn't as thick as we thought. You know, this is impressionistic,

02:37:12.560 --> 02:37:19.200
[Guest 2]: but the view I have of the science on this, the science hasn't been wrong. And that's one point.

02:37:19.200 --> 02:37:25.120
[Guest 2]: And linked to that is the fact that it is an existential threat. It's not that if we get it

02:37:25.120 --> 02:37:30.640
[Guest 2]: wrong, then we'll pick ourselves up and we'll do something. But the stakes are too high in

02:37:30.640 --> 02:37:39.040
[Guest 2]: some ways for us to take a more optimistic view of what the 95% of the scientists in the world are

02:37:39.040 --> 02:37:45.600
[Guest 2]: saying. I would take a more pessimistic view of that because it will pay to be risk averse.

02:37:46.640 --> 02:37:53.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, I agree with that. But the thing is that 95% is also not arriving at a homogenous

02:37:53.040 --> 02:37:58.000
[Amit Varma]: place like Nordhaus who won the Nobel Prize for economics for just climate science also disagrees

02:37:58.000 --> 02:38:02.400
[Amit Varma]: with a lot of the alarmism. If you look at, for example, the projections made in Al Gore's film,

02:38:02.400 --> 02:38:08.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, most of them turned out not to happen, turned out, you know, but where I agree with you

02:38:08.880 --> 02:38:14.480
[Amit Varma]: is that this is an extremely low probability event that the Hollywood film happens and the

02:38:14.480 --> 02:38:19.600
[Amit Varma]: world goes to hell. But even if it's a low probability event, the impact is so high that

02:38:19.600 --> 02:38:24.000
[Amit Varma]: we should do something about it. Now, where people would get skeptical is say that sure,

02:38:24.000 --> 02:38:28.480
[Amit Varma]: we should do something about it. But even if you buy insurance, how high is the cost of that

02:38:28.480 --> 02:38:33.840
[Amit Varma]: insurance? And where your paper gives me hope is that the cost need not be that high. You put the

02:38:33.840 --> 02:38:38.560
[Amit Varma]: right systems and incentives in place and we should be moving out of fossil fuels anyway,

02:38:38.560 --> 02:38:44.400
[Amit Varma]: right, regardless of alarmism or not. Where it gives me hope is that the cost need not be that

02:38:44.400 --> 02:38:50.800
[Amit Varma]: high. Even a developing country like India can move out of it and can flourish and can mitigate

02:38:50.800 --> 02:38:56.400
[Guest 2]: the damage, right? The frustration here is that there are many positive sum games to be had.

02:38:56.400 --> 02:39:01.200
[Guest 2]: Exactly. And which is what we, you know, point out in the paper when we in the part where we

02:39:01.200 --> 02:39:06.560
[Guest 2]: talk about why this is the right time for this, because the way that international relations,

02:39:06.560 --> 02:39:11.360
[Guest 2]: way that international investment, the way that what the West is saying about carbon border taxes,

02:39:11.360 --> 02:39:15.600
[Guest 2]: all of these, you line these sorts of things up, and there couldn't have been a better time

02:39:15.600 --> 02:39:21.280
[Guest 2]: to do this. I mean, what I'd really like to see have happened is a conversation between Biden and

02:39:21.280 --> 02:39:28.560
[Guest 2]: Modi, where Biden comes and says, you know, where are your numbers? Give me your exact pathway to

02:39:28.560 --> 02:39:33.280
[Guest 2]: achieve net zero. And Modi says, but you haven't given us enough money for this,

02:39:33.280 --> 02:39:37.600
[Guest 2]: because you haven't fulfilled your commitments under the climate accords. And Biden says,

02:39:37.600 --> 02:39:41.760
[Guest 2]: oh, yes, but we'll give you money, but you reform your power sector to electricity sector to make

02:39:41.760 --> 02:39:46.000
[Guest 2]: it more investable. And Modi says, yes, okay, we'll do it. Because these are all good things

02:39:46.000 --> 02:39:50.480
[Guest 2]: for everybody. This conversation is a good conversation to be had at some level. But

02:39:50.480 --> 02:39:54.800
[Guest 2]: that's not the conversation that's being had for a variety of reasons. And that's a whole other

02:39:54.800 --> 02:40:02.960
[Guest 2]: story. But what we should be doing is to say, and because it's beneficial for our power sector

02:40:02.960 --> 02:40:08.560
[Guest 2]: itself, and we've talked extensively, and everybody's talked about how much debt there

02:40:08.560 --> 02:40:14.800
[Guest 2]: is in the distribution companies and how bankrupt they are, to sort that problem out is a good

02:40:14.800 --> 02:40:21.360
[Guest 2]: problem irrespective of the climate transition. But it also makes the climate transition more

02:40:21.360 --> 02:40:28.800
[Guest 2]: feasible. So, this is a virtuous cycle that we need to find a way to spin into. And we are failing

02:40:28.800 --> 02:40:34.000
[Guest 2]: to do this because we are still captured within the concept of doing this within the state system.

02:40:34.560 --> 02:40:40.080
[Amit Varma]: So, let's dig deep into that then and double click on the state system. You know, what is

02:40:40.080 --> 02:40:45.600
[Amit Varma]: wrong with the way the electricity is organized? I mean, the third chapter of your paper lays this

02:40:45.600 --> 02:40:51.600
[Amit Varma]: out in absolutely tremendous detail. So, tell me a little bit about, you know, what is the scene

02:40:51.600 --> 02:40:56.640
[Amit Varma]: now? One, there is a mindset problem, the whole central planning thing that the state has to

02:40:56.640 --> 02:41:01.840
[Amit Varma]: control everything and so on and so forth. But going a little deeper, you know, what are the

02:41:01.840 --> 02:41:07.520
[Guest 1]: different variety of problems that we are faced with? He will have a better narration about those

02:41:07.520 --> 02:41:15.200
[Guest 1]: problems in a practical way. In a more conceptual way, I think two things. The first is that the

02:41:16.160 --> 02:41:22.400
[Guest 1]: central planning is the problem that the Indian electricity system is largely controlled by

02:41:22.400 --> 02:41:27.040
[Guest 1]: officials. There are bureaucrats, there are officials who make a vast amount of resource

02:41:27.040 --> 02:41:31.840
[Guest 1]: allocation decisions, who make decisions pertaining to products and processes. And

02:41:31.840 --> 02:41:36.480
[Guest 1]: there is a lack of a price system. There are no prices that fluctuate. There are no price signals.

02:41:37.040 --> 02:41:41.360
[Guest 1]: Risk taking doesn't happen. Entrepreneurship doesn't happen because everything is controlled

02:41:41.360 --> 02:41:48.240
[Guest 1]: by the Mayabab. That's one way to think about what is broken. And the other element to think

02:41:48.240 --> 02:41:56.080
[Guest 1]: about what is broken is that there is this great streak by the government where electricity gets

02:41:56.080 --> 02:42:03.040
[Guest 1]: sold to different people at different prices. And that's just a fundamental flaw in the arrangement.

02:42:03.040 --> 02:42:08.640
[Guest 1]: There are people who legally get electricity for free. There are people who steal electricity and

02:42:08.640 --> 02:42:12.960
[Guest 1]: the government acquiesces. In the paper, I think we have an example of Tamil Nadu,

02:42:12.960 --> 02:42:17.680
[Guest 1]: where there are 22 different prices for electricity. And that's just no way to get

02:42:17.680 --> 02:42:22.720
[Guest 1]: a sound resource allocation. So, there's just so much redistributive politics that has been

02:42:22.720 --> 02:42:31.120
[Guest 1]: tied into the electricity sector. The electricity sector has become the land on which the redistributive

02:42:31.120 --> 02:42:37.040
[Guest 1]: political fight is being played out. And that is very detrimental to the possibility of a sound

02:42:37.040 --> 02:42:41.600
[Guest 1]: resource allocation in the electricity sector. So, there's this mixture of government control,

02:42:41.600 --> 02:42:45.840
[Guest 1]: and then the abuse of government control for political ends. I mean, hypothetically,

02:42:45.840 --> 02:42:50.720
[Guest 1]: if the government controlled the bread industry in the same fashion, you'd have had the same

02:42:50.720 --> 02:42:55.200
[Guest 1]: bad outcome. You'd have 20 different prices of bread, bread factories would be inefficient,

02:42:55.200 --> 02:43:00.640
[Guest 1]: and there'd be 500 bureaucrats all over the country who'd be the thinkers on bread,

02:43:00.640 --> 02:43:04.240
[Guest 1]: and they'd be thinking more centrally planned solutions to the problems of bread.

02:43:06.720 --> 02:43:13.360
[Guest 2]: Yeah, and it stems from the fact that, you know, we've done some reform. We got a new act in 2003,

02:43:13.360 --> 02:43:18.160
[Guest 2]: which basically unbundled transmission and distribution and generation, put them into

02:43:18.160 --> 02:43:22.640
[Guest 2]: different government owned companies, and then said, okay, private guys, come, please come and

02:43:22.640 --> 02:43:28.080
[Guest 2]: generate electricity. So, we bolted on private generation to effectively a state system.

02:43:28.080 --> 02:43:33.760
[Guest 2]: But who am I selling to? I'm selling to a government company. There are a few that are

02:43:33.760 --> 02:43:38.320
[Guest 2]: now private, Delhi, Bombay, Calcutta, and one or two others. But they're basically every, you know,

02:43:38.320 --> 02:43:45.440
[Guest 2]: vast majority of them are owned by the government. They are busy fulfilling redistribution through

02:43:45.440 --> 02:43:49.760
[Guest 2]: subsidies, which go through the distribution companies very often, or they are supposed to be

02:43:49.760 --> 02:43:54.640
[Guest 2]: funded by the state, the state doesn't fund them. And then the state can, you know, the state doesn't

02:43:54.640 --> 02:43:59.600
[Guest 2]: fund them, the distribution company will still give the subsidy, but it won't pay the guys who

02:43:59.600 --> 02:44:06.320
[Guest 2]: are supplying power to it, because they're not voting. Right? So, that whole structure,

02:44:07.120 --> 02:44:12.000
[Guest 2]: the argument there is to say, you want to pay a subsidy, that's a perfectly reasonable

02:44:12.000 --> 02:44:18.240
[Guest 2]: redistributive goal of the state if it wants to have it. But don't make the distribution company

02:44:18.240 --> 02:44:23.040
[Guest 2]: do it. It's there to produce power and to sell it and to make money, even in the public sector.

02:44:23.840 --> 02:44:29.360
[Guest 2]: But the idea that electricity is a public good somehow, that it should be given for free is what

02:44:29.360 --> 02:44:34.720
[Guest 2]: still permeates over here. That's one. The fact that that's what makes them bankrupt. What makes

02:44:34.720 --> 02:44:42.080
[Guest 2]: them bankrupt, it makes them a bad contracting counterparty. They cannot give payment security.

02:44:42.080 --> 02:44:48.320
[Guest 2]: If they give payment security, they don't honour it. There are strictures on distribution companies

02:44:48.320 --> 02:44:53.920
[Guest 2]: to issue letters of credit and they don't. And they just don't. So, what's the consequence to

02:44:53.920 --> 02:44:59.120
[Guest 2]: a babu if they don't do that? In any case, it's not the babu's decision. The babu is being told

02:44:59.120 --> 02:45:05.200
[Guest 2]: by someone higher up the chain, don't do this. There is a state today, which I will not mention,

02:45:05.200 --> 02:45:14.480
[Guest 2]: the name of, where many people have not been paid on various contracts for months and now people

02:45:14.480 --> 02:45:19.600
[Guest 2]: are being paid depending on what kind of influence they are willing to wield in a state that should

02:45:19.600 --> 02:45:25.520
[Guest 2]: be doing a lot better than that. Now, why is this possible? It's possible because that company is

02:45:25.520 --> 02:45:31.520
[Guest 2]: owned by the government. That is a private guy, that would never happen. Then you have a situation

02:45:31.520 --> 02:45:38.640
[Guest 2]: where the contracts are handed down. So, the DISCOM in Maharashtra, not in Bombay because

02:45:38.640 --> 02:45:46.800
[Guest 2]: that's private, but MACDCL wants to procure power. It will say 200 megawatts of solar.

02:45:46.800 --> 02:45:51.520
[Guest 2]: It will put out a tender with a contract. The contract is sitting there. You don't have the

02:45:51.520 --> 02:45:56.800
[Guest 2]: chance to negotiate it. And the risk allocation in the contract is what some set of babus have

02:45:56.800 --> 02:46:00.480
[Guest 2]: decided it's going to be, which is obviously going to be risk averse for the government.

02:46:01.040 --> 02:46:06.960
[Guest 2]: Not only because they believe that you are doing us, we are doing you a favor by doing this,

02:46:06.960 --> 02:46:11.440
[Guest 2]: but also because if the terms of that contract are more balanced, they feel that questions will

02:46:11.440 --> 02:46:15.520
[Guest 2]: be raised internally saying, you have been bought out by the private sector.

02:46:15.520 --> 02:46:21.920
[Guest 2]: So, your contract terms aren't fair. Even where there is a contract term that is in favor of the

02:46:21.920 --> 02:46:27.600
[Guest 2]: private guy, there's a change in law. There's suddenly a GST that comes in. The GST that comes

02:46:27.600 --> 02:46:33.120
[Guest 2]: in now down the chain is increasing the price of power that this guy, what it's costing him

02:46:33.120 --> 02:46:38.560
[Guest 2]: to generate power. That entitles you to go and claim relief and get a higher tariff

02:46:39.520 --> 02:46:44.800
[Guest 2]: under the contract. But that will be contested, it will be litigated, sometimes all the time,

02:46:44.800 --> 02:46:49.360
[Guest 2]: sometimes all the way to the Supreme Court because again, there is no instinct to honor

02:46:49.360 --> 02:46:53.360
[Guest 2]: contracts and there's a fear that vigilance will come after me if I pay out money.

02:46:54.880 --> 02:47:01.920
[Guest 2]: So, you have this whole series of issues which all then, and this was sort of my learning process

02:47:01.920 --> 02:47:06.560
[Guest 2]: in saying, okay, the system itself needs to change and we need deep privatization,

02:47:06.560 --> 02:47:11.360
[Guest 2]: is that you trace each one of these issues back and it comes from the fact that there's either

02:47:11.360 --> 02:47:17.600
[Guest 2]: state bullying or there's lack of incentives to do the right thing, whether it's to draft a

02:47:17.600 --> 02:47:24.080
[Guest 2]: contract which has got a good balance of risk. Take land, for example. If there's a contract

02:47:24.080 --> 02:47:29.120
[Guest 2]: with a state entity, the state entity is much better placed to organize the land than a private

02:47:29.120 --> 02:47:34.640
[Guest 2]: guy who's to go and get commissions, approvals, hua nahi hua. But that's not what happens, right?

02:47:34.640 --> 02:47:41.200
[Guest 2]: It happens now to a limited extent. So, the issue really is, these issues, either what you're going

02:47:41.200 --> 02:47:48.160
[Guest 2]: to have is that the state reforms and becomes, has an epiphany and decides that it's going to be

02:47:48.160 --> 02:47:54.560
[Guest 2]: the best contracting counterparty that it could be, be fair, etc. Or you have to sell all these

02:47:54.560 --> 02:48:00.960
[Guest 2]: discoms. Which do you think is more likely to bring a result? Which brings us to the title of

02:48:00.960 --> 02:48:04.960
[Guest 2]: the paper, it's the lowest hanging fruit on the coconut tree. All solutions are hard.

02:48:05.760 --> 02:48:09.040
[Amit Varma]: This is possibly a little less hard. So, a couple of things strike me. One is,

02:48:09.040 --> 02:48:13.360
[Amit Varma]: I don't know which state you had in mind, but I saw a couple of news items over the

02:48:13.360 --> 02:48:17.280
[Amit Varma]: last two days. And we are, of course, recording this on Feb 18th. It will broadcast a long time

02:48:17.280 --> 02:48:22.240
[Amit Varma]: later, I think. But a couple of news items recently, one is Amit Shah saying while campaigning

02:48:22.240 --> 02:48:26.320
[Amit Varma]: in UP that, hey, if we come to power, free electricity for farmers for five years.

02:48:26.320 --> 02:48:31.920
[Amit Varma]: And the other was Punjab, just the day before, berating Amarinder Singh and saying the reason

02:48:31.920 --> 02:48:36.400
[Amit Varma]: that you guys don't have free power is that I told Amarinder, give them free power. And Amarinder

02:48:36.400 --> 02:48:40.480
[Amit Varma]: said that no, no, there are contracts we have to honour with all these people. And that is why you

02:48:40.480 --> 02:48:45.200
[Amit Varma]: don't have it, you know, as if it is a bad thing to honour contracts, which kind of blew my mind.

02:48:45.840 --> 02:48:49.840
[Guest 2]: Should blow your mind slightly more. I mean, once it's blown, it's blown. So, it can actually get

02:48:49.840 --> 02:48:56.560
[Guest 2]: blown more. But what I'll throw into the mix there is that in Punjab itself, a few months ago,

02:48:56.560 --> 02:49:02.560
[Guest 2]: the Punjab government passed a law, which went through, which was unanimously passed in the

02:49:02.560 --> 02:49:07.680
[Guest 2]: legislature. This is not just government action or one party, passed a law saying,

02:49:07.680 --> 02:49:14.080
[Guest 2]: we are going to redo the tariff clauses of all the power purchase agreements in the state,

02:49:14.080 --> 02:49:19.760
[Guest 2]: because power is too expensive. This is causing a burden on the population. And it's causing a

02:49:19.760 --> 02:49:27.920
[Guest 2]: burden on the state-owned companies. And referred all these clauses to the regulator to say revisit

02:49:27.920 --> 02:49:33.600
[Guest 2]: these and come up with a price. Some of these contracts, Amit, are bid, they are not negotiated.

02:49:33.600 --> 02:49:39.520
[Guest 2]: The government puts out a bid and the lowest bid wins. So, this somebody has invested whatever

02:49:39.520 --> 02:49:43.680
[Guest 2]: they have on the basis of getting a certain return. But because there are elections around

02:49:43.680 --> 02:49:48.480
[Guest 2]: the corner, we will not only cancel these contracts, but we will put in a law to do it.

02:49:49.040 --> 02:49:54.240
[Guest 2]: Because what Andhra Pradesh did some time ago was to refer the matter to the commission,

02:49:54.240 --> 02:49:59.200
[Guest 2]: said take a look and see if you can reduce the tariffs. This case went to the Supreme Court and

02:49:59.200 --> 02:50:04.080
[Guest 2]: the Supreme Court has now said, no, you can't do that. You've signed contracts. But what Punjab

02:50:04.080 --> 02:50:09.280
[Guest 2]: did was one step further, they said, we know that this is going on in the Andhra case, where they've

02:50:09.280 --> 02:50:16.320
[Guest 2]: referred it to them. Let's just pass a law because law is law. We'll change the contract, we'll change

02:50:16.320 --> 02:50:21.840
[Guest 2]: the law. In doing so, they have violated the constitution. They have violated the contracts.

02:50:21.840 --> 02:50:27.760
[Guest 2]: And forget about, you know, what's a good thing to do? And what have they done to the impression

02:50:27.760 --> 02:50:33.520
[Guest 2]: of investors about putting money in that state? So, you just, they should not have that tool to

02:50:33.520 --> 02:50:39.440
[Guest 1]: play with. It's a classic case. I want to add to that. There's been a phenomenal collapse of

02:50:40.160 --> 02:50:49.280
[Guest 1]: solar capital goods in the last 10-15 years. So many people in the Indian centrally planned state

02:50:49.280 --> 02:50:58.480
[Guest 1]: electricity system seem to think that that's a bad thing in the sense that we did a tendering

02:50:58.480 --> 02:51:04.160
[Guest 1]: and a bidding and procured solar electricity five years ago at a double quotes high price.

02:51:04.160 --> 02:51:08.640
[Guest 1]: And now when I buy the same thing, it's available at a low price. So, there's something wrong with

02:51:08.640 --> 02:51:13.840
[Guest 1]: that contract. I should find a way to renege on that contract or somehow disrupt that contract

02:51:13.840 --> 02:51:19.760
[Guest 1]: or break that contract. Whereas, absolute basics of contract law teach us that, okay,

02:51:19.760 --> 02:51:23.360
[Guest 1]: if you want to shut down that contract, you'll have to pay them the liquidated damages,

02:51:23.360 --> 02:51:28.400
[Guest 1]: in which case you should just let those panels continue to generate electricity because there

02:51:28.400 --> 02:51:34.960
[Guest 1]: is no benefit from disrupting that contract. But this basic hygiene of commercial thinking

02:51:34.960 --> 02:51:41.120
[Guest 1]: that deals a deal. And if you are willing to be tempted to violate deals, then just think of what

02:51:41.120 --> 02:51:47.200
[Guest 1]: that does to the risk premium. And how will the domestic and the global private sector and

02:51:47.200 --> 02:51:53.120
[Guest 1]: financial sector get involved in the Indian electricity system as vendors hanging at the

02:51:53.120 --> 02:51:58.720
[Guest 1]: edges of a centrally planned system? And how will India achieve a giant climate transition

02:51:58.720 --> 02:52:04.160
[Guest 1]: of eliminating all this fossil fuel electricity generation and greatly increasing renewables

02:52:04.160 --> 02:52:09.760
[Guest 1]: generation if this is the body language and the contracting stance of a wide variety of

02:52:09.760 --> 02:52:14.640
[Amit Varma]: Indian state entities? And this is really, it strikes me as a classic case of the seen and

02:52:14.640 --> 02:52:18.320
[Amit Varma]: the unseen, where the politician says, we will bring prices down, we are doing this for you.

02:52:18.320 --> 02:52:23.760
[Amit Varma]: That's the scene sort of posturing that is there. But the unseen effect is the incentives. Like,

02:52:23.760 --> 02:52:28.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, you've, I think, given a bunch of issues with DISCOMs, some of which you

02:52:28.080 --> 02:52:33.360
[Amit Varma]: summarise right now. For example, DISCOMs will have bidding conditions that allowed private

02:52:33.360 --> 02:52:37.680
[Amit Varma]: power producers to not price the escalation of coal prices into their tariff bids,

02:52:37.680 --> 02:52:42.240
[Amit Varma]: leading to power producers defaulting on their supply commitments when coal prices went up,

02:52:42.240 --> 02:52:45.920
[Amit Varma]: as it's not rational for them to produce it anymore. Again, quoting from your paper,

02:52:45.920 --> 02:52:50.560
[Amit Varma]: little things like what you mentioned about land, that whatever permits and consents and

02:52:50.560 --> 02:52:54.480
[Amit Varma]: all that that has to be done, they will leave it to the private player, they won't do it themselves.

02:52:54.480 --> 02:52:59.840
[Amit Varma]: And then payments can be delayed, they can change the law, blah, blah, blah. Also,

02:52:59.840 --> 02:53:04.080
[Amit Varma]: you've pointed out our DISCOMs are so litigious, even in a case where they are at fault,

02:53:04.080 --> 02:53:08.400
[Amit Varma]: and they're going to lose, they will still go to court, they will still hold the process up,

02:53:08.400 --> 02:53:13.920
[Amit Varma]: because, you know, that's the way that they play the game. And just sort of a whole bunch of areas.

02:53:13.920 --> 02:53:19.360
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, the risk is so high that if you're a private player, you pointed out at one,

02:53:19.360 --> 02:53:23.280
[Amit Varma]: then foreign capital won't come into this because the risk is just way too high for them. The

02:53:23.280 --> 02:53:28.480
[Amit Varma]: environment is just way too unstable. And even private players here, like, why would you just

02:53:28.480 --> 02:53:34.240
[Amit Varma]: get into this? And you might say that, oh, I can start, say, a renewables business here,

02:53:34.240 --> 02:53:38.480
[Amit Varma]: or I can start XYZ, anything else, everything is opportunity cost. And you'll just look at

02:53:38.480 --> 02:53:44.080
[Guest 2]: this environment and you'll say, nahi, nahi karna hai. So you can do it if you're good at

02:53:44.080 --> 02:53:48.080
[Guest 2]: environmental management. If you can manage the environment withinâ€¦ You mean the political

02:53:48.080 --> 02:53:53.920
[Guest 2]: environment? The political, regulatory and legal environment, if you know, if you're willing to

02:53:53.920 --> 02:53:59.200
[Guest 2]: price in what litigation is going to cost, which means you've got to be very, very big. That's one.

02:54:00.320 --> 02:54:04.880
[Guest 2]: And also, you know, we will point to the limited amount of foreign investment that's there to say,

02:54:04.880 --> 02:54:09.200
[Guest 2]: look, all the big private equity funds are here. The big Canadian pension funds are here. Yes,

02:54:09.200 --> 02:54:14.880
[Guest 2]: they all have investments. But I've seen internally, you know, I've sat on the same

02:54:14.880 --> 02:54:20.720
[Guest 2]: side of the table as some of these people and evaluating these things, evaluating an investment

02:54:20.720 --> 02:54:27.200
[Guest 2]: and saying, I would love to make this investment. But 30% of this portfolio of renewable energy

02:54:27.200 --> 02:54:32.800
[Guest 2]: assets is in the state of Andhra Pradesh. And the state of Andhra Pradesh is not paying its

02:54:33.360 --> 02:54:39.760
[Guest 2]: PPAs. So I will not do this deal, or I will price this deal lower. So the Indian guy who's selling

02:54:39.760 --> 02:54:43.840
[Guest 2]: them their project is either getting lower value, not for his fault, but the fact that

02:54:44.560 --> 02:54:49.360
[Guest 2]: his offtaker is not paying him, or the deal is not happening. So we, but we'll still go back and

02:54:49.360 --> 02:54:54.400
[Guest 2]: point to that 6 billion saying, look at that 6 billion, look at the fact that we've got to renew

02:54:54.400 --> 02:54:59.600
[Guest 2]: power, we've got all these domestic industries as well. But the question that no one can answer

02:54:59.600 --> 02:55:05.920
[Guest 2]: is bothering to answer is to say, what have we lost out? I mean, it's a broader issue in of being

02:55:05.920 --> 02:55:11.600
[Guest 2]: an entrepreneur in India in general. But I know at least 50 people who are sitting in well-paying

02:55:11.600 --> 02:55:16.160
[Guest 2]: jobs in Gurgaon, who would set up a business tomorrow, if it was remotely rational to do so.

02:55:16.160 --> 02:55:20.560
[Guest 2]: And in this sector, even more so because you're dealing with regulation and government,

02:55:20.560 --> 02:55:23.920
[Guest 2]: much more than you are in anything that's on the in the digital world, for example.

02:55:25.440 --> 02:55:33.440
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And just beyond the problem of discoms, for example, you've, you know, given five reasons

02:55:33.440 --> 02:55:37.840
[Amit Varma]: why these problems will deepen in your words, you know, so can you take me through some of them?

02:55:37.840 --> 02:55:44.800
[Guest 1]: There is a sense in the mainstream that what's likely to happen is we'll just fumble along,

02:55:45.360 --> 02:55:52.560
[Guest 1]: we will do a little jugadu improvisation here and there. And we will meander along like nothing much

02:55:52.560 --> 02:55:57.360
[Guest 1]: will change. Okay, so we'll muddle along, like nothing much will change. In the paper, we argue

02:55:57.360 --> 02:56:03.520
[Guest 1]: that we are actually standing at a bit of a tipping point. And the world in this field is

02:56:03.520 --> 02:56:09.280
[Guest 1]: likely to change in substantial ways. Why? Okay, there are basically two important forces that are

02:56:09.280 --> 02:56:16.800
[Guest 1]: at work. The first important force is the rise of renewables as a business proposition. So,

02:56:16.800 --> 02:56:23.520
[Guest 1]: for more and more people, the appeal of putting up a windmill, putting up a little bit of a solar

02:56:23.520 --> 02:56:29.360
[Guest 1]: generation capacity for self consumption, the business case is very strong right now. And that

02:56:29.360 --> 02:56:35.120
[Guest 1]: is leading to the best customers peeling off. So the best customers who are so the present

02:56:35.120 --> 02:56:40.880
[Guest 1]: electricity system overcharges the commercial and industrial customer to pay for the subsidized and

02:56:40.880 --> 02:56:46.160
[Guest 1]: stolen electricity. Now, those best customers are being charged such high prices. And the

02:56:46.160 --> 02:56:52.400
[Guest 1]: renewables revolution has generated lower prices that to an increasing extent, some of those users

02:56:52.400 --> 02:56:58.160
[Guest 1]: are peeling off and saying, I'll do less business with the system. So now the system comes under a

02:56:58.160 --> 02:57:03.600
[Guest 1]: fiscal squeeze, because the paying customers are peeling off. The second dimension of this is

02:57:03.600 --> 02:57:10.000
[Guest 1]: coming from the changes in the global world of investment. The rise of global ESG investment

02:57:10.000 --> 02:57:15.920
[Guest 1]: has implied that for a large number of Indian firms, it has become important to make auditable

02:57:15.920 --> 02:57:22.880
[Guest 1]: promises to the investor that I am on a decarbonization path. Individual firms in India

02:57:22.880 --> 02:57:28.560
[Guest 1]: are making promises like net zero by 2035, even though the Indian state is not, because it's

02:57:28.560 --> 02:57:35.600
[Guest 1]: rational and efficient for the firms to do so. And ESG investment is already important. About

02:57:35.600 --> 02:57:41.280
[Guest 1]: 30% of the global investment pool is now ESG and the number may go up a little bit. But

02:57:41.280 --> 02:57:46.640
[Guest 1]: 30% of the global investment pool is now ESG and the number may go up over the years,

02:57:46.640 --> 02:57:55.040
[Guest 1]: but 30% is already a lot. For instance, if you wonder, why did important firms like Reliance

02:57:55.040 --> 02:58:02.800
[Guest 1]: and Adani Group pivot away from a pure fossil fuel strategy to a lot of effort and accent

02:58:02.800 --> 02:58:08.560
[Guest 1]: on clean energy? And the answer lies in ESG investment that they would get a bad valuation

02:58:08.560 --> 02:58:13.280
[Guest 1]: for their equity if they were shunned by 30% of the global investable pool.

02:58:14.400 --> 02:58:20.080
[Guest 1]: So when ESG investment is creating pressures upon Indian companies to decarbonize,

02:58:20.080 --> 02:58:26.320
[Guest 1]: that further accentuates the exit by Indian companies from the grid. Partly the Indian

02:58:26.320 --> 02:58:31.600
[Guest 1]: company will try to say to the grid, I need you to give me auditable, renewable electricity and

02:58:31.600 --> 02:58:35.840
[Guest 1]: the grid will say, I'm not equipped to do so. That's not how I think about it. I think electrons

02:58:35.840 --> 02:58:43.360
[Guest 1]: are fungible. Don't bug me about where I'm getting electricity from. Then the Indian company, the C&I

02:58:43.360 --> 02:58:48.800
[Guest 1]: user of electricity will just say, OK, fine, I'm going to go do my own renewables thing

02:58:48.800 --> 02:58:55.280
[Guest 1]: and they will peel off. So these are the two pressures that charging high prices to the C&I

02:58:55.280 --> 02:59:00.240
[Guest 1]: customers to run across subsidy system has created conditions where in many cases,

02:59:00.240 --> 02:59:06.480
[Guest 1]: renewables are attractive. And the second is the ESG world is pushing the Indian private sector

02:59:06.480 --> 02:59:14.560
[Guest 1]: to systematically seek renewables energy. The two forces put together are hollowing out the revenue

02:59:14.560 --> 02:59:20.560
[Guest 1]: base of the Sarkari system and the Sarkari system will come under hideous fiscal stress as a

02:59:20.560 --> 02:59:28.320
[Guest 2]: consequence. And just to add a bit to that, you've got, for example, Coca-Cola will require all its

02:59:28.320 --> 02:59:32.480
[Guest 2]: vendors to sign up to a sustainability pledge about where they get their electricity from.

02:59:32.480 --> 02:59:38.320
[Guest 2]: So the buyers of products in the West in particular and increasingly in India will want something to

02:59:38.320 --> 02:59:43.600
[Guest 2]: be certified to be green. Now, that certification will lead to somebody coming up with a set of

02:59:43.600 --> 02:59:49.200
[Guest 2]: standards and somebody measuring whether that product is green with respect to those standards.

02:59:49.200 --> 02:59:54.000
[Guest 2]: Initially, it will be imperfect. Some people will fudge it, but that system will improve

02:59:54.000 --> 02:59:58.800
[Guest 2]: and therefore, you will have to. And people will make promises to their shareholders that

02:59:58.800 --> 03:00:03.680
[Guest 2]: we will make sure that everything we buy is sustainable. And then another thing that we

03:00:03.680 --> 03:00:10.640
[Guest 2]: talk about in the paper, already saying book because maybe that's something that we should

03:00:10.640 --> 03:00:15.840
[Guest 2]: do at some point. But there's another thing that we can expect to happen in less than five years

03:00:15.840 --> 03:00:20.640
[Guest 2]: from now is that countries, especially in the European Union, bring into place a carbon border

03:00:20.640 --> 03:00:26.480
[Guest 2]: tax where if you're not green energy, if you're goods of a certain kind, steel, that sort of thing,

03:00:26.480 --> 03:00:31.600
[Guest 2]: not produced with green energy, 20% tariff, which makes you uncompetitive. So people are already

03:00:31.600 --> 03:00:38.960
[Guest 2]: anticipating that and pivoting away from that. But query how many people can actually do that.

03:00:38.960 --> 03:00:43.520
[Guest 2]: The big companies in India will be able to do that. Some of the smaller ones will wither away.

03:00:43.520 --> 03:00:49.120
[Guest 2]: So there's a very complex set of circumstances that you put them all together and it's almost

03:00:49.120 --> 03:00:54.000
[Amit Varma]: like a perfect storm. And you've pointed out that over the last three, four decades,

03:00:54.000 --> 03:00:58.080
[Amit Varma]: people have tried to actually change the system, but there have been incremental changes

03:00:58.080 --> 03:01:04.640
[Amit Varma]: in, you know, localized ways and not fundamental enough. I'll just quote this para from your paper

03:01:04.640 --> 03:01:09.920
[Amit Varma]: where you write, why has considerable policy activism and investments of significant political

03:01:09.920 --> 03:01:15.120
[Amit Varma]: and financial capital not delivered the desired results? The problem is at the core, a government

03:01:15.120 --> 03:01:20.240
[Amit Varma]: controlled centrally planned system. Government control transmits the limitations of state

03:01:20.240 --> 03:01:25.520
[Amit Varma]: capacity into the working of the industry. The growing complexity of the Indian economy requires

03:01:25.520 --> 03:01:31.280
[Amit Varma]: subtle judgments that vary by space and time on the production and consumption of electricity.

03:01:31.280 --> 03:01:37.760
[Amit Varma]: Centrally planned systems lack nuance and single national solutions fare poorly at many places and

03:01:37.760 --> 03:01:43.360
[Amit Varma]: times. And later, there is a key line which sums it all up where you say, policy influences society

03:01:43.360 --> 03:01:51.360
[Amit Varma]: by reshaping the incentives of private persons, stop quote. So let's actually sort of get down

03:01:51.360 --> 03:01:56.160
[Amit Varma]: to what you are suggesting, like what is your recommendation for changing the system,

03:01:56.160 --> 03:02:02.960
[Amit Varma]: price system, complete privatization, and having a carbon tax as a key lever that, you know,

03:02:02.960 --> 03:02:07.600
[Amit Varma]: drives everyone's incentives are sort of the three fronts of it. So tell me a little bit about

03:02:07.600 --> 03:02:13.360
[Amit Varma]: each of those and how, paint a picture of how the system would then function.

03:02:13.360 --> 03:02:18.960
[Guest 1]: So you start at the problem of the climate transition, we consider it inevitable that

03:02:18.960 --> 03:02:24.880
[Guest 1]: there will be a time where India has to get more worried about carbon emissions. Prime Minister

03:02:24.880 --> 03:02:32.240
[Guest 1]: Narendra Modi has promised that India will come to net zero by 2070. Net zero is actually a pretty

03:02:32.240 --> 03:02:38.400
[Guest 1]: hair-raising promise. Zero. Zero is a very small number. It's net zero. It's not a low amount of

03:02:38.400 --> 03:02:44.720
[Guest 1]: emissions. It is on net, no emissions. It's staggering to think of this landscape without

03:02:44.720 --> 03:02:48.880
[Amit Varma]: fossil fuels, without coal, without. Yeah, but you know, I can imagine a comic strip on this,

03:02:48.880 --> 03:02:54.480
[Amit Varma]: that Biden comes to Modi and says, give me a number. And Modi says 56 inches. And Biden says,

03:02:54.480 --> 03:02:58.880
[Amit Varma]: no, not that number. Give me a better number. And then advisor whispers into his ears and he says,

03:02:58.880 --> 03:03:04.800
[Amit Varma]: okay, net zero by when will I be dead by 2070? It's easy to do, right? Sorry, sorry, continue.

03:03:04.800 --> 03:03:09.680
[Guest 1]: I couldn't help that. Yeah. So India will come under pressure and we'll need to figure out

03:03:09.680 --> 03:03:16.320
[Guest 1]: pathways to reduction of carbon emissions. Well, how will that happen? At present, the paradigm is

03:03:17.040 --> 03:03:21.040
[Guest 1]: government will order this and order that. So there'll just be a whole bunch of centrally

03:03:21.040 --> 03:03:26.080
[Guest 1]: planned instructions to various industries. Well, that's very expensive in terms of welfare. The

03:03:26.080 --> 03:03:31.600
[Guest 1]: overall cost of adaptation for the economy will be high. That any centrally planned system imposes

03:03:31.600 --> 03:03:37.520
[Guest 1]: a higher cost to get the same job done. We argue that the way to get that same job done is a carbon

03:03:37.520 --> 03:03:44.400
[Guest 1]: tax. So yes, you want to bring down carbon emissions, tax them and let the private sector

03:03:44.400 --> 03:03:51.360
[Guest 1]: figure out the cost minimizing places where you can emit less carbon. So we have no doubt that

03:03:51.360 --> 03:03:57.680
[Guest 1]: there are pockets of society where it is incredibly efficient to use coal. They should do it because

03:03:57.680 --> 03:04:02.080
[Guest 1]: they're willing to pay more for the coal, even after a reasonably high tax rate, and they should

03:04:02.080 --> 03:04:05.600
[Guest 1]: do it. And there'll be other places where people will say, you know, at this price of coal, I'm

03:04:05.600 --> 03:04:10.320
[Guest 1]: better off changing over to something different. And so all over the country, these local decisions

03:04:10.880 --> 03:04:15.920
[Guest 1]: will be made in terms of production and consumption and how the economy works. And that's

03:04:15.920 --> 03:04:20.720
[Guest 1]: our argument in favor of the carbon tax. So that's the first element. The second element is the

03:04:20.720 --> 03:04:28.800
[Guest 1]: electricity system. When we tax fossil fuels, cooking and mobility, energy requirements will

03:04:28.800 --> 03:04:34.800
[Guest 1]: come into electrical solutions. So the demand for electricity will grow and the overall electricity

03:04:34.800 --> 03:04:40.640
[Guest 1]: sector will need to become large. And the electricity sector is an important emitter of

03:04:40.640 --> 03:04:47.520
[Guest 1]: carbon dioxide. The same carbon tax will need to play through in terms of reshaping the resource

03:04:47.520 --> 03:04:52.480
[Guest 1]: allocation of the electricity sector. And the beauty of this approach is the carbon tax

03:04:52.480 --> 03:04:57.600
[Guest 1]: simultaneously fixes both supply and demand. A lot of present thinking in the electricity sector in

03:04:57.600 --> 03:05:03.840
[Guest 1]: India tends to be supply centric. We kind of think demand cannot be touched. Demand is inflexible.

03:05:03.840 --> 03:05:10.400
[Guest 1]: Demand is incapable of thinking and adapting. No, it's a question of price, that when prices

03:05:10.400 --> 03:05:15.440
[Guest 1]: fluctuate by space and time, this will create incentives for people to change their behavior.

03:05:15.440 --> 03:05:21.360
[Guest 1]: Similarly, we think high intraday price fluctuations create market-based incentives

03:05:21.360 --> 03:05:27.200
[Guest 1]: for storage and market-based incentives to change consumption patterns. So when should you run a

03:05:27.200 --> 03:05:33.760
[Guest 1]: shift? Maybe the right time to run a shift is deep in the night when the electricity is cheap

03:05:33.760 --> 03:05:37.840
[Guest 1]: in the present paradigm or in the middle of the day when the sun is shining. These kinds of

03:05:37.840 --> 03:05:42.720
[Guest 1]: decisions will happen both on supply and demand side. So that's the second critical building

03:05:42.720 --> 03:05:49.840
[Guest 1]: block, which is that the carbon tax will play through into the electricity sector. And that's

03:05:49.840 --> 03:05:55.520
[Guest 1]: how the entire reshaping will be done. So this is our big picture of how to think about this

03:05:55.520 --> 03:06:00.880
[Guest 1]: whole thing. And so I want to be careful about the word transmission, because in this field,

03:06:00.880 --> 03:06:07.120
[Guest 1]: it means electricity transmission. But there's a useful metaphor in the phrase climate policy

03:06:07.120 --> 03:06:12.960
[Guest 1]: transmission, which is analogous to monetary policy transmission, that how do you get your

03:06:12.960 --> 03:06:18.160
[Guest 1]: work done? The climate policy transmission runs through carbon tax and then electricity sector.

03:06:18.160 --> 03:06:22.640
[Guest 1]: You need both to work. The electricity sector needs to be placed on a foundation of the price

03:06:22.640 --> 03:06:28.320
[Guest 1]: system so that when a carbon tax goes up, the price system will respond. At present,

03:06:28.320 --> 03:06:32.160
[Guest 1]: the electricity sector does not work through the price system. So even if you introduce a carbon

03:06:32.160 --> 03:06:37.280
[Guest 1]: tax, that heavy lifting of adaptation by buyers and sellers will not happen.

03:06:38.400 --> 03:06:42.720
[Amit Varma]: Now, one response that people could have to say, and I'll quickly kind of sum up,

03:06:42.720 --> 03:06:47.120
[Amit Varma]: and you can tell me if I'm summing it up right, where what you're essentially saying is that,

03:06:47.120 --> 03:06:51.920
[Amit Varma]: look, we have to move in a particular direction. This is a direction we have to move in,

03:06:51.920 --> 03:06:55.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, more renewables, bring down carbon emissions, make it net zero as

03:06:55.840 --> 03:07:01.040
[Amit Varma]: great Prime Minister promised. And we can't do it in the current system, because the incentives

03:07:01.040 --> 03:07:06.720
[Amit Varma]: are just all over the place. You know, discoms mess up in their contracts and putting too much

03:07:06.720 --> 03:07:12.800
[Amit Varma]: risk on private parties and unjustified litigation in bad incentives. You know,

03:07:12.800 --> 03:07:17.040
[Amit Varma]: they're treated in a partisan way by regulators and courts, so private parties don't get justice.

03:07:17.040 --> 03:07:20.880
[Amit Varma]: They respond to political incentives, free power for so and so and blah, blah, blah.

03:07:20.880 --> 03:07:25.200
[Amit Varma]: All that is fine. So the argument then is that, look, we have to privatize completely,

03:07:25.200 --> 03:07:29.680
[Amit Varma]: let the price system have its way, the same way it does in bread, as you said, or so many other

03:07:29.680 --> 03:07:34.320
[Amit Varma]: things. Everything that really works in our lives today, is because there is a price system in play,

03:07:34.320 --> 03:07:38.800
[Amit Varma]: and people are responding to incentives to make our lives better. And everything that is

03:07:38.800 --> 03:07:44.160
[Amit Varma]: dysfunctional about India is where at some level, there is a problem, and the price system isn't

03:07:44.160 --> 03:07:50.160
[Amit Varma]: allowed to have its way. Now, a question that would commonly come up, especially in the popular

03:07:50.160 --> 03:07:56.160
[Amit Varma]: discourse, would be that you want to privatize everything? That won't greedy capitalists come

03:07:56.160 --> 03:08:02.480
[Amit Varma]: in and the Adani and Ambani's come in and charge insane amounts of money. And you know, it is okay

03:08:02.480 --> 03:08:06.400
[Amit Varma]: for the elites and all of that. But you're basically handing the company over to the

03:08:06.400 --> 03:08:11.120
[Amit Varma]: corporates. In some sense, some of the, you know, criticisms which were raised against the farm

03:08:11.120 --> 03:08:17.360
[Amit Varma]: bills, which we had a very popular episode on. How does one tackle that populism? I think at the

03:08:17.360 --> 03:08:24.560
[Amit Varma]: first level of winning the battle is not so much a question of winning it in terms of persuading

03:08:24.560 --> 03:08:29.840
[Amit Varma]: policymakers and politicians, but winning it in terms of winning the popular narrative,

03:08:29.840 --> 03:08:34.400
[Amit Varma]: because that itself sets the incentives right then for the politicians and the bureaucrats.

03:08:34.960 --> 03:08:40.480
[Guest 2]: We think even on that the narrative is beginning to move. We finally sold Air India,

03:08:40.480 --> 03:08:46.000
[Guest 2]: that finally Air India is in private hands. And there is as far as the central government

03:08:46.000 --> 03:08:51.440
[Guest 2]: is concerned, there is a privatization or an asset disposal program that's on board.

03:08:51.440 --> 03:08:56.640
[Guest 2]: But there's good reason to believe that as far as the central government is concerned,

03:08:56.640 --> 03:09:02.160
[Guest 2]: they are not opposed to privatizing the discoms, because they are regularly called upon to bail

03:09:02.160 --> 03:09:06.560
[Guest 2]: out the states in this. And it's the locus of the problem, therefore, lies in the states.

03:09:07.120 --> 03:09:12.320
[Guest 2]: So, you have to create, therefore, the right incentive for a state to do this. And you have

03:09:12.320 --> 03:09:18.720
[Guest 2]: to do it by showing them that there is either money to be had in making the transition,

03:09:18.720 --> 03:09:23.600
[Guest 2]: or that there is money to be had post the transition. And that is why we've talked

03:09:23.600 --> 03:09:29.200
[Guest 2]: about a state-by-state approach, not just in terms of dealing with the political economy in

03:09:29.200 --> 03:09:33.920
[Guest 2]: terms of individual people, but also in terms of the government itself or the people within

03:09:33.920 --> 03:09:37.920
[Guest 2]: government who stand to lose under those circumstances. So, I think we think that,

03:09:37.920 --> 03:09:43.520
[Guest 2]: you know, the issue on privatization isn't as bad as it used to be. That's number one.

03:09:43.520 --> 03:09:47.360
[Guest 2]: Number two, one of the market failures that you're going to have to correct for through regulation

03:09:47.360 --> 03:09:51.600
[Guest 2]: is competition. So, the competition will come through two ways, one through the general

03:09:51.600 --> 03:09:57.280
[Guest 2]: competition law. And secondly, the new regime of regulation that you have for electricity in

03:09:57.280 --> 03:10:02.320
[Guest 2]: a largely privatized world will also have some amount of competition control done through it.

03:10:02.320 --> 03:10:07.680
[Guest 2]: I mean, that goes into a very complex issue of the overlapping powers of regulators. But in

03:10:07.680 --> 03:10:12.000
[Guest 2]: some areas, it's good to have overlapping powers of regulators, because on the one hand, you've got

03:10:12.000 --> 03:10:16.720
[Guest 2]: deep sectoral knowledge about how competition plays out in this sector. On the other hand,

03:10:16.720 --> 03:10:21.040
[Guest 2]: you've got the general principles of competition, and, you know, how that should work at the level

03:10:21.040 --> 03:10:27.840
[Guest 2]: of the economy. So, a little bit of competitive competition regulation, if you like, is possibly

03:10:27.840 --> 03:10:35.360
[Guest 2]: not such a bad thing. So, that's the other answer to that. But, you know, it is still a coconut tree.

03:10:35.360 --> 03:10:41.200
[Guest 1]: There's no question about that. I want to add to that, it does not have to be a monolithic

03:10:41.200 --> 03:10:49.440
[Guest 1]: industry with two companies. The bottleneck is rule of law and the behavior of the state system

03:10:49.440 --> 03:10:56.160
[Guest 1]: and the regulatory capacity. So, when regulators have arbitrary power and are capricious,

03:10:56.720 --> 03:11:04.320
[Guest 1]: and the rule of law is absent, then for a smaller firm, this is a deterrent. For a foreign firm,

03:11:04.320 --> 03:11:09.520
[Guest 1]: this is a deterrent. And then we end up with a collapse into a small market with

03:11:09.520 --> 03:11:16.960
[Guest 1]: a very small number of players. So, again, the machinery of this paper is key, that if

03:11:16.960 --> 03:11:21.520
[Guest 1]: we get the state system out of this game, and you are not in a centrally planned world,

03:11:22.320 --> 03:11:29.440
[Guest 1]: and we actually build regulatory capacity and set regulators in motion in a good way, as is

03:11:30.560 --> 03:11:36.480
[Guest 1]: described in the paper, and this is drawing on the larger arc of the development of regulatory

03:11:36.480 --> 03:11:40.880
[Guest 1]: theory and public administration concepts on regulation in India. So, as you know,

03:11:40.880 --> 03:11:45.840
[Guest 1]: there has been considerable progress in thinking, though not acting, about how to make financial

03:11:45.840 --> 03:11:50.080
[Guest 1]: regulators work properly. And so there's a lot of knowledge on how to make regulators work

03:11:50.080 --> 03:11:55.280
[Guest 1]: correctly. And you bring that knowledge into the construction of regulators in India.

03:11:55.280 --> 03:12:00.800
[Guest 1]: Then we are offering many, many private people profit opportunities. It can be very local.

03:12:00.800 --> 03:12:05.520
[Guest 1]: It doesn't have to be monstrous. It can be, I'm sitting here in Amravati and I'm seeing this

03:12:05.520 --> 03:12:11.200
[Guest 1]: opportunity and I'll build one small storage system or I have one small generation opportunity

03:12:11.200 --> 03:12:16.800
[Guest 1]: here and so on. So, there'll be many, many elements of the energy all across the system.

03:12:16.800 --> 03:12:24.560
[Guest 1]: So, the reason why we are criticising this sector as having two giant companies is the

03:12:25.680 --> 03:12:33.120
[Guest 1]: extent of government domination and the lack of rule of law and the failures of how regulators

03:12:33.120 --> 03:12:39.680
[Guest 1]: work. So, in a sense, the Electricity Act was a very nice achievement in the early 2000s,

03:12:39.680 --> 03:12:46.160
[Guest 1]: but it predated the modern development of thinking about regulators and regulatory theory

03:12:46.160 --> 03:12:51.440
[Guest 1]: and the public administration about regulation that has taken place in India in the last 20 years.

03:12:51.440 --> 03:12:57.120
[Guest 1]: Today, the intelligence in India knows more about regulation. We understand the failures

03:12:57.120 --> 03:13:01.520
[Guest 1]: of regulation. We know how to construct regulators. And today that knowledge set

03:13:01.520 --> 03:13:05.440
[Amit Varma]: is ready and it can be done right. So, one important point I just want to kind

03:13:05.440 --> 03:13:12.240
[Amit Varma]: of clarify for listeners is that when Ajay and Akshay talk of privatisation and the price system,

03:13:12.240 --> 03:13:18.800
[Amit Varma]: they don't mean a random anarchic free-for-all. In fact, that section on building regulatory

03:13:18.800 --> 03:13:24.480
[Amit Varma]: capacity is a key section of your paper where you point out, for example, that regulation should

03:13:24.480 --> 03:13:28.880
[Amit Varma]: only focus on market failure. You point out the four different kinds of market failure.

03:13:28.880 --> 03:13:34.400
[Amit Varma]: You also talk about how it takes three hands to clap, which is such a nice image. And you talk

03:13:34.400 --> 03:13:41.040
[Amit Varma]: about the different ways in which you sort of build that kind of regulatory capacity and so on.

03:13:41.040 --> 03:13:46.480
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, as far as people worried about high prices and so on, I would say that, look,

03:13:46.480 --> 03:13:51.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, look at every area of your life around you where the price system is allowed to function.

03:13:51.680 --> 03:13:59.760
[Amit Varma]: Look at bread, you know, bread is by and large, it is affordable and supply is regular. And it is,

03:13:59.760 --> 03:14:04.400
[Amit Varma]: you know, and why should not that, and that is really kind of the case with everything else.

03:14:04.400 --> 03:14:10.400
[Amit Varma]: So, why not with electricity as well, where some of us just take failure for granted. And this is,

03:14:10.400 --> 03:14:14.800
[Amit Varma]: in fact, something the Prime Minister should also sort of take to heart because one of the

03:14:14.800 --> 03:14:19.520
[Amit Varma]: stories about him, which I often, which I've told a couple of times on the show is a friend of his,

03:14:19.520 --> 03:14:24.800
[Amit Varma]: a friend of Mr. Modi's who had worked with him in Gujarat. She was at a gathering at his house in

03:14:25.760 --> 03:14:30.640
[Amit Varma]: circa 2007 or whatever. And he told the story about his childhood, about how his mother was

03:14:30.640 --> 03:14:35.200
[Amit Varma]: ill one day, and she was sweating and feeling hot and he went to switch on the fan and he found

03:14:35.200 --> 03:14:39.920
[Amit Varma]: there was no electricity. And as he told the story, he started crying. And, you know, for us

03:14:39.920 --> 03:14:44.320
[Amit Varma]: in the big cities in Bombay, Delhi, electricity is something we can take for granted that we're

03:14:44.320 --> 03:14:48.320
[Amit Varma]: going to get power all day. That is simply not the case for most of the country. And,

03:14:48.320 --> 03:14:53.840
[Amit Varma]: well, that's also a huge failure. And that goes back exactly to the points that you're making.

03:14:53.840 --> 03:14:59.040
[Amit Varma]: The other key point that you've made, which I think deserves to be underscored, is the

03:14:59.040 --> 03:15:04.240
[Amit Varma]: localization, the local thinking, that even if you build the system, you don't have to do it,

03:15:04.240 --> 03:15:08.560
[Amit Varma]: you know, where centrally the PMO will pass an order for the whole country, sub-privatize,

03:15:08.560 --> 03:15:13.360
[Amit Varma]: Karo, price system, Karo. But you can do it state by state, allow different states to experiment

03:15:13.360 --> 03:15:19.200
[Amit Varma]: at a local level and to sort of compete with each other. Have I kind of summed that up?

03:15:19.200 --> 03:15:23.680
[Guest 2]: That's a point worth underscoring a little bit from a couple of different perspectives. One is

03:15:23.680 --> 03:15:31.280
[Guest 2]: that it isn't legally possible for the central government to sort of have a diktat to say you

03:15:31.280 --> 03:15:35.440
[Guest 2]: need to do that. It can only be done through, if it wants to be involved, it can only do it

03:15:35.440 --> 03:15:39.840
[Guest 2]: through a system of incentives, that we will give you money to do this if you do that. And to some

03:15:39.840 --> 03:15:46.000
[Guest 2]: extent, some of the bailing out of the discoms within the states has been done on the basis,

03:15:46.000 --> 03:15:50.320
[Guest 2]: they will give you this money if you do this reform. And in some cases, a little bit of reform

03:15:50.320 --> 03:15:54.720
[Guest 2]: has happened. In other cases, it's still not been done. But it's very difficult for some of the

03:15:54.720 --> 03:15:59.200
[Guest 2]: central government to pull the plug and to say, okay, we're going to let you run into the ground

03:15:59.200 --> 03:16:04.000
[Guest 2]: because the state will turn around and say, we want to give you electricity, but the central

03:16:04.000 --> 03:16:09.840
[Guest 2]: government isn't doing it. That's number one. And secondly, when we talk about central planning,

03:16:09.840 --> 03:16:14.480
[Guest 2]: the central planning isn't really, we don't mean that there is one central planner,

03:16:14.480 --> 03:16:18.960
[Guest 2]: but there are series of central planners all through the system. There are central planners

03:16:18.960 --> 03:16:23.440
[Guest 2]: in each state, there are central planners for transmission versus for distribution. So,

03:16:23.440 --> 03:16:31.120
[Guest 2]: you put together the regulatory and state decision making apparatus, and you could remove all the

03:16:31.120 --> 03:16:35.760
[Guest 2]: individual decision makers, and it would be a completely centrally planned system. So, the point

03:16:35.760 --> 03:16:41.680
[Guest 2]: being that this is not a willing buyer and a willing seller doing a deal. This is a, because

03:16:41.680 --> 03:16:45.760
[Guest 2]: people also say, but what do you mean price system? There's a price, there's a bid, somebody

03:16:45.760 --> 03:16:50.960
[Guest 2]: bids on a power purchase agreement, and they win the bid, and the bid is at 2 rupees 50 paisa,

03:16:50.960 --> 03:16:56.880
[Guest 2]: and they supply power that. But that is not what we mean by the price system. That is the

03:16:56.880 --> 03:17:02.720
[Guest 2]: determination of a long term of the price of electricity on a long term contract, as opposed

03:17:02.720 --> 03:17:07.600
[Guest 2]: to the day to day adjustment of prices that could take place in a system where private guys were

03:17:07.600 --> 03:17:14.800
[Guest 2]: doing deals with other private guys. So, there's a big difference, you know, in those two ideas.

03:17:15.520 --> 03:17:20.400
[Guest 1]: And I just want to underline that we say carbon tax, the price of fossil fuels should go up,

03:17:20.960 --> 03:17:24.560
[Guest 1]: subsidies on electricity should go away, prices on electricity should go up,

03:17:24.560 --> 03:17:29.760
[Guest 1]: prices of electricity should fluctuate through the day. So, there will be some 6 pm surge at

03:17:29.760 --> 03:17:35.600
[Guest 1]: which your use of the air conditioner will be rather expensive. Well, there is an alternative,

03:17:35.600 --> 03:17:41.440
[Guest 1]: which is a centrally planned climate transition. If the government goes around giving orders

03:17:42.000 --> 03:17:49.120
[Guest 1]: that there will be a solar plant here and there will be this ban on use of coal by this industry

03:17:49.120 --> 03:17:54.640
[Guest 1]: there, that will also impose welfare costs on society. They'll just be concealed. So, you won't

03:17:54.640 --> 03:18:03.600
[Guest 1]: see it as a change in prices and damage to GDP and the incomes of the people that came about

03:18:03.600 --> 03:18:07.840
[Guest 1]: because there was a detailed regulatory restriction that was introduced by the government. But the

03:18:07.840 --> 03:18:13.600
[Guest 1]: costs are there. The climate transition will introduce costs upon society. The only question

03:18:13.600 --> 03:18:17.760
[Guest 1]: is, do you want to pay more or do you want to pay less? So, this is the lowest fruit of the

03:18:17.760 --> 03:18:23.280
[Guest 1]: coconut tree. A centrally planned climate transition will always be more expensive than a

03:18:23.280 --> 03:18:28.880
[Guest 1]: climate transition that is implemented through the price system where thousands of intelligent,

03:18:28.880 --> 03:18:35.680
[Guest 1]: self-interested people all around the country are thinking and acting and finding clever solutions

03:18:35.680 --> 03:18:40.320
[Guest 2]: at every place that they are. There's a technical issue that bears mention over here, which is that

03:18:41.200 --> 03:18:45.440
[Guest 2]: because of the fact, as we mentioned earlier, because of the fact that you can't store large

03:18:45.440 --> 03:18:50.640
[Guest 2]: amounts of electricity at the moment, it's not that you can produce it, wait for a good price,

03:18:50.640 --> 03:18:59.920
[Guest 2]: etc. So, there's going to be some adjustments that need to be made between what you and I might

03:18:59.920 --> 03:19:06.000
[Guest 2]: otherwise conceive of as a completely free system. There may need to be some amount of

03:19:06.000 --> 03:19:09.760
[Guest 2]: systems operation management, which might have to be done by a central entity, which

03:19:09.760 --> 03:19:14.640
[Guest 2]: could potentially be owned by all the participants in the power sector together, but which is

03:19:14.640 --> 03:19:20.480
[Guest 2]: performing a public good. It's saying, I will not allow the dispatch of that plant at this point in

03:19:20.480 --> 03:19:25.120
[Guest 2]: time, even though it's a good price for you to do it at, because of the fact that the grid is weak

03:19:25.120 --> 03:19:29.760
[Guest 2]: there, and there's going to be a problem. But it's only on the basis of on technical grounds.

03:19:29.760 --> 03:19:34.240
[Guest 2]: You may need to have a few power plants. This is just one of the solutions that you could have.

03:19:34.240 --> 03:19:38.880
[Guest 2]: A few power plants that are sitting around relatively idle, that come into play when

03:19:38.880 --> 03:19:43.360
[Guest 2]: they are required to be brought into play. And that is a cost that the entire system pays through

03:19:43.360 --> 03:19:49.840
[Guest 2]: some sort of charge. So, the way I'm beginning to start thinking of this is that you may retain

03:19:49.840 --> 03:19:56.720
[Guest 2]: some amount of central planning, which can also be diluted from government and made more cooperative,

03:19:58.320 --> 03:20:04.400
[Guest 2]: say 10% of the system to allow 90% of the system to work within the price system.

03:20:04.400 --> 03:20:11.440
[Guest 2]: And that's okay. But at the moment, what we've got is we've got 90% in this thing for 10%,

03:20:11.440 --> 03:20:17.200
[Guest 2]: which might be in the price system. And in fact, by coincidence, 10% is the amount of money that

03:20:17.200 --> 03:20:23.120
[Guest 2]: is the amount of electricity that is traded on the electricity exchanges. So, that's exactly

03:20:23.120 --> 03:20:28.400
[Amit Varma]: what we have at the moment. So, here's a question. At a conceptual level, I absolutely, obviously

03:20:28.400 --> 03:20:32.800
[Amit Varma]: agree with you. Everything just makes so much sense, it falls into place. Are there concrete

03:20:32.800 --> 03:20:38.400
[Amit Varma]: examples of A, such systems in play elsewhere in the world and other advanced countries and

03:20:38.400 --> 03:20:43.600
[Amit Varma]: two, more importantly, such transitions that have been that might have been made from a status

03:20:43.600 --> 03:20:49.440
[Amit Varma]: system like ours to one which respects the price system and then begins to work better? Because

03:20:49.440 --> 03:20:53.840
[Amit Varma]: once you know, you can point to examples of such things actually working elsewhere,

03:20:53.840 --> 03:20:58.560
[Guest 2]: it becomes a far easier sell, doesn't it? Yes, I mean, there are some examples. The

03:20:58.560 --> 03:21:04.080
[Guest 2]: most prominent examples are the UK and California, both of which have had enormous problems

03:21:04.080 --> 03:21:09.760
[Guest 2]: in the functioning of a market system in the way that it existed. Now, there's a lot of detail as

03:21:09.760 --> 03:21:13.840
[Guest 2]: to why those problems arose. And, you know, you'll have seen that the prices in Europe,

03:21:13.840 --> 03:21:18.000
[Guest 2]: this winter got of electricity went up significantly. And there were, you know,

03:21:18.000 --> 03:21:24.400
[Guest 2]: there were complaints about it, etc. But these are places where for large amounts of the time,

03:21:24.960 --> 03:21:30.880
[Guest 2]: and for a fairly long period of time, the price system effectively has worked. There have been

03:21:30.880 --> 03:21:36.400
[Guest 2]: been periods of problems where the problems have been caused because of exceptional circumstances.

03:21:36.400 --> 03:21:44.000
[Guest 2]: So, the point is not to measure that what we achieved, what we've got today against an ideal

03:21:44.000 --> 03:21:48.720
[Guest 2]: that could exist, but to measure what we've got today against what they've got in those places

03:21:48.720 --> 03:21:53.280
[Guest 2]: where you can choose your provider, you can change your provider. And that itself will

03:21:53.840 --> 03:21:58.480
[Guest 2]: be an incentive to the provider to give you a better price and to function better.

03:21:58.480 --> 03:22:04.640
[Guest 2]: One of the issues is that in a situation which is largely fossil fuel based, your price is

03:22:05.200 --> 03:22:12.800
[Guest 2]: significantly dependent on the price of the fuel. And that's an extra cost. If you've got a mainly

03:22:12.800 --> 03:22:17.920
[Guest 2]: renewables based system with storage and with a few plants that perhaps are acting as backup,

03:22:18.480 --> 03:22:26.480
[Guest 2]: you have got a system where the marginal cost of power is close to zero. So, you are not going to

03:22:26.480 --> 03:22:32.320
[Guest 2]: going to have that degree of fluctuation as you might have in a system which is more fuel based.

03:22:33.440 --> 03:22:38.560
[Amit Varma]: One of the heartening sort of things about your paper was a section that addresses

03:22:38.560 --> 03:22:43.360
[Amit Varma]: how feasible these changes are. And you've pointed out that there are six important reasons to

03:22:43.360 --> 03:22:47.920
[Amit Varma]: believe that while we have been satisfied with incremental changes all along that these,

03:22:48.480 --> 03:22:52.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, wide ranging changes can actually happen today. I won't ask you to sort of

03:22:52.720 --> 03:22:56.880
[Amit Varma]: go into each of those in detail, you know, listeners can just download the paper and read

03:22:56.880 --> 03:23:01.920
[Amit Varma]: that, hopefully. But in general, when you have been talking to policymakers or politicians and

03:23:01.920 --> 03:23:07.360
[Amit Varma]: so on, what's the kind of response that you've got? Like, how likely, for example, let's say,

03:23:08.960 --> 03:23:13.600
[Amit Varma]: I'll sort of ask you to speculate, but you have all the information, you have the best possible

03:23:13.600 --> 03:23:17.840
[Amit Varma]: information you need to actually speculate on this. How likely is this to actually be

03:23:17.840 --> 03:23:24.880
[Amit Varma]: implemented on a scale of zero to 10 by say, 2020, 2027, five years from now?

03:23:25.760 --> 03:23:34.080
[Guest 2]: Very low, very low chance of it being implemented. But you need one state, you need to have one

03:23:34.080 --> 03:23:42.480
[Guest 2]: state that has a vision of what its electricity sector could look like in the context of a climate

03:23:42.480 --> 03:23:47.920
[Guest 2]: transition. And, you know, take the four industrialized, most industrialized states,

03:23:47.920 --> 03:23:53.840
[Guest 2]: Maharashtra, Gujarat, Tamil Nadu and Karnataka, they all stand to lose, their industries stand

03:23:53.840 --> 03:24:00.080
[Guest 2]: to lose if they aren't in a more green energy environment, as we were talking about earlier,

03:24:00.080 --> 03:24:04.640
[Guest 2]: because they are exporters, people will stop buying their products, or they'll have taxes

03:24:04.640 --> 03:24:08.720
[Guest 2]: imposed upon them. So, there's a good reason for them to potentially look into doing it.

03:24:08.720 --> 03:24:14.640
[Guest 2]: Some states might want to do it because they want to have a target that is well before 2070,

03:24:14.640 --> 03:24:21.040
[Guest 2]: and they want to score political points there. But I'm most heartened by a specific development

03:24:21.040 --> 03:24:28.640
[Guest 2]: that's happening under the aegis of the Paris Agreement and COP26, which is that a deal has

03:24:28.640 --> 03:24:36.080
[Guest 2]: been struck between South Africa, on the one hand, and the EU, the US and France and Germany

03:24:36.080 --> 03:24:43.520
[Guest 2]: in the individual capacity, by which $8.5 billion is going to be given to South Africa to move from

03:24:43.520 --> 03:24:51.520
[Guest 2]: being 80% fossil fuel to much more renewables based over a certain period of time. That's in

03:24:51.520 --> 03:24:55.520
[Guest 2]: an MOU phase now, in two years' time, they'll come out with details, there'll be lots of problems,

03:24:55.520 --> 03:25:02.800
[Guest 2]: maybe it'll take five years to happen. But there's a deal where if a state could conceive of a plan

03:25:02.800 --> 03:25:09.920
[Guest 2]: based along the lines of the ideas that we have in this paper, a state could go with that to the EU

03:25:09.920 --> 03:25:14.240
[Guest 2]: and to other such people in the world, to John Kerry's team, etc, and say, look, we've got this

03:25:14.240 --> 03:25:20.960
[Guest 2]: plan. Can you find us some money to finance this? Now, that money has to go through the central

03:25:20.960 --> 03:25:25.680
[Guest 2]: governments, you know, foreign money can't go directly to a state government. But then if that

03:25:25.680 --> 03:25:30.000
[Guest 2]: were to, if the EU were to go to the central government and say, look, you're already pro

03:25:30.000 --> 03:25:34.320
[Guest 2]: privatisation, you're already pro a lot of these ideas, you've got these commitments internationally,

03:25:34.320 --> 03:25:39.840
[Guest 2]: which you've made, the states have not made, we've got a good, we've seen a good plan for this state,

03:25:39.840 --> 03:25:44.240
[Guest 2]: we want to finance that, allow it to happen. If that then happens, and you get one state,

03:25:44.240 --> 03:25:49.920
[Guest 2]: one state happens, it's a success, you find money coming in for to enable the transition to happen.

03:25:49.920 --> 03:25:54.560
[Guest 2]: And then you have potentially investment because that transition has happened. And then you might

03:25:54.560 --> 03:26:00.160
[Guest 2]: have an effect on other states. As I say this, I realised that it's extremely speculative, and it's

03:26:00.160 --> 03:26:04.160
[Guest 2]: the chances of it happening are very small, which is why that's how I started my answer to your

03:26:04.160 --> 03:26:09.200
[Guest 2]: question. But this is the one of the most plausible paths potentially that I see.

03:26:09.840 --> 03:26:11.200
[Guest 1]: I don't agree with you at all.

03:26:12.720 --> 03:26:13.040
[Unknown]: Okay.

03:26:14.320 --> 03:26:23.760
[Guest 1]: Yeah, I think that we are at the dying phases of the old paradigm. The old paradigm is past its

03:26:23.760 --> 03:26:32.240
[Guest 1]: sell by date. And there are inexorable pressures that are messing with the old paradigm. And

03:26:33.360 --> 03:26:42.720
[Guest 1]: every year, the pressure on the old system gets worse. So there will be a market for ideas. And

03:26:42.720 --> 03:26:47.520
[Guest 1]: there will be many, many attempts all across the country, different, different states will try

03:26:47.520 --> 03:26:53.840
[Guest 1]: different, different things. And there will be many experiments. And I think, in the end,

03:26:54.560 --> 03:26:59.840
[Guest 1]: we will end up with this kind of answer. I think we are at the cusp of that transformation.

03:26:59.840 --> 03:27:05.520
[Guest 1]: Sentence in the paper is that men and nations will do the right thing after trying every

03:27:05.520 --> 03:27:06.800
[Amit Varma]: reasonable alternative.

03:27:06.800 --> 03:27:10.480
[Amit Varma]: People and nations, you got to watch out for this kind of thing.

03:27:10.480 --> 03:27:12.800
[Guest 1]: I'm on the original Churchill text.

03:27:12.800 --> 03:27:13.120
[Guest 1]: Okay.

03:27:13.120 --> 03:27:19.680
[Guest 1]: Okay. So I think that we are at a transformative point in the story of this field,

03:27:20.240 --> 03:27:24.480
[Guest 1]: that there is a state control system, and it is trying to adapt what best it can.

03:27:25.120 --> 03:27:30.800
[Guest 1]: But there is just so many things going wrong under its watch. And finally, as Akshay said,

03:27:31.680 --> 03:27:38.560
[Guest 1]: if you are Gujarat, Maharashtra, Karnataka, Tamil Nadu, the very GDP of these states

03:27:38.560 --> 03:27:43.760
[Guest 1]: is exposed to good quality, reliable electricity and export markets.

03:27:43.760 --> 03:27:50.000
[Guest 1]: And the ESG world matters to the companies in these states. So all those forces

03:27:50.000 --> 03:27:54.080
[Guest 1]: are coming together in these four states. And there will also be some other states

03:27:54.080 --> 03:27:55.760
[Guest 1]: that are facing this similar mix.

03:27:56.400 --> 03:28:00.560
[Guest 2]: I don't know how much you believe in this yourself, but you don't have to worry. I'm

03:28:00.560 --> 03:28:04.800
[Guest 2]: still going to continue working with you on this despite that, despite my relative pessimism.

03:28:04.800 --> 03:28:09.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, even though you disagreed with each other, my instinct is to agree with both of

03:28:09.600 --> 03:28:15.600
[Amit Varma]: you in this way that, you know, as that old cliche goes, that some of us tend to overestimate the

03:28:15.600 --> 03:28:19.840
[Amit Varma]: short term and underestimate the long term. And I think, yes, we shouldn't overestimate

03:28:19.840 --> 03:28:24.720
[Amit Varma]: the short term, as Akshay, you pointed out. And as you pointed out, we should not underestimate

03:28:25.440 --> 03:28:30.080
[Amit Varma]: the long term either. A couple of sort of final questions before we kind of

03:28:30.080 --> 03:28:33.760
[Amit Varma]: wrap it up, because whatever the, you know, the energy industry outside might be like,

03:28:33.760 --> 03:28:35.920
[Amit Varma]: I worry that you guys are running out of energy.

03:28:35.920 --> 03:28:36.800
[Amit Varma]: We're not that old.

03:28:39.360 --> 03:28:43.840
[Amit Varma]: So one, I want to go to nuclear for a second, because the more I read about nuclear and think

03:28:43.840 --> 03:28:49.040
[Amit Varma]: about it, it seems to me that that could be one kind of game changer, which just makes this whole

03:28:49.040 --> 03:28:52.640
[Amit Varma]: question moot. I mean, we were talking about Michael Schellenberger's work before

03:28:52.640 --> 03:28:56.400
[Amit Varma]: the recording, and I'll give suitable links. And there's also an excellent op-ed

03:28:56.400 --> 03:28:59.920
[Amit Varma]: in the New York Times co-written by Steven Pinker a couple of years ago,

03:28:59.920 --> 03:29:03.760
[Amit Varma]: which kind of spoke about that. Now, people think about nuclear and they say, oh shit,

03:29:03.760 --> 03:29:09.200
[Amit Varma]: the dangers and all that. But those dangers are massively overstated in the sense that

03:29:09.200 --> 03:29:13.760
[Amit Varma]: one of the things that Pinker and his co-writers pointed out in the op-ed was that if you look

03:29:13.760 --> 03:29:17.520
[Amit Varma]: at the total number of people who died in Chernobyl, including the several thousand

03:29:17.520 --> 03:29:23.520
[Amit Varma]: from cancer, that's the same number of people killed by coal emissions in one day, right?

03:29:23.520 --> 03:29:29.120
[Amit Varma]: Nuclear energy is by far orders of magnitude safer than any other kind of energy. In fact,

03:29:29.120 --> 03:29:34.560
[Amit Varma]: even Chernobyl was really caused by a dysfunctional bureaucracy. And nuclear energy is really sort of,

03:29:35.440 --> 03:29:40.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, the safest kind of power generation that exists today, as in fact, France,

03:29:40.720 --> 03:29:45.120
[Amit Varma]: where you're from Akshay, has kind of demonstrated and seems to be winning that argument with

03:29:45.120 --> 03:29:49.520
[Amit Varma]: Germany, which we were talking about earlier. So what are your sort of thoughts on this?

03:29:49.520 --> 03:29:54.400
[Guest 2]: Well, one, I think there are two sets of risks with nuclear. One is the one you mentioned,

03:29:54.400 --> 03:30:00.720
[Guest 2]: which is the danger of fallout and having disasters. The second is the more unseen risk

03:30:00.720 --> 03:30:07.840
[Guest 2]: of waste disposal. So there was a pretty good article recently, I think it was in the Financial

03:30:07.840 --> 03:30:15.120
[Guest 2]: Times, I'll find it and send you the link for it so that people can read it. But it's an article

03:30:15.120 --> 03:30:21.120
[Guest 2]: which talks about the dangers of storage of waste, of nuclear waste. There are caverns underneath

03:30:21.120 --> 03:30:28.240
[Guest 2]: certain towns in France and in the desert in, you know, in the US, etc. That's a bigger problem.

03:30:28.240 --> 03:30:34.160
[Guest 2]: But the way I look at it is this, and I might be accused for being slightly flippant or

03:30:35.200 --> 03:30:40.160
[Guest 2]: technologically deterministic about it. But if we accept that climate change is an existential

03:30:40.160 --> 03:30:47.120
[Guest 2]: problem today, then you shouldn't be ramping down on nuclear for sure. What Germany did,

03:30:47.120 --> 03:30:53.200
[Guest 2]: I think was wrong, because it is today burning coal. It's burning more expensive gas and arguably

03:30:53.200 --> 03:30:59.440
[Guest 2]: it's more, diplomatically it's more open to being arm twisted by Russia than it otherwise would

03:30:59.440 --> 03:31:08.000
[Guest 2]: have been. So I'm saying kick that problem down the road. It's not generally recommended that you

03:31:08.000 --> 03:31:13.440
[Guest 2]: do that, but kick that down the road, sort out the climate change issue, and then figure out

03:31:13.440 --> 03:31:18.560
[Guest 2]: what you're going to do about that. That's one. And secondly, there is promise with more small

03:31:18.560 --> 03:31:26.720
[Guest 2]: scale nuclear. There's some promise with the holy grail of fusion. So we don't know how that will

03:31:26.720 --> 03:31:33.840
[Guest 2]: go. But I think that we need to seriously consider it because the alternative is a little hard to

03:31:33.840 --> 03:31:39.120
[Amit Varma]: contemplate, which is that we'll go up in smoke. And I just like to quote from that op-ed since

03:31:39.120 --> 03:31:44.320
[Amit Varma]: you mentioned nuclear waste, where Pinker and his co-writers write, quote, nuclear waste is compact.

03:31:44.320 --> 03:31:48.960
[Amit Varma]: America's total from 60 years would fit in a Walmart and is safely stored in concrete

03:31:48.960 --> 03:31:53.840
[Amit Varma]: casts and pools becoming less radioactive over time. After we have solved the more pressing

03:31:53.840 --> 03:31:58.080
[Amit Varma]: challenge of climate change, we can either burn the waste as fuel in new types of reactors or

03:31:58.080 --> 03:32:02.400
[Amit Varma]: buried deep underground. It's a far easier environmental challenge than the world's

03:32:02.400 --> 03:32:08.960
[Amit Varma]: enormous coal waste routinely dumped near poor communities and often laden with toxic arsenic,

03:32:08.960 --> 03:32:13.600
[Amit Varma]: mercury and lead that can last forever. And the forever is an itals, which you know,

03:32:13.600 --> 03:32:16.720
[Amit Varma]: NYT doesn't normally, I don't think newspapers use itals.

03:32:17.520 --> 03:32:21.840
[Guest 1]: I want to worry about the behavior of real world states and political systems,

03:32:21.840 --> 03:32:29.040
[Guest 1]: and about the bureaucratic competence that set the stage for Chernobyl. So I have the highest

03:32:29.040 --> 03:32:36.480
[Guest 1]: respect for the engineering capabilities and the state capacity in Japan. Okay, and yet,

03:32:36.480 --> 03:32:40.400
[Guest 1]: A, we got Fukushima, which was just a horrendous disaster.

03:32:40.400 --> 03:32:44.320
[Amit Varma]: The tsunami killed people. The birds say the Fukushima leak didn't.

03:32:44.320 --> 03:32:51.040
[Guest 1]: But then B, political systems respond to these things in ways that are less than rational. For

03:32:51.040 --> 03:32:56.480
[Guest 1]: example, apparently, nuclear reactors were closed down all across Japan at the time of the Fukushima

03:32:56.480 --> 03:33:01.760
[Guest 1]: crisis because people just panicked. And hundreds of people died of cold in that period because

03:33:01.760 --> 03:33:08.720
[Guest 1]: energy supplies to households were cut off. Okay, so there is nuclear energy as an engineering

03:33:08.720 --> 03:33:14.400
[Guest 1]: construct. And then there is the bureaucratic incompetence about how it is dealt with. And then

03:33:14.400 --> 03:33:22.720
[Guest 1]: there is the knee jerk and extreme reactions of political systems to extreme threats. And under

03:33:22.720 --> 03:33:29.280
[Guest 1]: the third category, I would put the decision by Germany to mothball the nuclear industry in

03:33:29.280 --> 03:33:36.400
[Guest 1]: response to Fukushima. Under the third, I would put the less than sophisticated responses of large

03:33:36.400 --> 03:33:43.440
[Guest 1]: numbers of countries to a threat like COVID-19. Governments, political systems don't fare well

03:33:43.440 --> 03:33:51.120
[Guest 1]: when faced with risk and the concerns around nuclear energy lend themselves to panic and

03:33:51.120 --> 03:33:56.000
[Guest 1]: the entire posturing of a political system that, oh, we are so great, we are on top of this.

03:33:56.000 --> 03:34:02.240
[Guest 1]: And when you bring this kind of worldview to a place like India, I would worry even more

03:34:02.800 --> 03:34:09.120
[Guest 1]: that Chernobyl bureaucratic incompetence, you know, it could happen here. Political system

03:34:09.120 --> 03:34:14.560
[Guest 1]: overreacting, you know, it could happen here. So while I love and admire nuclear technology,

03:34:14.560 --> 03:34:20.080
[Guest 1]: and there is a lot to be said for technological change, I'm a little nervous about how this could

03:34:20.080 --> 03:34:26.000
[Amit Varma]: play out here. The thought just comes to mind that even if you solve for climate change, how will you

03:34:26.000 --> 03:34:32.320
[Amit Varma]: solve for human idiocy? Maybe climate change is solving for human idiocy. Okay, a couple of final

03:34:32.320 --> 03:34:37.280
[Amit Varma]: questions. My penultimate question is this, that you've come out with a paper. It's a great paper,

03:34:37.280 --> 03:34:40.640
[Amit Varma]: everyone should read it. And obviously, the download link and everything will be in the show

03:34:40.640 --> 03:34:44.960
[Amit Varma]: notes. Two part question, a two part penultimate question. So this is not the end, there is more

03:34:44.960 --> 03:34:50.640
[Amit Varma]: after this. And the two part penultimate question is this, that one, where do you plan to now go

03:34:50.640 --> 03:34:56.960
[Amit Varma]: with this ideas and this sort of body of thought that you guys are building? And two, if any of my

03:34:56.960 --> 03:35:00.800
